{"title_page": "Furigana", "text_new": "{{Short description|Japanese style of ruby text}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Japanese writing}}\n[[File:Seimikaisou.jpg|thumb|A des&shy;crip&shy;tion of a [[Alessandro Volta|Volta]] bat&shy;tery in ''In&shy;tro&shy;duc&shy;tion to Chem&shy;istry'' (''Seimi Kais\u014d'') by [[Udagawa Y\u014dan]], published in 1840.]]\n{{nihongo|'''Furigana'''|[[wikt:\u632f\u308a\u4eee\u540d|\u632f\u308a\u4eee\u540d]], \u3075\u308a\u304c\u306a||{{IPA-ja|\u0278\u026f\u027eiga\ua71cna}} <small>or</small> {{IPA-ja|\u0278\u026f\u027eigana|}}}} is a [[Japanese language|Japanese]] reading aid, consisting of smaller [[kana]] or syllabic characters, printed next to a [[kanji]] ([[Ideogram|ideographic]] character) or other character to indicate its [[pronunciation]]. It is one type of [[ruby character|ruby text]]. Furigana is also known as {{nihongo|'''yomigana'''|\u8aad\u307f\u4eee\u540d}} or {{nihongo|'''rubi'''|[[wikt:\u30eb\u30d3|\u30eb\u30d3]]||{{IPA-ja|\u027e\u026f\ua71cbi|}}}} in Japanese. In modern Japanese, it is mostly used to gloss rare kanji, to clarify rare, nonstandard or ambiguous kanji readings, or in children's or learners' materials. Before the post-World War II [[Japanese script reform|script reforms]], it was more widespread.<ref name=\"Sampson1990\">{{cite book|author=Geoffrey Sampson|title=Writing Systems: A Linguistic Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tVcdNRvwoDkC&pg=PA190|date=1990|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-1756-4|page=190}}</ref>\n\nFurigana is most often written in [[hiragana]], though [[katakana]], Roman alphabet letters or other kanji can also be used in certain special cases. In vertical text, ''[[Horizontal and vertical writing in East Asian scripts|tategaki]]'', the furigana is placed to the right of the line of text; in horizontal text, ''[[Horizontal and vertical writing in East Asian scripts|yokogaki]]'', it is placed above the line of text, as illustrated below.\n\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-3}}\n{| \n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" | {{lang|ja|\u6f22}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em\" |{{lang|ja|\u304b<br>\u3093}}\n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" | {{lang|ja|\u5b57}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em\" |{{lang|ja|\u3058}}\n|}\n{{col-3|align=center|valign=middle}}\nor\n{{col-3}}\n{| \n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em; text-align:center\" | {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3093}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em; text-align:center\" |{{lang|ja|\u3058}}\n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" | {{lang|ja|\u6f22}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" |{{lang|ja|\u5b57}}\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\nThese examples spell the word ''kanji'', which is made up of two kanji characters: {{lang|ja|\u6f22}} (''kan'', written in hiragana as {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3093}}) and {{lang|ja|\u5b57}} (''ji'', written in hiragana as {{lang|ja|\u3058}}).\n\n==Appearance==\nFurigana may be added by character, in which case the furigana character(s) that correspond to a kanji are centered over that kanji; or by word or phrase, in which case the entire furigana text is centered over several kanji characters, even if the kanji do not represent equal shares of the kana needed to write them. The latter method is more common, especially since some words in Japanese have unique pronunciations (''[[jukujikun]]'') that are not related to readings of any of the characters the word is written with.\n\nFurigana fonts are generally sized so that two kana characters fit naturally over one kanji; when more kana are required, this is resolved either by adjusting the furigana by using a [[condensed font]] (narrowing the kana), or by adjusting the kanji by [[intercharacter spacing]] (adding spaces around the kanji). In case an isolated kanji character has a long reading\u2014for example {{lang|ja|\u301c\u306b\u643a\u308f\u308b}} (where {{lang|ja|\u643a}} reads {{lang|ja|\u305f\u305a\u3055}}, ''tazusa'')\u2014the furigana may instead spill over into the space next to the neighboring kana characters, without condensing or changing spacing. Three-kana readings are not uncommon, particularly due to ''[[y\u014don]]'' with a long vowel, such as {{Nihongo||\u308a\u3087\u3046|ry\u014d}}; five kana are required for {{Nihongo||\u5fd7\u3001\u3053\u3053\u308d\u3056\u3057|kokorozashi}} and six for {{Nihongo||\u627f\u308b\u3001\u3046\u3051\u305f\u307e\u308f\u308b|uketamawaru}}, the longest of any character in the [[Joyo kanji]]. Very long readings also occur for certain kanji or symbols which have a ''[[gairaigo]]'' reading; the word \"centimeter\" is generally written as \"cm\" (with two half-width characters, so occupying one space) and has the seven-kana reading {{lang|ja|\u30bb\u30f3\u30c1\u30e1\u30fc\u30c8\u30eb}} (''senchim\u0113toru'') (it can also be written as the kanji {{lang|ja|\u7cce}}, though this is very rare); another common example is \"%\" (the percent sign), which has the five kana reading {{lang|ja|\u30d1\u30fc\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8}} (''p\u0101sento''). These cause severe spacing problems due to length and these words being used as units (hence closely associated with the preceding figure).\n\nWhen it is necessary to distinguish between native Japanese ''[[Kanji#Kun'yomi (Japanese reading)|kun'yomi]]'' and [[Chinese language|Chinese]]-derived ''[[Kanji#On'yomi (Chinese reading)|on'yomi]]'' pronunciations, for example in [[Japanese dictionary|kanji dictionaries]], the Japanese pronunciations are written in [[hiragana]], and the Chinese pronunciations are written in [[katakana]]. However, this distinction is really only important in dictionaries and other reference works. In ordinary prose, the script chosen will usually be [[hiragana]]. The one general exception to this is ''modern'' Chinese place names, personal names, and (occasionally) food names\u2014these will often be written with kanji, and katakana used for the furigana; in more casual writing these are simply written in katakana, as borrowed words. Occasionally this style is also used for loanwords from other languages (especially English). For example, the kanji {{lang|ja|\u4e00\u89d2\u7363}} (literally \"one horn beast\") might be glossed with katakana {{lang|ja|\u30e6\u30cb\u30b3\u30fc\u30f3}}, ''yunik\u014dn'', to show the pronunciation of the loanword \"unicorn\", which is unrelated to the normal reading of the kanji. Generally, though, such loanwords are just written in straight katakana.\n\nThe distinction between regular kana and the smaller character forms ([[y\u014don]] and [[sokuon]]), which are used in regular orthography to mark such things as [[gemination]] and [[Palatalization (phonetics)|palatalization]], is often not made in furigana: for example, the usual [[hiragana]] spelling of the word {{lang|ja|\u5374\u4e0b}} (''kyakka'') is {{lang|ja|\u304d\u3083\u3063\u304b}}, but in furigana it might be written {{lang|ja|\u304d\u3084\u3064\u304b}}. This was especially common in old-fashioned [[printing press|movable type]] printing when smaller fonts were not available. Nowadays, with computer-based printing systems, this occurs less frequently.\n\n==Alignment rules in word processing or typesetting==\n{{Expand section|date=December 2018}}\nVarious [[Word processor|word processing]] or [[typesetting]] [[software]] programs, such as [[Microsoft Word]], [[Adobe InDesign]], [[Adobe InCopy]], etc. have features for adding [[Ruby character|ruby text]], especially Japanese furigana. Among formatting features are different rules for aligning the kana over or to the right of the base text, usually either when the base text string is longer than the furigana string or vice-versa. Extra spaces may be needed depending on the size of the shorter string (either the ruby string or the base string) relatively to the longer one.\n* [[Typographic alignment|Centered, left/top or right/bottom]]: No spaces are added in between the characters. The shorter string is aligned to the center (\u4e2d\u4ed8\u304d\u30eb\u30d3 ''nakatsuki rubi'')<ref name=align>{{cite web|url=https://www.w3.org/TR/2012/NOTE-jlreq-20120403/#ruby_and_emphasis_dots|title=Requirements for Japanese Text Layout|date=April 2012|website=www.w3.org|publisher=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]}}</ref>, the left/top (\u80a9\u4ed8\u304d\u30eb\u30d3 ''katatsuki rubi'')<ref name=align /> or the right/bottom of the longer string.\n* 1-2-1 ([[Japanese Industrial Standards|JIS]]): Spaces are added at the start of and the end of the shorter string, and in between its component characters, so that the spaces in between are twice as wide or tall as the spaces at the start and at the end. Space width or height is calculated based on the width or height of the square bounding box of a glyph (Japanese [[typeface]]s are generally [[Monospaced font|monospaced]]). The strings are still, in essence, aligned to the center of each other, rather than to the left/top or right/bottom.\n* 0-1-0: Equal spaces are added, similarly to the 1-2-1 rule, in between the component characters of the shorter string, but not its start or end.\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:JR Namba entrance.jpg|thumb|300px|On this sign, furigana indicate the pronunciation of the Latin letters \"[[Japan Railways Group|JR]]\" and the [[kanji]] for \"[[JR Namba Station|Namba]]\", though in this case the kana are not directly above the kanji, or even above at all.]]\nFurigana are most commonly used in works for children, who may not have sufficiently advanced reading skills to recognize the kanji, but can understand the word when written phonetically in [[hiragana]]. Because children learn hiragana before [[katakana]], in books for very young children, there are hiragana furigana next to the katakana characters. It is common to use furigana on all kanji characters in works for young children. This is called {{nihongo|''s\u014drubi''|[[wikt:\u7dcf\u30eb\u30d3|\u7dcf\u30eb\u30d3]]}} in Japanese.\n\nNumeric characters used for counting (e.g. {{lang|ja|\u4e8c{{ruby-ja|\u672c|\u307b\u3093}}/\uff12{{ruby-ja|\u672c|\u307b\u3093}}}} ''ni-hon'' \"two long things\"; {{lang|ja|\uff12\u3064\u3081}} ''futatsume'' \"second\"; {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u7b2c|\u3060\u3044}}\u4e8c{{ruby-ja|\u5dfb|\u304b\u3093}}/{{ruby-ja|\u7b2c|\u3060\u3044}}\uff12{{ruby-ja|\u5dfb|\u304b\u3093}}}} ''dai-ni kan'' \"book 2\"; {{lang|ja|\uff12\u30da\u30fc\u30b8}} ''ni-p\u0113ji'' \"page 2\"; etc.) are usually not tagged with furigana. Exceptions include a few cases such as \u4e00\u4eba/\uff11\u4eba ''hitori'' \"one person\" and \u4e8c\u4eba/\uff12\u4eba ''futari'' \"two people\", which may be tagged with separate kana for each character ({{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00|\u3072\u3068}}{{ruby-ja|\u4eba|\u308a}}}}/{{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\uff11|\u3072\u3068}}{{ruby-ja|\u4eba|\u308a}}}}), or non-separated kana for the whole word ({{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00\u4eba|\u3072\u3068\u308a}}}}/{{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\uff11\u4eba|\u3072\u3068\u308a}}}}), depending on the style of the publisher in question. Numeric words in established compounds (e.g. {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00|\u3044\u3063}}{{ruby-ja|\u6b69|\u307d}}}} ''ippo'' \"step\"; {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00|\u3072\u3068}}{{ruby-ja|\u76ee|\u3081}}}} ''hitome'' \"sight; attention\"), however, are generally tagged with furigana.\n\nMany [[Children's anime and manga|children's]], [[sh\u014dnen]] and [[sh\u014djo manga]] use furigana (however, rarely on [[Japanese numerals|numerals]]). Sh\u014dnen and sh\u014djo manga tend to have furigana for all non-numeric characters, while children's manga, such as ''[[Doraemon]]'', may also ignore furigana on elementary-grade kanji. [[Seinen]] and [[josei manga]] ignores furigana most of the time, even on the names of the characters if they're common names. There are also books with a phonetic guide (mainly in [[hiragana]] but sometimes in [[r\u014dmaji]]) for Japanese learners, which may be bilingual or Japanese only. These are popular with foreigners wishing to master Japanese faster and enjoy reading Japanese short stories, novels or articles.\n\nDue to the small type used for furigana, for maximum readability, some manga publishers may use regular kana instead of small kana. For example, \u306f\u3063\u3057\u3093 ''hasshin'' may be spelled \u306f\u3064\u3057\u3093 *''hatsushin'' instead.\n\nSome websites and tools exist which provide a phonetic guide for Japanese web pages (in hiragana, r\u014dmaji or [[Cyrillization of Japanese|kiriji]]); these are popular with both Japanese children and foreign Japanese learners.\n\nIn works aimed at adult Japanese speakers, furigana may be used on a word written in uncommon kanji; in the mass media, they are generally used on words containing non-[[J\u014dy\u014d kanji]].\n\nFurigana commonly appear alongside kanji names and their romanizations on signs for railway stations, even if the pronunciation of the kanji is commonly known. Furigana also appear often on maps to show the pronunciation of unusual place names.\n\nBefore the war, youths might arguably have been almost illiterate if not for furigana.<ref>{{cite book|last=Defrancis|first=John|title=The Chinese Language: Fact and Fantasy|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|location=Honolulu|page=216|date=1986}}</ref>\n\n===Names===\n[[Japanese name]]s are usually written in [[kanji]]. Because there are many possible readings for kanji names, including special name-only readings called [[nanori]], furigana are often used to give the readings of names. On Japanese official forms, where the name is to be written, there is  always an adjacent column for the name to be written in furigana. Usually katakana is preferred.\n\nFurigana may also be used for foreign names written in kanji. Chinese and Korean names are the most common examples: Chinese names are usually pronounced with Japanese readings and the pronunciation written in hiragana, while Korean names are usually pronounced with Korean readings and the pronunciation written in katakana. Furigana may also be necessary in the rare case where names are transliterated into kanji from other languages (e.g. soccer star [[Ruy Ramos]] and politician [[Marutei Tsurunen]].)\n\n===Language learning===\nKanji and kanji compounds are often presented with furigana in Japanese language textbooks for non-native speakers.\n\nFurigana are also often used in foreign language textbooks for Japanese learners to indicate pronunciation. The words are written in the original foreign script, such as [[hangul]] for [[Korean language|Korean]], and furigana is used to indicate the pronunciation. According to Ministry of Education guidelines, and the opinions of educators, the use of Japanese furigana should be avoided in English teaching due to the differences in pronunciation between English and Japanese. For instance, the word \"birthdate\" might be glossed in furigana as {{lang|ja|\u30d0\u30fc\u30b9\u30c7\u30a4\u30c8}} (''b\u0101sudeito''), which corresponds to an imperfect pronunciation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gifu-net.ed.jp/kyoka/eigo/CommunicativeEnglish/05-11cSpeaking.htm |title=Speaking/Pronunciation |author=Lena Ginsburg |date=July 2005|publisher=Gifu Prefectural Board of Education |accessdate=3 May 2012|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://genkienglish.net/katakana.htm |title=No Katakana!! |author=Richard Graham|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Punning and double meaning===\nSome writers use furigana to represent slang pronunciations, particularly those that would become hard to understand without the kanji to provide their meaning.\n\nAnother use is to write the kanji for something which had been previously referenced, but write furigana for {{transl|ja|''sore''}} ({{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u305d\u308c|\u305d\u308c]]}}) or {{transl|ja|''are''}} ({{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3042\u308c|\u3042\u308c]]}}), meaning \"that\". This means that the actual word used was \"that\", but the kanji clarify for the reader what \"that\" refers to. Another way to use it is to tag {{transl|ja|''koko''}} ({{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3053\u3053|\u3053\u3053]]}}) onto words or names for places, to convey something along the line of, for example, \"here (at this hospital)\" ({{ruby-ja|\u75c5\u9662|\u3053\u3053}}) or \"here (in [[Los Angeles|LA]])\" ({{ruby-ja|LA|\u3053\u3053}}).\n\nFurigana unrelated to the kanji they are assigned to are quite often used to convey certain effects, rather than to denote a phonetic guide, especially in manga, anime and games<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.japanesewithanime.com/2016/11/furigana-meaning.html|title=Furigana - What Is It?|work=Japanese with Anime|access-date=2017-08-28|language=en-US}}</ref> (card games, board games and video games all included). This usage is known as ''gikun'' (see also [[Kanji#Special readings]]). The specific types of effects vary: furigana could be used to visually reinforce complex ideas without having to use long expressions; to annotate strange, foreign, rarely seen text; to use more artistic or more explanatory spellings for regular words (see [[Kanji#Gikun]]); or simply for shorthand for base text abbreviation, thanks to the small type of furigana. For example, the word {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u60aa\u5922|{{ruby-ja|\u60aa|\u3057\u3093}}{{ruby-ja|\u5922|\u3058\u3064}}]]}} \"nightmare\" may be assigned with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u771f\u5b9f|\u3057\u3093\u3058\u3064]]}} ''shinjitsu'' \"truth\" rather than its true reading, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3042\u304f\u3080|\u3042\u304f\u3080]]}} ''akumu'', to convey the meaning of \"nightmarish truth\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Aoyama|first=Gosho|author-link=Gosho Aoyama|date=March 15, 2007|title=Magic Kaito|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30fb\u30ca\u30a4\u30c8\u306e{{ruby-ja|\u5dfb|\u307e\u304d}}\u3010{{ruby-ja|\u5f8c|\u3053\u3046}}{{ruby-ja|\u7de8|\u3078\u3093}}\u3011</span>|trans-chapter=Dark Knight [Last Chapter]|volume=4|title-link=Magic Kaito}}</ref> Some authors may even use furigana that means the opposite of what the base text does to reinforce an effect, such as the complicated relationship between characters. For example, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u89aa\u53cb|{{ruby-ja|\u89aa\u53cb|\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb}}]]}} ''shin'y\u016b'' \"close friend\" may be tagged with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb|\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb]]}} ''raibaru'' \"rival\", to mean \"you're my rival, but also my friend\";<ref>{{cite book|last=Sorachi|first=Hideaki|author-link=Hideaki Sorachi|date=February 9, 2008|title=Gintama|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\u7b2c|\u3060\u3044}}\u767e\u4e5d\u5341\u4e09{{ruby-ja|\u8a13|\u304f\u3093}}\u3000\u300e\u30d7\u30ea\u30ba\u30f3\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30af\u3000\u30b7\u30fc\u30ba\u30f3{{ruby-ja|\uff12|\u30c4\u30fc}}\u300f\u3063\u3066\u30a2\u30ec\u3000\u3082\u3046\u30d7\u30ea\u30ba\u30f3\u3092\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30af\u3057\u3066\u308b\u304b\u3089\u30d7\u30ea\u30ba\u30f3\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30af\u3058\u3083\u306a\u304f\u306d\uff1f</span>|trans-chapter=Lesson 193: Is There Even a Prison Break in \u201cPrison Break Season 2\u201d If You\u2019ve Already Broken out of Prison in Season 1?|volume=22|title-link=Gintama}}</ref> or conversely, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u597d\u6575\u624b|{{ruby-ja|\u597d\u6575\u624b|\u3068\u3082}}]]}} ''k\u014dtekishu'' \"eternal rival\" may be tagged with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u53cb|\u3068\u3082]]}} ''tomo'' \"friend\".<ref>{{cite book|date=February 26, 2004|publisher=[[Konami]]|title=<span lang=\"ja\">\u30a2\u30d3\u30b9\u30fb\u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0</span>|trans-title=Abyss Rising|url=https://www.db.yugioh-card.com/yugiohdb/card_search.action?ope=2&cid=10297&request_locale=ja|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\u597d\u6575\u624b|\u3068\u3082}}\u306e{{ruby-ja|\u8a18|\u304d}}{{ruby-ja|\u61b6|\u304a\u304f}}</span>|trans-chapter=Memory of a Frenemy}}</ref> Some manga make use of the furigana renditions of foreign words (especially obscure ones) as the intended reading of a term, and the more familiar kanji for the meaning of such a term. For example, {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u9ed2\u30fb\u9b54\u30fb\u5c0e|\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30de\u30b8\u30c3\u30af}}}} may be assigned with {{lang|ja|\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30de\u30b8\u30c3\u30af}} ''burakku majikku'', the [[Transcription into Japanese|rendition]] of the English \"black magic\", to convey a foreign, exotic feel;<ref>{{cite book|date=February 26, 2004|publisher=[[Konami]]|title=<span lang=\"ja\">\u30d5\u30a1\u30e9\u30aa\u306e\u907a\u7523</span>|trans-title=Pharaoh's Legacy|url=https://www.db.yugioh-card.com/yugiohdb/card_search.action?ope=2&cid=6057&request_locale=ja|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\u9ed2\u30fb\u9b54\u30fb\u5c0e|\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30de\u30b8\u30c3\u30af}}</span>|trans-chapter=Black Magic}}</ref> {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|[[wikt:\u99c5|\u99c5]]|\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}}} with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3]]}} ''sut\u0113shon'' \"station\";<ref>{{cite book|last=Amano|first=Kozue|author-link=Kozue Amano|date=April 27, 2002|title=Aqua|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|Navigation|\u30ca\u30d3\u30b2\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}06\u3000{{ruby-ja|\u59cb|\u306f\u3058}}\u3081\u3066\u306e\u304a{{ruby-ja|\u5ba2|\u304d\u3083\u304f}}{{ruby-ja|\u69d8|\u3055\u307e}}</span>|trans-chapter=Navigation 06: A First-Time Customer|volume=2|title-link=Aria (manga)}}</ref> {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|[[wikt:\u65b0\u5a5a\u65c5\u884c|\u65b0\u5a5a\u65c5\u884c]]|\u30cf\u30cb\u30fc\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3}}}} with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30cf\u30cb\u30fc\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3|\u30cf\u30cb\u30fc\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3]]}} ''han\u012bm\u016bn'' \"honeymoon\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Yamazaki|first=Kore|date=April 10, 2014|title=The Ancient Magus' Bride|chapter=Composition 2: One today is worth two tomorrows.|volume=1|title-link=The Ancient Magus' Bride}}</ref> This is sometimes done conversely, for example, by using {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30ad\u30c3\u30b9|\u30ad\u30c3\u30b9]]}} ''kissu'' \"kiss\", the more familiar term, as furigana to convey meaning, and {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u30d9\u30fc\u30bc|\u30ad\u30c3\u30b9}}}} ''b\u0113ze'' \"{{lang|fr|baiser}}\", the exotic term, as base text.<ref>{{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Rumiko|author-link=Rumiko Takahashi|date=August 15, 1991|title=Ranma \u00bd|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\uff30\uff21\uff32\uff34|\u30d1\u30fc\u30c8}}.\uff19\u3000{{ruby-ja|\u602a|\u304b\u3044}}{{ruby-ja|\u5947|\u304d}}\uff01\u304a{{ruby-ja|\u4e0a|\u3058\u3087\u3046}}{{ruby-ja|\u54c1|\u3072\u3093}}{{ruby-ja|\u9928|\u3084\u304b\u305f}}</span>|trans-chapter=Part 9: Horror! Folks of Class|volume=16|title-link=Ranma \u00bd}}</ref> For shorthand purposes, abbreviations such as {{ruby-ja|[[Interpol|ICPO]]|\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30dd\u30fc\u30eb}} may be used to make the regular kana spelling that is too long smaller type.\n\nIn [[karaoke]] it is extremely common for furigana to be placed on the song lyrics. The song lyrics are often written in kanji pronounced quite differently from the furigana. The furigana version is used for pronunciation.\n\nAlso, because the kanji represent meaning while the furigana represent sound, one can combine the two to create [[pun]]s or indicate meanings of foreign words. One might write the kanji for \"blue\", but use katakana to write the pronunciation of the English word \"blue\"; this may be done, for example, in Japanese subtitles on foreign films, where it can help associate the written Japanese with the sounds actually being spoken by the actors, or it may be used in a translation of a work of fiction to enable the translator to preserve the original sound of a proper name (such as \"Firebolt\" in the [[Harry Potter]] series) in furigana, while simultaneously indicating its meaning with kanji. A similar practice is used in native fiction to clarify extended meanings. For example, in a work of science fiction, some astronaut could use the word {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3075\u308b\u3055\u3068|\u3075\u308b\u3055\u3068]]}}, ''furusato'', meaning \"my hometown\", when referring to planet Earth. To clarify that for the reader, the word ''furusato'' (hometown) might be written in hiragana over the kanji for ''chikyuu'' (Earth).\n\n==Other Japanese reading aids==\n===Okurigana===\n{{Main|Okurigana}}\nOkurigana are kana that appear inline at normal size following kanji stems, typically to complete and to inflect adjectives and verbs. In this use they may also help to disambiguate kanji with multiple readings; for example, {{lang|ja|\u4e0a\u304c\u308b}} ({{lang|ja|\u3042\u304c\u308b}}, ''agaru'') vs. {{lang|ja|\u4e0a\u308b}} ({{lang|ja|\u306e\u307c\u308b}}, ''noboru''). Unlike furigana, the use of okurigana is a mandatory part of the written language.\n\n===Kunten===\n\nIn the written style known as ''[[kanbun]]'', which is the Japanese approximation of [[Classical Chinese]], small marks called ''[[kunten]]'' are sometimes added as reading aids. Unlike furigana, which indicate pronunciation, ''kunten'' indicate Japanese grammatical structures absent from the ''kanbun'', as well as showing how words should be reordered to fit Japanese sentence structure.\n\n===Furikanji===\nFurigana are sometimes also used to indicate meaning, rather than pronunciation. Over the foreign text, smaller sized Japanese words, in kana or kanji, corresponding to the ''meaning'' of the foreign words, effectively translate it in place. While rare now, some late 19th\u2013early 20th century authors used kanji as furigana for [[loanword]]s written in katakana. This usage is called {{nihongo|''furikanji''|\u632f\u308a\u6f22\u5b57}} in Japanese, since ''furi'''gana''''' implies the use of '''''[[kana]]'''''. For example, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30ea\u30ea\u30c3\u30af|{{ruby-ja|\u30ea\u30ea\u30c3\u30af|\u6b4c\u8a5e}}]]}} ''ririkku'' \"lyric\" may be tagged with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u6b4c\u8a5e|\u6b4c\u8a5e]]}} ''kashi'' \"lyrics\" for clarification rather than for phonetic guidance.<ref>{{cite book|author=TAGRO|date=July 23, 2008|title=Hen Semi|chapter=#06|volume=1|title-link=Hen Semi}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Okurigana]]\n*[[Ruby character]]\n*[[Zhuyin]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n===Bibliography===\n* ''Mangajin's Basic Japanese Through Comics [Part I]'' New York: Weatherhill, 1998: 48\u201349\n* J Paul Warnick, Review of ''Nihon o Hanasoo'' in ''The Journal of the Association of Teachers of Japanese'', Vol. 32, No. 2 (Oct., 1998), pp.&nbsp;80\u201383\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070704184818/http://yomoyomo.jp/ Add Ruby automatically for Japanese Web site]\u2014Multi-language phonetic reading site that can add phonetic reading to any site or texts in five different alphabets, hiragana, katakana, Roman, hangul, Devanagari, and Cyrillic letters for Japanese.\n* [http://www.furiganizer.com The Furiganizer] is a convenient online reading aid for all kinds of Japanese text. It automatically adds Furigana, offers easy access to the [[EDICT]] dictionary, and learns interactively which kanji the user already knows. Furiganized results can be printed or exported to Microsoft Word.\n\n{{Japanese language}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese writing system terms]]\n[[Category:Kana]]\n[[Category:Ruby characters]]\n[[Category:Japanese writing system]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Japanese style of ruby text}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n{{Japanese writing}}\n[[File:Seimikaisou.jpg|thumb|A des&shy;crip&shy;tion of a [[Alessandro Volta|Volta]] bat&shy;tery in ''In&shy;tro&shy;duc&shy;tion to Chem&shy;istry'' (''Seimi Kais\u014d'') by [[Udagawa Y\u014dan]], published in 1840.]]\n{{nihongo|'''Furigana'''|[[wikt:\u632f\u308a\u4eee\u540d|\u632f\u308a\u4eee\u540d]], \u3075\u308a\u304c\u306a||{{IPA-ja|\u0278\u026f\u027eiga\ua71cna}} <small>or</small> {{IPA-ja|\u0278\u026f\u027eigana|}}}} is a [[Japanese language|Japanese]] reading aid, consisting of smaller [[kana]] or syllabic characters, printed next to a [[kanji]] ([[Ideogram|ideographic]] character) or other character to indicate its [[pronunciation]]. It is one type of [[ruby character|ruby text]]. Furigana is also known as {{nihongo|'''yomigana'''|\u8aad\u307f\u4eee\u540d}} or {{nihongo|'''rubi'''|[[wikt:\u30eb\u30d3|\u30eb\u30d3]]||{{IPA-ja|\u027e\u026f\ua71cbi|}}}} in Japanese. In modern Japanese, it is mostly used to gloss rare kanji, to clarify rare, nonstandard or ambiguous kanji readings, or in children's or learners' materials. Before the post-World War II [[Japanese script reform|script reforms]], it was more widespread.<ref name=\"Sampson1990\">{{cite book|author=Geoffrey Sampson|title=Writing Systems: A Linguistic Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tVcdNRvwoDkC&pg=PA190|date=1990|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-1756-4|page=190}}</ref>\n\nFurigana is most often written in [[hiragana]], though [[katakana]], Roman alphabet letters or other kanji can also be used in certain special cases. In vertical text, ''[[Horizontal and vertical writing in East Asian scripts|tategaki]]'', the furigana is placed to the right of the line of text; in horizontal text, ''[[Horizontal and vertical writing in East Asian scripts|yokogaki]]'', it is placed above the line of text, as illustrated below.\n\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-3}}\n{| \n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" | {{lang|ja|\u6f22}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em\" |{{lang|ja|\u304b<br>\u3093}}\n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" | {{lang|ja|\u5b57}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em\" |{{lang|ja|\u3058}}\n|}\n{{col-3|align=center|valign=middle}}\nor\n{{col-3}}\n{| \n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em; text-align:center\" | {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3093}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:0.8em; text-align:center\" |{{lang|ja|\u3058}}\n|-\n| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" | {{lang|ja|\u6f22}}|| style=\"line-height:1em; font-size:2em\" |{{lang|ja|\u5b57}}\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\nThese examples spell the word ''kanji'', which is made up of two kanji characters: {{lang|ja|\u6f22}} (''kan'', written in hiragana as {{lang|ja|\u304b\u3093}}) and {{lang|ja|\u5b57}} (''ji'', written in hiragana as {{lang|ja|\u3058}}).\n\n==Appearance==\nFurigana may be added by character, in which case the furigana character(s) that correspond to a kanji are centered over that kanji; or by word or phrase, in which case the entire furigana text is centered over several kanji characters, even if the kanji do not represent equal shares of the kana needed to write them. The latter method is more common, especially since some words in Japanese have unique pronunciations (''[[jukujikun]]'') that are not related to readings of any of the characters the word is written with.\n\nFurigana fonts are generally sized so that two kana characters fit naturally over one kanji; when more kana are required, this is resolved either by adjusting the furigana by using a [[condensed font]] (narrowing the kana), or by adjusting the kanji by [[intercharacter spacing]] (adding spaces around the kanji). In case an isolated kanji character has a long reading\u2014for example {{lang|ja|\u301c\u306b\u643a\u308f\u308b}} (where {{lang|ja|\u643a}} reads {{lang|ja|\u305f\u305a\u3055}}, ''tazusa'')\u2014the furigana may instead spill over into the space next to the neighboring kana characters, without condensing or changing spacing. Three-kana readings are not uncommon, particularly due to ''[[y\u014don]]'' with a long vowel, such as {{Nihongo||\u308a\u3087\u3046|ry\u014d}}; five kana are required for {{Nihongo||\u5fd7\u3001\u3053\u3053\u308d\u3056\u3057|kokorozashi}} and six for {{Nihongo||\u627f\u308b\u3001\u3046\u3051\u305f\u307e\u308f\u308b|uketamawaru}}, the longest of any character in the [[Joyo kanji]]. Very long readings also occur for certain kanji or symbols which have a ''[[gairaigo]]'' reading; the word \"centimeter\" is generally written as \"cm\" (with two half-width characters, so occupying one space) and has the seven-kana reading {{lang|ja|\u30bb\u30f3\u30c1\u30e1\u30fc\u30c8\u30eb}} (''senchim\u0113toru'') (it can also be written as the kanji {{lang|ja|\u7cce}}, though this is very rare); another common example is \"%\" (the percent sign), which has the five kana reading {{lang|ja|\u30d1\u30fc\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8}} (''p\u0101sento''). These cause severe spacing problems due to length and these words being used as units (hence closely associated with the preceding figure).\n\nWhen it is necessary to distinguish between native Japanese ''[[Kanji#Kun'yomi (Japanese reading)|kun'yomi]]'' and [[Chinese language|Chinese]]-derived ''[[Kanji#On'yomi (Chinese reading)|on'yomi]]'' pronunciations, for example in [[Japanese dictionary|kanji dictionaries]], the Japanese pronunciations are written in [[hiragana]], and the Chinese pronunciations are written in [[katakana]]. However, this distinction is really only important in dictionaries and other reference works. In ordinary prose, the script chosen will usually be [[hiragana]]. The one general exception to this is ''modern'' Chinese place names, personal names, and (occasionally) food names\u2014these will often be written with kanji, and katakana used for the furigana; in more casual writing these are simply written in katakana, as borrowed words. Occasionally this style is also used for loanwords from other languages (especially English). For example, the kanji {{lang|ja|\u4e00\u89d2\u7363}} (literally \"one horn beast\") might be glossed with katakana {{lang|ja|\u30e6\u30cb\u30b3\u30fc\u30f3}}, ''yunik\u014dn'', to show the pronunciation of the loanword \"unicorn\", which is unrelated to the normal reading of the kanji. Generally, though, such loanwords are just written in straight katakana.\n\nThe distinction between regular kana and the smaller character forms ([[y\u014don]] and [[sokuon]]), which are used in regular orthography to mark such things as [[gemination]] and [[Palatalization (phonetics)|palatalization]], is often not made in furigana: for example, the usual [[hiragana]] spelling of the word {{lang|ja|\u5374\u4e0b}} (''kyakka'') is {{lang|ja|\u304d\u3083\u3063\u304b}}, but in furigana it might be written {{lang|ja|\u304d\u3084\u3064\u304b}}. This was especially common in old-fashioned [[printing press|movable type]] printing when smaller fonts were not available. Nowadays, with computer-based printing systems, this occurs less frequently.\n\n==Alignment rules in word processing or typesetting==\n{{Expand section|date=December 2018}}\nVarious [[Word processor|word processing]] or [[typesetting]] [[software]] programs, such as [[Microsoft Word]], [[Adobe InDesign]], [[Adobe InCopy]], etc. have features for adding [[Ruby character|ruby text]], especially Japanese furigana. Among formatting features are different rules for aligning the kana over or to the right of the base text, usually either when the base text string is longer than the furigana string or vice-versa. Extra spaces may be needed depending on the size of the shorter string (either the ruby string or the base string) relatively to the longer one.\n* [[Typographic alignment|Centered, left/top or right/bottom]]: No spaces are added in between the characters. The shorter string is aligned to the center (\u4e2d\u4ed8\u304d\u30eb\u30d3 ''nakatsuki rubi'')<ref name=align>{{cite web|url=https://www.w3.org/TR/2012/NOTE-jlreq-20120403/#ruby_and_emphasis_dots|title=Requirements for Japanese Text Layout|date=April 2012|website=www.w3.org|publisher=[[World Wide Web Consortium]]}}</ref>, the left/top (\u80a9\u4ed8\u304d\u30eb\u30d3 ''katatsuki rubi'')<ref name=align /> or the right/bottom of the longer string.\n* 1-2-1 ([[Japanese Industrial Standards|JIS]]): Spaces are added at the start of and the end of the shorter string, and in between its component characters, so that the spaces in between are twice as wide or tall as the spaces at the start and at the end. Space width or height is calculated based on the width or height of the square bounding box of a glyph (Japanese [[typeface]]s are generally [[Monospaced font|monospaced]]). The strings are still, in essence, aligned to the center of each other, rather than to the left/top or right/bottom.\n* 0-1-0: Equal spaces are added, similarly to the 1-2-1 rule, in between the component characters of the shorter string, but not its start or end.\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:JR Namba entrance.jpg|thumb|300px|On this sign, furigana indicate the pronunciation of the Latin letters \"[[Japan Railways Group|JR]]\" and the [[kanji]] for \"[[JR Namba Station|Namba]]\"]]\nFurigana are most commonly used in works for children, who may not have sufficiently advanced reading skills to recognize the kanji, but can understand the word when written phonetically in [[hiragana]]. Because children learn hiragana before [[katakana]], in books for very young children, there are hiragana furigana next to the katakana characters. It is common to use furigana on all kanji characters in works for young children. This is called {{nihongo|''s\u014drubi''|[[wikt:\u7dcf\u30eb\u30d3|\u7dcf\u30eb\u30d3]]}} in Japanese.\n\nNumeric characters used for counting (e.g. {{lang|ja|\u4e8c{{ruby-ja|\u672c|\u307b\u3093}}/\uff12{{ruby-ja|\u672c|\u307b\u3093}}}} ''ni-hon'' \"two long things\"; {{lang|ja|\uff12\u3064\u3081}} ''futatsume'' \"second\"; {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u7b2c|\u3060\u3044}}\u4e8c{{ruby-ja|\u5dfb|\u304b\u3093}}/{{ruby-ja|\u7b2c|\u3060\u3044}}\uff12{{ruby-ja|\u5dfb|\u304b\u3093}}}} ''dai-ni kan'' \"book 2\"; {{lang|ja|\uff12\u30da\u30fc\u30b8}} ''ni-p\u0113ji'' \"page 2\"; etc.) are usually not tagged with furigana. Exceptions include a few cases such as \u4e00\u4eba/\uff11\u4eba ''hitori'' \"one person\" and \u4e8c\u4eba/\uff12\u4eba ''futari'' \"two people\", which may be tagged with separate kana for each character ({{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00|\u3072\u3068}}{{ruby-ja|\u4eba|\u308a}}}}/{{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\uff11|\u3072\u3068}}{{ruby-ja|\u4eba|\u308a}}}}), or non-separated kana for the whole word ({{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00\u4eba|\u3072\u3068\u308a}}}}/{{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\uff11\u4eba|\u3072\u3068\u308a}}}}), depending on the style of the publisher in question. Numeric words in established compounds (e.g. {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00|\u3044\u3063}}{{ruby-ja|\u6b69|\u307d}}}} ''ippo'' \"step\"; {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u4e00|\u3072\u3068}}{{ruby-ja|\u76ee|\u3081}}}} ''hitome'' \"sight; attention\"), however, are generally tagged with furigana.\n\nMany [[Children's anime and manga|children's]], [[sh\u014dnen]] and [[sh\u014djo manga]] use furigana (however, rarely on [[Japanese numerals|numerals]]). Sh\u014dnen and sh\u014djo manga tend to have furigana for all non-numeric characters, while children's manga, such as ''[[Doraemon]]'', may also ignore furigana on elementary-grade kanji. [[Seinen]] and [[josei manga]] ignores furigana most of the time, even on the names of the characters if they're common names. There are also books with a phonetic guide (mainly in [[hiragana]] but sometimes in [[r\u014dmaji]]) for Japanese learners, which may be bilingual or Japanese only. These are popular with foreigners wishing to master Japanese faster and enjoy reading Japanese short stories, novels or articles.\n\nDue to the small type used for furigana, for maximum readability, some manga publishers may use regular kana instead of small kana. For example, \u306f\u3063\u3057\u3093 ''hasshin'' may be spelled \u306f\u3064\u3057\u3093 *''hatsushin'' instead.\n\nSome websites and tools exist which provide a phonetic guide for Japanese web pages (in hiragana, r\u014dmaji or [[Cyrillization of Japanese|kiriji]]); these are popular with both Japanese children and foreign Japanese learners.\n\nIn works aimed at adult Japanese speakers, furigana may be used on a word written in uncommon kanji; in the mass media, they are generally used on words containing non-[[J\u014dy\u014d kanji]].\n\nFurigana commonly appear alongside kanji names and their romanizations on signs for railway stations, even if the pronunciation of the kanji is commonly known. Furigana also appear often on maps to show the pronunciation of unusual place names.\n\nBefore the war, youths might arguably have been almost illiterate if not for furigana.<ref>{{cite book|last=Defrancis|first=John|title=The Chinese Language: Fact and Fantasy|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|location=Honolulu|page=216|date=1986}}</ref>\n\n===Names===\n[[Japanese name]]s are usually written in [[kanji]]. Because there are many possible readings for kanji names, including special name-only readings called [[nanori]], furigana are often used to give the readings of names. On Japanese official forms, where the name is to be written, there is  always an adjacent column for the name to be written in furigana. Usually katakana is preferred.\n\nFurigana may also be used for foreign names written in kanji. Chinese and Korean names are the most common examples: Chinese names are usually pronounced with Japanese readings and the pronunciation written in hiragana, while Korean names are usually pronounced with Korean readings and the pronunciation written in katakana. Furigana may also be necessary in the rare case where names are transliterated into kanji from other languages (e.g. soccer star [[Ruy Ramos]] and politician [[Marutei Tsurunen]].)\n\n===Language learning===\nKanji and kanji compounds are often presented with furigana in Japanese language textbooks for non-native speakers.\n\nFurigana are also often used in foreign language textbooks for Japanese learners to indicate pronunciation. The words are written in the original foreign script, such as [[hangul]] for [[Korean language|Korean]], and furigana is used to indicate the pronunciation. According to Ministry of Education guidelines, and the opinions of educators, the use of Japanese furigana should be avoided in English teaching due to the differences in pronunciation between English and Japanese. For instance, the word \"birthdate\" might be glossed in furigana as {{lang|ja|\u30d0\u30fc\u30b9\u30c7\u30a4\u30c8}} (''b\u0101sudeito''), which corresponds to an imperfect pronunciation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gifu-net.ed.jp/kyoka/eigo/CommunicativeEnglish/05-11cSpeaking.htm |title=Speaking/Pronunciation |author=Lena Ginsburg |date=July 2005|publisher=Gifu Prefectural Board of Education |accessdate=3 May 2012|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://genkienglish.net/katakana.htm |title=No Katakana!! |author=Richard Graham|accessdate=3 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Punning and double meaning===\nSome writers use furigana to represent slang pronunciations, particularly those that would become hard to understand without the kanji to provide their meaning.\n\nAnother use is to write the kanji for something which had been previously referenced, but write furigana for {{transl|ja|''sore''}} ({{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u305d\u308c|\u305d\u308c]]}}) or {{transl|ja|''are''}} ({{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3042\u308c|\u3042\u308c]]}}), meaning \"that\". This means that the actual word used was \"that\", but the kanji clarify for the reader what \"that\" refers to. Another way to use it is to tag {{transl|ja|''koko''}} ({{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3053\u3053|\u3053\u3053]]}}) onto words or names for places, to convey something along the line of, for example, \"here (at this hospital)\" ({{ruby-ja|\u75c5\u9662|\u3053\u3053}}) or \"here (in [[Los Angeles|LA]])\" ({{ruby-ja|LA|\u3053\u3053}}).\n\nFurigana unrelated to the kanji they are assigned to are quite often used to convey certain effects, rather than to denote a phonetic guide, especially in manga, anime and games<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.japanesewithanime.com/2016/11/furigana-meaning.html|title=Furigana - What Is It?|work=Japanese with Anime|access-date=2017-08-28|language=en-US}}</ref> (card games, board games and video games all included). This usage is known as ''gikun'' (see also [[Kanji#Special readings]]). The specific types of effects vary: furigana could be used to visually reinforce complex ideas without having to use long expressions; to annotate strange, foreign, rarely seen text; to use more artistic or more explanatory spellings for regular words (see [[Kanji#Gikun]]); or simply for shorthand for base text abbreviation, thanks to the small type of furigana. For example, the word {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u60aa\u5922|{{ruby-ja|\u60aa|\u3057\u3093}}{{ruby-ja|\u5922|\u3058\u3064}}]]}} \"nightmare\" may be assigned with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u771f\u5b9f|\u3057\u3093\u3058\u3064]]}} ''shinjitsu'' \"truth\" rather than its true reading, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3042\u304f\u3080|\u3042\u304f\u3080]]}} ''akumu'', to convey the meaning of \"nightmarish truth\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Aoyama|first=Gosho|author-link=Gosho Aoyama|date=March 15, 2007|title=Magic Kaito|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">\u30c0\u30fc\u30af\u30fb\u30ca\u30a4\u30c8\u306e{{ruby-ja|\u5dfb|\u307e\u304d}}\u3010{{ruby-ja|\u5f8c|\u3053\u3046}}{{ruby-ja|\u7de8|\u3078\u3093}}\u3011</span>|trans-chapter=Dark Knight [Last Chapter]|volume=4|title-link=Magic Kaito}}</ref> Some authors may even use furigana that means the opposite of what the base text does to reinforce an effect, such as the complicated relationship between characters. For example, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u89aa\u53cb|{{ruby-ja|\u89aa\u53cb|\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb}}]]}} ''shin'y\u016b'' \"close friend\" may be tagged with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb|\u30e9\u30a4\u30d0\u30eb]]}} ''raibaru'' \"rival\", to mean \"you're my rival, but also my friend\";<ref>{{cite book|last=Sorachi|first=Hideaki|author-link=Hideaki Sorachi|date=February 9, 2008|title=Gintama|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\u7b2c|\u3060\u3044}}\u767e\u4e5d\u5341\u4e09{{ruby-ja|\u8a13|\u304f\u3093}}\u3000\u300e\u30d7\u30ea\u30ba\u30f3\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30af\u3000\u30b7\u30fc\u30ba\u30f3{{ruby-ja|\uff12|\u30c4\u30fc}}\u300f\u3063\u3066\u30a2\u30ec\u3000\u3082\u3046\u30d7\u30ea\u30ba\u30f3\u3092\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30af\u3057\u3066\u308b\u304b\u3089\u30d7\u30ea\u30ba\u30f3\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30af\u3058\u3083\u306a\u304f\u306d\uff1f</span>|trans-chapter=Lesson 193: Is There Even a Prison Break in \u201cPrison Break Season 2\u201d If You\u2019ve Already Broken out of Prison in Season 1?|volume=22|title-link=Gintama}}</ref> or conversely, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u597d\u6575\u624b|{{ruby-ja|\u597d\u6575\u624b|\u3068\u3082}}]]}} ''k\u014dtekishu'' \"eternal rival\" may be tagged with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u53cb|\u3068\u3082]]}} ''tomo'' \"friend\".<ref>{{cite book|date=February 26, 2004|publisher=[[Konami]]|title=<span lang=\"ja\">\u30a2\u30d3\u30b9\u30fb\u30e9\u30a4\u30b8\u30f3\u30b0</span>|trans-title=Abyss Rising|url=https://www.db.yugioh-card.com/yugiohdb/card_search.action?ope=2&cid=10297&request_locale=ja|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\u597d\u6575\u624b|\u3068\u3082}}\u306e{{ruby-ja|\u8a18|\u304d}}{{ruby-ja|\u61b6|\u304a\u304f}}</span>|trans-chapter=Memory of a Frenemy}}</ref> Some manga make use of the furigana renditions of foreign words (especially obscure ones) as the intended reading of a term, and the more familiar kanji for the meaning of such a term. For example, {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u9ed2\u30fb\u9b54\u30fb\u5c0e|\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30de\u30b8\u30c3\u30af}}}} may be assigned with {{lang|ja|\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30de\u30b8\u30c3\u30af}} ''burakku majikku'', the [[Transcription into Japanese|rendition]] of the English \"black magic\", to convey a foreign, exotic feel;<ref>{{cite book|date=February 26, 2004|publisher=[[Konami]]|title=<span lang=\"ja\">\u30d5\u30a1\u30e9\u30aa\u306e\u907a\u7523</span>|trans-title=Pharaoh's Legacy|url=https://www.db.yugioh-card.com/yugiohdb/card_search.action?ope=2&cid=6057&request_locale=ja|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\u9ed2\u30fb\u9b54\u30fb\u5c0e|\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30de\u30b8\u30c3\u30af}}</span>|trans-chapter=Black Magic}}</ref> {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|[[wikt:\u99c5|\u99c5]]|\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}}} with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|\u30b9\u30c6\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3]]}} ''sut\u0113shon'' \"station\";<ref>{{cite book|last=Amano|first=Kozue|author-link=Kozue Amano|date=April 27, 2002|title=Aqua|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|Navigation|\u30ca\u30d3\u30b2\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}06\u3000{{ruby-ja|\u59cb|\u306f\u3058}}\u3081\u3066\u306e\u304a{{ruby-ja|\u5ba2|\u304d\u3083\u304f}}{{ruby-ja|\u69d8|\u3055\u307e}}</span>|trans-chapter=Navigation 06: A First-Time Customer|volume=2|title-link=Aria (manga)}}</ref> {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|[[wikt:\u65b0\u5a5a\u65c5\u884c|\u65b0\u5a5a\u65c5\u884c]]|\u30cf\u30cb\u30fc\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3}}}} with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30cf\u30cb\u30fc\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3|\u30cf\u30cb\u30fc\u30e0\u30fc\u30f3]]}} ''han\u012bm\u016bn'' \"honeymoon\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Yamazaki|first=Kore|date=April 10, 2014|title=The Ancient Magus' Bride|chapter=Composition 2: One today is worth two tomorrows.|volume=1|title-link=The Ancient Magus' Bride}}</ref> This is sometimes done conversely, for example, by using {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30ad\u30c3\u30b9|\u30ad\u30c3\u30b9]]}} ''kissu'' \"kiss\", the more familiar term, as furigana to convey meaning, and {{lang|ja|{{ruby-ja|\u30d9\u30fc\u30bc|\u30ad\u30c3\u30b9}}}} ''b\u0113ze'' \"{{lang|fr|baiser}}\", the exotic term, as base text.<ref>{{cite book|last=Takahashi|first=Rumiko|author-link=Rumiko Takahashi|date=August 15, 1991|title=Ranma \u00bd|chapter=<span lang=\"ja\">{{ruby-ja|\uff30\uff21\uff32\uff34|\u30d1\u30fc\u30c8}}.\uff19\u3000{{ruby-ja|\u602a|\u304b\u3044}}{{ruby-ja|\u5947|\u304d}}\uff01\u304a{{ruby-ja|\u4e0a|\u3058\u3087\u3046}}{{ruby-ja|\u54c1|\u3072\u3093}}{{ruby-ja|\u9928|\u3084\u304b\u305f}}</span>|trans-chapter=Part 9: Horror! Folks of Class|volume=16|title-link=Ranma \u00bd}}</ref> For shorthand purposes, abbreviations such as {{ruby-ja|[[Interpol|ICPO]]|\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30fc\u30dd\u30fc\u30eb}} may be used to make the regular kana spelling that is too long smaller type.\n\nIn [[karaoke]] it is extremely common for furigana to be placed on the song lyrics. The song lyrics are often written in kanji pronounced quite differently from the furigana. The furigana version is used for pronunciation.\n\nAlso, because the kanji represent meaning while the furigana represent sound, one can combine the two to create [[pun]]s or indicate meanings of foreign words. One might write the kanji for \"blue\", but use katakana to write the pronunciation of the English word \"blue\"; this may be done, for example, in Japanese subtitles on foreign films, where it can help associate the written Japanese with the sounds actually being spoken by the actors, or it may be used in a translation of a work of fiction to enable the translator to preserve the original sound of a proper name (such as \"Firebolt\" in the [[Harry Potter]] series) in furigana, while simultaneously indicating its meaning with kanji. A similar practice is used in native fiction to clarify extended meanings. For example, in a work of science fiction, some astronaut could use the word {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u3075\u308b\u3055\u3068|\u3075\u308b\u3055\u3068]]}}, ''furusato'', meaning \"my hometown\", when referring to planet Earth. To clarify that for the reader, the word ''furusato'' (hometown) might be written in hiragana over the kanji for ''chikyuu'' (Earth).\n\n==Other Japanese reading aids==\n===Okurigana===\n{{Main|Okurigana}}\nOkurigana are kana that appear inline at normal size following kanji stems, typically to complete and to inflect adjectives and verbs. In this use they may also help to disambiguate kanji with multiple readings; for example, {{lang|ja|\u4e0a\u304c\u308b}} ({{lang|ja|\u3042\u304c\u308b}}, ''agaru'') vs. {{lang|ja|\u4e0a\u308b}} ({{lang|ja|\u306e\u307c\u308b}}, ''noboru''). Unlike furigana, the use of okurigana is a mandatory part of the written language.\n\n===Kunten===\n\nIn the written style known as ''[[kanbun]]'', which is the Japanese approximation of [[Classical Chinese]], small marks called ''[[kunten]]'' are sometimes added as reading aids. Unlike furigana, which indicate pronunciation, ''kunten'' indicate Japanese grammatical structures absent from the ''kanbun'', as well as showing how words should be reordered to fit Japanese sentence structure.\n\n===Furikanji===\nFurigana are sometimes also used to indicate meaning, rather than pronunciation. Over the foreign text, smaller sized Japanese words, in kana or kanji, corresponding to the ''meaning'' of the foreign words, effectively translate it in place. While rare now, some late 19th\u2013early 20th century authors used kanji as furigana for [[loanword]]s written in katakana. This usage is called {{nihongo|''furikanji''|\u632f\u308a\u6f22\u5b57}} in Japanese, since ''furi'''gana''''' implies the use of '''''[[kana]]'''''. For example, {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u30ea\u30ea\u30c3\u30af|{{ruby-ja|\u30ea\u30ea\u30c3\u30af|\u6b4c\u8a5e}}]]}} ''ririkku'' \"lyric\" may be tagged with {{lang|ja|[[wikt:\u6b4c\u8a5e|\u6b4c\u8a5e]]}} ''kashi'' \"lyrics\" for clarification rather than for phonetic guidance.<ref>{{cite book|author=TAGRO|date=July 23, 2008|title=Hen Semi|chapter=#06|volume=1|title-link=Hen Semi}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Okurigana]]\n*[[Ruby character]]\n*[[Zhuyin]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n===Bibliography===\n* ''Mangajin's Basic Japanese Through Comics [Part I]'' New York: Weatherhill, 1998: 48\u201349\n* J Paul Warnick, Review of ''Nihon o Hanasoo'' in ''The Journal of the Association of Teachers of Japanese'', Vol. 32, No. 2 (Oct., 1998), pp.&nbsp;80\u201383\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070704184818/http://yomoyomo.jp/ Add Ruby automatically for Japanese Web site]\u2014Multi-language phonetic reading site that can add phonetic reading to any site or texts in five different alphabets, hiragana, katakana, Roman, hangul, Devanagari, and Cyrillic letters for Japanese.\n* [http://www.furiganizer.com The Furiganizer] is a convenient online reading aid for all kinds of Japanese text. It automatically adds Furigana, offers easy access to the [[EDICT]] dictionary, and learns interactively which kanji the user already knows. Furiganized results can be printed or exported to Microsoft Word.\n\n{{Japanese language}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese writing system terms]]\n[[Category:Kana]]\n[[Category:Ruby characters]]\n[[Category:Japanese writing system]]\n", "name_user": "Hkbusfan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUsage:Add detail", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furigana"}
{"title_page": "Guy Sebastian", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=January 2013}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image = Guy_Sebastian_2014.jpg\n| name = Guy Sebastian\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100|AM}}\n| image_size = \n| caption = Sebastian in 2014\n| birth_name = Guy Theodore Sebastian\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1981|10|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Klang (city)|Klang]], [[Malaysia]]\n| home_town = [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], Australia\n| spouse = {{marriage|Jules Egan|17 May 2008}}\n| children = 3\n| Cairo_efs follow me on instagram \n| occupation = Singer-songwriter, [[record producer]]\n| module = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Pop music|Pop]]|[[Soul music|soul]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Gospel music|gospel]]}}\n| instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]], [[guitar]], [[piano]]/keyboards, [[drum kit|drums]]\n| years_active = 2003\u2013present\n| label = [[Sony Music Australia|Sony]], [[The Cherry Party]],<ref name=\"RCA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403141710/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691 |title=FMQB: Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Nielsen Ratings, Music News and more |archivedate=3 April 2014 |accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> [[Rush Associated Labels|RAL]], [[RCA Records|RCA]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcarecords.com/artists/guy-sebastian |title=RCA Artists: Guy Sebastian |publisher=[[RCA Records]] |accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref>\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Steve Cropper]]|[[Booker T. & the M.G.'s|The MGs]]|[[Lupe Fiasco]]|[[David Ryan Harris]]|[[Planetshakers]]|}}\n| website = {{URL|guysebastian.com}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Guy Theodore Sebastian''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AM}} (born 26 October 1981) is an Australian singer and songwriter who was the winner of the first ''[[Australian Idol]]'' in 2003, and a judge on Australia's ''[[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|The X Factor]]'' in 2010, 2011, 2012, 2015 and 2016.<ref name=\"Chris Isaak and James Blunt: Meet the new X Factor guys\">Moran, Jonathon (2 May 2015). [https://www.webcitation.org/6YEg9yttl?url=http://m.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/confidential/chris-isaak-and-james-blunt-meet-the-new-x-factor-guys/story-fnilxh2q-1227331987033?nk=7e9fbf0201661a67b58674032624dcac Chris Isaak and James Blunt: Meet the new X Factor guys]. Perthnow. Archived from [https://archive.today/20150524134401/http://m.perthnow.com.au/entertainment/confidential/chris-isaak-and-james-blunt-meet-the-new-x-factor-guys/story-fnilxh2q-1227331987033 the original] on 3 May 2015.</ref> He represented Australia at the [[2015 Eurovision Song Contest]], finishing in 5th place.<ref name=\"Eurovision 2015: Sweden's Mans Zelmerlow wins; Australia's Guy Sebastian fifth\">Idato, Michael (24 March 2015).[http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/eurovision-2015-swedens-mans-zelmerlow-wins-australias-guy-sebastian-fifth-20150524-gh8b1b.html#ixzz3tUUB6RHN Eurovision 2015: Sweden's Mans Zelmerlow wins; Australia's Guy Sebastian fifth]. [[Sydney Morning Herald]]. Retrieved 6 December 2015.</ref> Sebastian was  a coach for ''[[The Voice Australia]]'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guy Sebastian Is The New Superstar Coach On The Voice |url=https://www.nineentertainmentco.com.au/2018/11/14/14/24/guy-sebastian-is-the-new-superstar-coach-on-the-voice |website=nineentertainmentco.com.au}}</ref>\n\nSebastian has released nine top ten albums, including two number ones. The first seven all gained either platinum or multi-platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\">[http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian Girly Sebastian in the Australian Charts]. australian-charts.com. Retrieved 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"aria.com.au\">[http://aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations.htm Album and Single Accreditations 1997\u20132012]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 5 March 2009.</ref> He has also achieved twenty two top twenty singles, with thirteen reaching the top ten, including six number ones.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/> He is the only Australian male artist in Australian chart history to achieve six number one singles, and places third overall for all Australian acts.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian Equals Abba For Number 1 Hits In Australia\">Ryan, Gavin (19 August 2012). [https://www.webcitation.org/6A1tCs1VF?url=http://www.noise11.com/news/guy-sebastian-equals-abba-for-number-1-hits-in-australia-20120819 Guy Sebastian Equals Abba For Number 1 Hits In Australia]. Noise11. Archived from [http://www.noise11.com/news/guy-sebastian-equals-abba-for-number-1-hits-in-australia-20120819 the original] on 19 August 2012.</ref> Nine of his singles have been certified multi-platinum, including the 11\u00d7 platinum \"[[Battle Scars]]\".<ref name=\"ARIA 2010 Singles Accreditations\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.auaccreds2010.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2010 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 4 May 2010</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Single Accreditations 2011\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.auSINGLEaccreds2011.htm ARIA Single Accreditations 2011] Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 1 May 2011</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2012 Singles\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSINGLEaccreds2012.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2012 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA). Retrieved 15 June 2012.</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2013 Singles\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesaria-charts-accreditations-singles-2013.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2013 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 14 March 2013</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSinglesAccreds2019.htm ARIA Accreditations \u2013 2019 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA). Retrieved 30 March 2019.</ref> His debut single \"[[Angels Brought Me Here]]\" was the highest selling song in Australia in the decade 2000 to 2009.<ref name=\"ARIA's End Of Decade Charts\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qhIqoaj?url=http://www.aria.com.au/documents/ARIAEndOfDecadeCharts.pdf ARIA's End Of Decade Charts*] (PDF). Australian Recording Industry Association. 7 January 2010. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/documents/ARIAEndOfDecadeCharts.pdf the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> With 65 platinum and five gold certifications and combined album and single sales of over 4.7&nbsp;million in Australia, he has the [[Australian Idol discography#Album and single certification totals|highest certifications and sales of any ''Australian Idol'' contestant]].<ref name=\"aria.com.au\"/>\n\nSebastian has worked with a number of notable American musicians, including [[Brian McKnight]], [[Robin Thicke]], [[Steve Cropper]], [[John Mayer]], [[Jordin Sparks]], [[Eve (entertainer)|Eve]] and [[Lupe Fiasco]]. \"Battle Scars\", a collaboration with Fiasco, spent 20 weeks on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, peaking at number 71 and achieved platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian and Lupe Fiasco \u2013 Battle Scars\">[http://acharts.us/song/72443 Guy Sebastian and Lupe Fiasco - Battle Scars]. aCharts.US. Retrieved 29 January 2013.</ref><ref name=\"Gold Platinum searchable database\">[https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=Lupe+Fiasco&ti=Battle+Scars#search_section Gold Platinum searchable database]. [[Recording Industry Association of America]]. Retrieved 6 November 2016</ref> \"Battle Scars\" also reached number two in Norway and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Battle Scars Norway\">[http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian+feat%2E+Lupe+Fiasco&titel=Battle+Scars&cat=s Battle Scars Norway]. norwegiancharts.com. Hung Medien. Retrieved 3 January 2013.</ref> Sebastian has reached the top ten in New Zealand with an album and six singles, including two number ones, and gained six platinum and three gold certifications there.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts\">[http://charts.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts]. Charts.org.nz. Retrieved on 17 September 2012.</ref><ref name=\"RIANZ Archived Charts\">[http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=1256 RIANZ Archived Charts 18 January 2004].[[Recorded Music NZ|Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] (RIANZ). Retrieved 4 October 2013.</ref><ref name=\"Latest Gold/Platinum Singles\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110724195845/http://www.radioscope.net.nz/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=77&Itemid=61 Latest Gold/Platinum Singles]. RadioScope New Zealand. Archived from [http://www.radioscope.net.nz/ the original] on 24 July 2011. Retrieved 15 January 2012.</ref> In 2015 his Eurovision song charted in the top 50 in five European countries.<ref name=\"ACharts.US\">[http://acharts.us/song/92872 Guy Sebastian - Tonight Again]. acharts.us. Retrieved 30 May 2015.</ref><ref>[http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian&titel=Tonight+Again&cat=s Guy Sebastian on Dutch Charts]. Dutch Chart Archives. Retrieved 30 May 2015</ref><ref name=\"Iceland\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6Z90qzuCH?url=http://www.tonlist.is/Music/Chartlist/679/ Guy Sebastian \u2013 Tonight Again, Chartlist week 23, 2015]. Tonlist. Archived from [http://www.tonlist.is/Music/Chartlist/679/ the original] on 9 June 2015.</ref>\n\nDuring his career Sebastian has received 32 [[ARIA Award]] nominations, winning six including Best Pop Release and Best Live Act.<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20130926110926/http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/search?q=Guy%2BSebastian ARIA Awards History by Artist]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Archived from [http://www.ariaawards.com.au/history/search?q=Guy+Sebastian the original] on 30 November 2012.</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Nominations Announced\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64xGTk3GS?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/documents/2010ARIAAwardNominationsandArtisanAwardwinnersannounced.pdf ARIA Nominations]. Australian Recording Industry Association. 28 September 2010. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/documents/2010ARIAAwardNominationsandArtisanAwardwinnersannounced.pdf the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Award nominees announced for 2011\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6CYmruLuA?url=http://www.thevine.com.au/music/news/aria-award-nominees-announced-for-2011/ ARIA Award nominees announced for 2011]. thevine.com.au. 12 October 2011. Archived from [http://www.thevine.com.au/music/news/aria-award-nominees-announced-for-2011/ the original] on 30 November 2012.</ref><ref name=\"Winners of the 2011 ARIA Awards\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6CYmXzHHH?url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/winners-of-the-2011-aria-awards-20111127-1o1mr.html Winners of the 2011 ARIA Awards]. ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. 27 November 2011. Archived from [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/winners-of-the-2011-aria-awards-20111127-1o1mr.html the original] on 30 November 2012.</ref><ref name=\"2014 Aria Awards\">Smith, Sarah (6 October 2014). [https://www.webcitation.org/6T8jVgQiJ?url=http://www.fasterlouder.com.au/news/40788/Chet-Faker-and-Violent-Soho-lead-2014-ARIA-nominations Chet Faker and Violent Soho lead 2014 ARIA nominations]. Faster Louder. Archived from [http://www.fasterlouder.com.au/news/40788/Chet-Faker-and-Violent-Soho-lead-2014-ARIA-nominations the original] on 7 October 2014.</ref><ref name=\"Here are all the winners from the 2019 ARIA Awards\">[https://themusicnetwork.com/2019-aria-awards-winners/ Here are all the winners from the 2019 ARIA Awards].The Music Network. 27 November 2019. Retrieved 28 November 2019.</ref> Other awards include the [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA]] Urban Work of the Year, the [[Channel V Australia|[V] Oz Artist of the Year]], [[Urban Music Awards Australia and New Zealand|Urban Music Awards]] for Best Male Artist and Best R&B Album, and an International Songwriting Competition award for \"Battle Scars\". Sebastian has sung at many notable events, including performing for [[Pope Benedict XVI]], [[Oprah Winfrey]] and [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=\"Pope personally thanks WYD08 Volunteers\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qKKyxYE?url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/pope_personally_thanks_wyd08_volunteers/ Pope personally thanks WYD08 Volunteers]. Catholic News Agency. 20 July 2008. Archived from [http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/pope_personally_thanks_wyd08_volunteers/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"Guy Sebastian sings at Oprah's private party\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qKQXh9J?url=http://www.fox.com.au/entertainment/the_dirt/blog/exclusive-guy-sebastian-sings-at-oprahs-private-party/20101216-ay0n.html Exclusive: Guy Sebastian sings at Oprah's private party]. Today Network. The Dirt. 16 December 2010. Archived from [http://www.fox.com.au/entertainment/the_dirt//blog/exclusive-guy-sebastian-sings-at-oprahs-private-party/20101216-ay0n.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"Queen welcomes 54 countries to CHOGM\">Iggulden, Tom (28 October 2011). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qKW0GJL?url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2011/s3351123.htm Queen welcomes 54 countries to CHOGM]. ABC Lateline. Archived from [http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2011/s3351123.htm the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He has a strong commitment to charity, and was previously an ambassador for [[World Vision Australia]] and the [[Australian Red Cross]]. He has created his own foundation, The Sebastian Foundation, with his wife Jules.<ref name=\"The X Factor Australia: Guy Sebastian\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qKaTln0?url=http://au.tv.yahoo.com/x-factor/judges/article/-/7693358/guy-sebastian/ The X Factor Australia: Guy Sebastian]. Yahoo!7 tv. Archived from [http://au.tv.yahoo.com/x-factor/judges/article/-/7693358/guy-sebastian/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"2016 Aria Awards\">Cronin, Seanna (5 October 2016).[http://www.dailymercury.com.au/news/flume-leads-nominations-30th-annual-aria-awards/3097059/ Flume leads nominations for 30th annual ARIA Awards]. Retrieved 5 October 2016.</ref> Sebastian was made a [[Member of the Order of Australia]] (AM) in the [[2019 Queen's Birthday Honours (Australia)|2019 Queen's Birthday Honours]] in recognition of his significant service to music and charity.<ref name=\"Order of Australia\">[https://www.oztix.com.au/news/archive/2019/06/10/darren-hayes-guy-sebastian--more-named-on-queens-birthday-honours-list-themusic/ Darren Hayes, Guy Sebastian & More Named On Queen's Birthday Honours List].OZtix. Retrieved 11 June 2019.</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGuy Sebastian was born in [[Klang (city)|Klang]], [[Selangor]], Malaysia, on 26 October 1981. His father Ivan was also born in Malaysia and is an ethnic [[Malaysian Indian]] of [[Tamil people|Tamil]] origin and [[Sri Lankans in Malaysia|Ceylonese]] descent with distant colonial Portuguese roots, while his mother Nellie is an ethnic [[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]] of English and Portuguese descent and was raised in India.<ref name=\"Nice guys do win\">Cheah, Jason (22 December 2003). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qLhp6Jk?url=http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=%2F2003%2F12%2F22%2Ffeatures%2F6951322 Nice guys do win]. thestar.com. Archived from [http://thestar.com.my/lifestyle/story.asp?file=/2003/12/22/features/6951322 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> They met while Ivan was studying geology in India and they married a year later. Sebastian is the second of four sons. His older brother Ollie was born in India, and his younger brothers Chris and Jeremy were born in Australia after the family migrated there in 1988, when he was six years old. They lived in [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]], for several years before eventually moving to [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], due to Ivan's work as a geologist.<ref name=\"Angels Brought Me Here: The Official Biography\">Bermingham, L. B. (2004). Guy Sebastian ''Angels Brought Me Here: The Official Biography'', Funtastic, Victoria. {{ISBN|1-74150-055-9}}</ref>\n\nAs a child Sebastian took violin lessons; he would later learn to play guitar, drums and piano, although he has had no formal training in these other musical instruments. He attended [[Paradise Community Church]], an [[Assemblies of God]] church and one of the largest churches in Australia, and he became one of their main worship singers. He also sang with the Paradise Community Church Youth Conference [[Planetshakers]], performing both lead and backup vocals for their 2002 and 2003 conferences and albums. (After winning ''Australian Idol'' he recorded on two of their albums, ''Adore'' in 2004 and ''Set Me Free'' in 2005.)<ref name=\"Nice guys do win\"/><ref name=\"Angels Brought Me Here: The Official Biography\"/> Sebastian attended [[King's Baptist Grammar School]]. He then began studies in Medical Radiation at the [[University of South Australia]], but left to pursue a career in music. He taught vocals at Temple Christian College and other high schools while also working as a recording engineer and studying [[Music Technology]] at the [[University of Adelaide]]'s [[Elder Conservatorium|Elder School of Music]].<ref name=\"Nice guys do win\"/>\n\n==Recording career==\n\n===2003\u20132004: ''Australian Idol'' and ''Just as I Am''===\n[[File:Guy Sebastian at Australian Gospel Music Fesitval 11 April 2004 (1).jpg|right|thumb|Sebastian performing at the [[Australian Gospel Music Festival]], April 2004]]\nIn May 2003 Sebastian successfully auditioned for ''[[Australian Idol]]'', singing [[Stevie Wonder]]'s \"[[Ribbon in the Sky]]\". He progressed through the ''Idol'' series, establishing a strong fanbase and praise from the judges, who often made reference to his afro hairstyle which became a focal point of his image.<ref name=\"Angels Brought Me Here: The Official Biography\"/> He was declared the winner on 19 November 2003, and gained a recording contract with [[BMG Australia|BMG]], which later merged with [[Sony Music Australia|Sony]]. Following his ''Idol'' win Sebastian was required to record his debut album in six days, but despite this time restriction the album included three songs co-written by him.<ref>[http://www.cqbiblestudy.org/article.php?id=41 Guy Sebastian: \"I believe everything has a season.\"]. cqbiblestudy.org. Archived from [http://www.cqbiblestudy.org/article.php?id=41 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He then travelled to the UK to compete in ''[[World Idol]]''. Although he impressed the judges, with several suggesting he could win the competition, he finished seventh.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64qLuHCaH?url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/12/27/1072308689856.html Guy wows World Idol judges]. ''The Age''. 27 December 2003. Archived from [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/12/27/1072308689856.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref>\n\nSebastian's winner's single \"[[Angels Brought Me Here]]\" debuted at number one and was the highest selling single in Australia in 2003, reaching 5\u00d7 platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2003\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64u04DekU?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2003.htm ARIA Charts Top 100 Singles 2003]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2003.htm the original] on 23 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/> In 2010 it was named the highest selling song of the decade 2000 to 2009, ahead of [[Anthony Callea]]'s \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\".<ref name=\"ARIA's End Of Decade Charts\"/> \"Angels Brought Me Here\" held the record for being the highest selling single ever released by an Australian act until 2011.<ref name=\"aria.com.au\"/><ref name=\"Anthony Callea Premature Sales Announcement\">[[Paul Cashmere|Cashmere, Paul]] (29 January 2005). [https://web.archive.org/web/20050131033809/http://www.undercover.com.au/news/2005/jan05/20050129_anthonycallea.html Anthony Callea Premature Sales Announcement]. undercover.com.au. Archived from [http://www.undercover.com.au/news/2005/jan05/20050129_anthonycallea.html the original] on 31 January 2004. Retrieved 4 February 2012.</ref> Sebastian's debut album ''[[Just as I Am (Guy Sebastian album)|Just as I Am]]'' was released in December 2003 and also achieved number one. Its first week sales of 163,711 units are the second highest one week sales in Australian chart history, the highest for an Australian act.<ref>Cashmere, Paul (27 December 2006). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qitzWeu?url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/1121-damien-leith-has-biggest-seller-of-the-year Damien Leith Has Biggest Seller Of The Year]. Undercover.com.au. Archived from [http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=1133 the original] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830182137/http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=1133 |date=30 August 2007 }} on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>Adams, Cameron (29 December 2009). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qj0v9RS?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/susan-boyles-album-smashes-sales-records/story-e6frfmvr-1225814357408 Susan Boyle's album smashes sales records]. ''Herald Sun''. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/susan-boyles-album-smashes-sales-records/story-e6frfmvr-1225814357408 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> It eventually reached sales just short of 7\u00d7 platinum, and is the highest selling album ever released by an Australian ''Idol'' contestant.<ref name=\"ARIA's End Of Decade Charts\"/><ref>Quinn, Karl (21 November 2004).\n[https://www.webcitation.org/64qkPFst4?url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/Music/Everyones-a-winner/2004/11/19/1100748195505.html Everyone's A Winner]. ''The Age''. Archived from [http://www.theage.com.au/news/Music/Everyones-a-winner/2004/11/19/1100748195505.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>Sams, Christine (8 November 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/64xAjATAO?url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/how-i-beat-bullies-of-rocknroll-20101106-17i3j.html How I beat bullies of rock'n'roll]. ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. Archived from [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/how-i-beat-bullies-of-rocknroll-20101106-17i3j.html the original] on 25 January 2012.</ref> \"Angels Brought Me Here\" also reached number one in Malaysia, Singapore, the Philippines, Indonesia and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian biography\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qJVcIQx?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/bio/home.do Guy Sebastian biography]. Guy Sebastian official site. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/bio/home.do the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"Beautiful Life & Guy Facts\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64pjo0Gtd?url=http://www.opensubscriber.com/message/mediacare@yahoogroups.com/1997998.html Beautiful Life & Guy Facts]. opensubscriber.com. Archived from [http://www.opensubscriber.com/message/mediacare@yahoogroups.com/1997998.html the original] on 19 January 2012.</ref> ''Just as I Am'' reached number three and double platinum certification in New Zealand, with \"Angels Brought Me Here\" achieving platinum certification there.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts\"/><ref name=\"RIANZ Archived Charts\"/><ref>[http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=2117 RIANZ Archived Charts NZ Top 40 Singles 11 January 2004].[[Recorded Music NZ|Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] (RIANZ). Retrieved 4 October 2013.</ref> The second single \"[[All I Need Is You]]\" reached number one and platinum in Australia, and peaked at number five in New Zealand.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2004 Singles\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64wvNA3FI?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-singles-2004.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2004 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA). Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-singles-2004.htm the original] on 25 January 2012.</ref> In early 2004 Sebastian appeared at the Asian MTV Awards, was a guest judge on ''[[New Zealand Idol]]'' and performed on ''[[Indonesian Idol]]''.<ref name=\"Beautiful Life & Guy Facts\"/> After a promotional trip to Malaysia in April he travelled to Europe and the US to write for his next album, performing on ''[[American Idol]]'' while in the US.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian biography\"/>\n\n===2004\u20132007: ''Beautiful Life'' and ''Closer to the Sun''===\n''[[Beautiful Life (Guy Sebastian album)|Beautiful Life]]'', Sebastian's second album, had a more [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] edge to it and included songs he co-wrote with [[Robin Thicke]] and [[Brian McKnight]] and \"Forever with You\", a duet with American R&B singer [[M\u00fda]].<ref name=\"Beautiful Life & Guy Facts\"/> The lead single \"[[Out with My Baby]]\" debuted at number one in October 2004, and gained platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2004 Singles\"/> Sebastian performed at the 2004 ARIA Music Awards where he received the award for the Highest Selling Single for \"Angels Brought Me Here\", and the [[Channel V Australia|Channel V]] Oz Artist of the Year Award.<ref name=\"Musicdish: Aria Awards 2004\">Canak, Danny (15 November 2004). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qj63eoV?url=http://www.musicdish.com/mag/index.php3?id=9832 Aria Awards 2004]. Musicdish. Archived from [http://www.musicdish.com/mag/index.php3?id=9832 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He was also nominated for Highest Selling Album for ''Just as I Am''.<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\"/> ''Beautiful Life'' peaked at number two and was also certified platinum.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref>[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-albums-2004.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2004 Albums]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 28 August 2009.</ref> Sebastian embarked on a national tour in November, with a second stage from March to June 2005.<ref name=\"Beautiful Life Tour\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qkk1FuY?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829001636 Guy & Paulini Announce More Shows For The Beautiful Life Tour]. Guy Sebastian official website. 6 April 2005. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829001636 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian performed at the 20th Anniversary SAFM Sky Show in Adelaide in front of approximately 150,000 people along with [[Slinkee Minx]], one of the largest open-air concerts held in Australia in 2005.  Two further singles were released from the album, \"[[Kryptonite (Guy Sebastian song)|Kryptonite]]\" which peaked at number fifteen, and \"[[Oh Oh]]\" at number eleven.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/> In 2005 Sebastian received awards for Favourite Video, Favourite Music Artist, and Favourite Aussie at the [[Nickelodeon Kid's Choice Awards]], and a [[MTV Video Music Award]] for \"Out with my Baby\".<ref name=\"The Age: Kids' choice \u2013 Guy\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qkpWiyT?url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/tv--radio/kids-choice--guy/2005/09/21/1126982092531.html Kids' choice \u2013 Guy]. ''The Age''. 21 September 2005. Archived from [http://www.theage.com.au/news/tv--radio/kids-choice--guy/2005/09/21/1126982092531.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>Halliwell, Elle & Anderson, Juliet. [https://www.webcitation.org/64ql031Nd?url=http://www.mediasearch.com.au/music/spotlights/mtv-australianmtvmusicvideoawardfs-2005 MTV Australian Video Music Awards for 2005]. Mediasearch. Archived from [http://www.mediasearch.com.au/music/spotlights/mtv-australianmtvmusicvideoawardfs-2005 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He also received a Highest Selling Album ARIA Award nomination for ''Beautiful Life'', and was named as a state finalist in the [[Young Australian Of The Year|Young Australian of the Year Awards]].<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\"/><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64ql6GFOt?url=http://www.marssociety.org.au/library/media_release_081205.php MSA Member NSW Finalist for Young Australian of the Year]. marssociety.org.au. 1 December 2005. Archived from [http://www.marssociety.org.au/library/media_release_081205.php the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref>\n\nBetween May and August 2006, Sebastian appeared as a mentor on the inaugural ''[[It Takes Two (Australian TV series)|It Takes Two]]'', in which performers from non-musical fields are teamed with professional singers to perform a duet each week. Sebastian's partner was three-time Australian Olympic swimmer [[Sarah Ryan]] and they finished second.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sk7Q0uo?url=http://www.7perth.com.au/view/releases/20060731114235/ IT TAKES TWO]. 7 Perth. Archived from [http://www.7perth.com.au/view/releases/20060731114235/ the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> During this period Sebastian also recorded his third album ''[[Closer to the Sun (Guy Sebastian album)|Closer to the Sun]]'' which was a mix of genres including [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[Soul music|soul]], [[pop rock]] and [[jazz]] and mainly co-written with Australian musicians. The lead single \"[[Taller, Stronger, Better]]\" debuted at number three in August 2006, and achieved gold certification.<ref name=\"Accreditations \u2013 2007 Singles\">[http://aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesARIACharts-Accreditations-2007Singles.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2007 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 27 February 2009.</ref> The album peaked at number four and was certified platinum.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref>[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/ARIACharts-Accreditations-2006Albums.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2006 Albums]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 28 August 2009.</ref> The second single \"[[Elevator Love]]\" reached number 11 and gold certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"Accreditations \u2013 2007 Singles\"/> The video featured [[Jennifer Hawkins]] as his love interest.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64qkuQ5Ww?url=http://www.myspace.com/video/vid/3655345 ACA Preview of Video of Elevator Love with Jennifer Hawkins]. Myspace Videos. Archived from [https://archive.today/20121130024657/http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&VideoID=3655345 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian received an award for most played Urban work for \"Oh Oh\" at the 2006 [[Australasian Performing Right Association|APRA Music Awards]].<ref>Pascuzzi, Carmine. [https://www.webcitation.org/64qlA2sVA?url=http://www.mediasearch.com.au/music/spotlights/apraawards2006 2006 APRA Music Awards]. Mediasearch. Archived from [http://www.mediasearch.com.au/music/spotlights/apraawards2006 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> \"Oh Oh\" was also awarded Best Video and Sebastian named Best Male Artist at the [[Urban Music Awards Australia and New Zealand|Urban Music Awards]], and for the second year in succession he received the Fav Aussie award at the Nickelodeon Kids Choice Awards.<ref name=\"smh.com.au\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64qlEip64?url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/sebastian-macrae-get-gongs-at-urban-awards/2006/07/21/1153166583688.html Sebastian, MacRae get gongs at Urban awards]. ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. 21 July 2006. Archived from [http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/sebastian-macrae-get-gongs-at-urban-awards/2006/07/21/1153166583688.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>Bonawitz, Amy (11 October 2006). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qlLXtG3?url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/10/11/entertainment/main2082368.shtml Bindi & Terri Attend Kids Choice Awards]. CBS News. Archived from [http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/10/11/entertainment/main2082368.shtml the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> ''Closer to the Sun'''s third single \"Cover on My Heart\" was released in August 2007, peaking at number thirty two on the ARIA Singles Chart.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/> ''Closer the Sun'' was named Best Album at the 2007 Urban Music Awards and Most Popular Album at the [[Dolly Teen Choice Awards]].<ref name=\"inthemix.com.au\">Lizza (17 August 2007). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qlSRmfR?url=http://www.inthemix.com.au/events/reviews/33691/2007_Urban_Music_Awards_Luna_Park_Sydney_140807 2007 Urban Music Awards at Luna Park, Sydney]. inthemix. Archived from [http://www.inthemix.com.au/events/reviews/33691/2007_Urban_Music_Awards_Luna_Park_Sydney_140807 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64qlbqlCu?url=http://www.servinghistory.com/topics/Dolly_Teen_Choice_Awards::sub::Winners_07 Dolly Teen Choice Awards: Winners 07]. servinghistory.com. Archived from [http://www.servinghistory.com/topics/Dolly_Teen_Choice_Awards::sub::Winners_07 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132008: ''The Memphis Album'' and ''Tour''===\n{{Main|The Memphis Album}}\n[[File:Guy Sebastian The Memphis Tour 7 Mar 2008.JPG|left|thumb|Sebastian and [[Steve Cropper]] on stage during The Memphis Tour]]\nIn early 2007 it had been announced Sebastian would be recording a tribute album of soul classics in [[Memphis, Tennessee]] with [[Stax Records|Stax]] musicians who played on and wrote some of the original songs. The album was recorded at [[Ardent Studios]], Memphis in August 2007, with [[Steve Cropper]], [[Duck Dunn|Donald 'Duck' Dunn]], and [[Steve Potts (drummer)|Steve Potts]] (a.k.a. [[Booker T & The MGs|The MGs]]), with Lester Snell on keyboards. Cropper also co-produced the album with Sebastian, which was recorded on analogue tape live in the studio.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64qvEaBNM?url=http://www.myspace.com/video/vid/54159104 Curry Weber Studio Engineer talks about the Memphis Album]. Myspace Videos. Archived from [http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&VideoID=54159104 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian wrote about his time in Memphis in a series of blogs for Australian newspapers, \"I started recording four days ago with the band members from Booker T and the MGs. And in the four days, we cut 15 tracks. It's been such a great experience to watch these guys work. I mean, they are mostly in their late 60s and have such a wealth of experience.\"<ref>Sebastian, Guy (29 August 2007). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qvJ5rGZ?url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/guys-memphis-diary-week-4/story-e6frf96f-1111114293968 Guy's Memphis Diary \u2013 Week 4] ''Sunday Herald Sun''. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,22327811-2902,00.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Cropper later spoke on AllMemphisMusic, an online Memphis radio station, \"This kid came into Memphis, and just blew everybody's socks off. [...] he just took us by storm.\"<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rCd8tSP?url=http://www.myspace.com/video/vid/61522976 Steve Cropper talks about Guy Sebastian and The Memphis Album]. MySpace Videos. Archived from [http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&VideoID=61522976 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Shortly after Sebastian's return to Australia it was announced that The MGs would tour Australia with him in early 2008.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rCpcUna?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005131 Guy Sebastian Announces 2008 \"Memphis Tour\"!]. Guy Sebastian official website. 6 November 2007. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005131 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> ''[[The Memphis Album]]'' debuted at number three in November 2007, and was the seventh highest selling Australian artist album of the year.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64u0DRI2e?url=http://aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-australian-album-2007.htm ARIA End Of Year Charts \u2013 Top 50 Australian Artist Albums 2007]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Archived from [http://aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-australian-album-2007.htm the original] on 23 January 2012.</ref> The critically acclaimed album reached double platinum certification in 2008.<ref name=\"The Memphis Album Reviews\">[http://gsinfo-soulfan.blogspot.com/2010/07/memphis-album-reviews.html The Memphis Album Reviews] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/64yJdccWX?url=http://gsinfo-soulfan.blogspot.com/2010/07/memphis-album-reviews.html |date=26 January 2012 }}. Blogspot.com. Retrieved 25 June 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupagesARIACharts-Accreditations-2008Albums.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2008 Albums]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 28 August 2009.</ref> ''[[The Memphis Flyer]]'', a weekly alternative newspaper serving the Memphis area wrote a series of articles about Sebastian recording with The MGs.<ref>Branston, John (22 November 2007). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qvOGlMP?url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/TheDailyBuzz/archives/2007/11/22/guy-sebastians-memphis-album-is-actually-good Guy Sebastian's Memphis Album Is Actually Good]. ''The Memphis Flyer''. Archived from [http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/Content?oid=oid%3A36500 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> AllMemphisMusic, which specialises in playing music originating from Memphis, began playing ''The Memphis Album'' songs in late December 2007. They also had two special programs featuring songs from the album and interviews with some of the people involved in recording it.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64qu6HMC5?url=http://allmemphismusic.blogspot.com/2008/04/who-is-this-guy-sebastian.html Who is this \"Guy\" Sebastian?]. AllMemphisMusic. 23 April 2006. Archived from [http://allmemphismusic.blogspot.com/2008/04/who-is-this-guy-sebastian.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref>\n{{listen\n| filename=Guy Sebastian - Gimme Some Lovin' (Live).OGG\n| title=\"Gimme Some Lovin'\"\n| description=Excerpt of live performance by Sebastian & the [[Booker T. & the M.G.'s|MGs]] during [[The Memphis Tour]]\n|pos=right\n| format=[[Ogg]]\n}}\nThe [[Booker T. & the M.G.'s|MGs]] came to Australia in February 2008 to be Sebastian's backing band for his national tour. He spoke on radio about what it felt like fronting the MGs, \"There were so many moments when I just had to take a step back and think 'This is unbelievable'. Like the history that is behind me, and I'm singing these songs. You know they start playing Dock of the Bay, and the guys that played it are on the stage. You know the guy who wrote the song with [[Otis Redding]] is playing guitar.\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gmjQMESDdoE Stuart Bocking 2UE interviews Guy Sebastian about Steve Cropper]. YouTube. 27 May 2012. Retrieved 17 December 2015.</ref> Cropper later spoke on AllMemphisMusic, \"hearing him singing our music, which was born and raised and produced and recorded in Memphis, Tennessee. [...] It just filled our hearts.\"<ref>[https://myspace.com/songbirdbabe/video/steve-cropper-talks-about-guy-sebastian-and-the-memphis-album/61522976 Steve Cropper talks about Guy Sebastian and The Memphis Album] MySpace Videos. Retrieved 23 January 2015.</ref> One of the Melbourne concerts was filmed for a live DVD/CD titled ''[[The Memphis Tour]]''.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rEFu0E7?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005516 Guy's New DVD 'The Memphis Tour' Out Saturday]. Guy Sebastian official website. 29 April 2008. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005516 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian was nominated for a [[Helpmann Award]] for Best Performance in an Australian Contemporary Concert for ''The Memphis Tour'', and was awarded two Australian Club Entertainment Awards, best Original Music Performer and Outstanding Club Performer of the Year.<ref name=\"Helpman Awards: 2008 Nominations\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64rFq8EMO?url=http://www.helpmannawards.com.au/default.aspx?s=nominees&year=2008&cid=1 2008 Helpman Award Nominations]. Helpman Awards. Archived from [http://www.helpmannawards.com.au/default.aspx?s=nominees&year=2008&cid=1 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"ACE Awards: 11th Australian Club Awards\">[http://www.aceawards.com.au/2008.php 11th Australian Club Entertainment Awards] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303065920/http://www.aceawards.com.au/2008.php |date=3 March 2011 }}. ACE Awards. Retrieved 27 February 2009.</ref> ''The Memphis Album'' received a nomination for Highest Selling Album at the 2008 ARIA Awards, his third album to be nominated in this ARIA Awards category.<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\"/> He travelled to the US several times after ''The Memphis Tour'' to write for his fifth album, spending time with Cropper in Nashville on these trips.<ref>Cashmere, Paul (21 April 2008). [https://www.webcitation.org/64rGBG24N?url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/4591-guy-sebastian-is-hanging-with-the-croppers Guy Sebastian Is Hanging With The Croppers]. undercover.com.au. Archived from [http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=4644 the original] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922202758/http://undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=4644 |date=22 September 2008 }} on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rGJ8dao?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/guy-could-not-stop-staring-at/story-e6frfmqr-1111116783032 Guy Sebastian 'could not stop staring' at Nicole Kidman]. news.com.au. 1 July 2008. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0,26278,23949496-5013560,00.html the original] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080808221220/http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/story/0%2C26278%2C23949496-5013560%2C00.html |date=8 August 2008 }} on 21 January 2012.</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132010: ''Like It Like That''===\n{{Main|Like It Like That (album)}}\n[[File:Jordin Sparks & Guy Sebastian Club Nokia LA.jpg|thumb|right|Sebastian & [[Jordin Sparks]] performing \"[[Art of Love (song)|Art of Love]]\" at [[Club Nokia]] in LA in July 2010]]\nIn 2008 Sebastian was signed to release an album in the US, and in November he returned to America to work on it. He recorded songs with John Mayer's band, and [[John Mayer]] himself played guitar and sang backing vocals on three of the tracks.<ref>Dennehy, Luke (30 November 2008). [https://www.webcitation.org/64rGNutzr?url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/sunday-heraldsun/guy-sees-future-in-memphis/story-e6frf92x-1111118177315 Guy sees future in Memphis]. ''Herald Sun''. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,24725290-5006024,00.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He moved to New York in early 2009 to prepare for the release of the US album which was a mix of Memphis soul covers and original songs.<ref>Reines, Ros (15 February 2009). [https://www.webcitation.org/64rGSV1DO?url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/guy-targets-the-states/story-e6frezt9-1111118854324 Guy targets the States]. ''The Daily Telegraph''. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,25055628-5013110,00.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He performed showcases at the [[SXSW]] Music Festival in Austin Texas, and a residency at the Drom in New York.<ref>Cashmere, Paul (20 March 2009). [https://www.webcitation.org/64rGYbPTZ?url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/7794-guy-sebastian-wins-the-tough-sxsw-crowd Guy Sebastian Wins The Tough SXSW Crowd]. Undercover.com.au. Archived from [http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=7869 the original] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521080545/http://undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=7869 |date=21 May 2009 }} on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>Nanton, Nick [https://www.webcitation.org/64rGddi4M?url=http://www.thebusinessgrowthlawyers.com/blogs/texas-and-australia-collide.php Texas and Australia Collide!!\u2026???]. D&N Dicks $ Nanton P.A. Archived from [http://www.thebusinessgrowthlawyers.com/blogs/texas-and-australia-collide.php the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rG1L7C7?url=http://sociallysuperlative.com/2009/04/22/guy-sebastian-at-drom/ Guy Sebastian at DROM]. Socially Superlative. Archived from [http://sociallysuperlative.com/2009/04/22/guy-sebastian-at-drom/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> His song \"[[Like It Like That (Guy Sebastian song)|Like It Like That]]\" was chosen as the theme song for the [[NBC]] network's summer promotional campaign.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rGiX1Vk?url=http://www.myspace.com/video/vid/57700390 NBC Network Summer Campaign featuring Guy Sebastian theme]. Myspace Video. Archived from [https://archive.today/20120720112318/http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&VideoID=57700390 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rGqzY5a?url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/guy-sebastians-hit-song-will-beused-for-us-tv-promotion/story-e6frewz0-1225711556633 Guy Sebastian's hit song will be used for US TV promotion]. ''The Daily Telegraph'', 13 May 2009. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,25470469-5006002,00.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> The US release was then delayed due to restructuring of Victor Records, but it was later reaffirmed the album would be released in 2010.<ref>Moran, Jonathon (19 December 2009). [https://www.webcitation.org/64rGxOfTi?url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/insider/carnival-for-the-danimals/story-e6frewt9-1225812018581 Carnival for the Danimals, US glitch for Guy]. ''The Sunday Telegraph''. Archived from [http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/sunday-telegraph/carnival-for-the-danimals/story-e6frewt9-1225812018581 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> \"Like It Like That\", the title track of Sebastian's fifth album, was released in Australia in August 2009 and reached number one.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/> It was the highest selling Australian artist song in 2009, and achieved 4\u00d7 platinum certification.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64u0Nlau6?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-australian-singles-2009.htm ARIA Charts Top 50 Australian Artist Singles 2009]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-australian-singles-2009.htm the original] on 23 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2014 Singles\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesaria-charts-accreditations-singles-2014.htm ARIA Charts - Accreditations - 2014 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 14 March 2014</ref> ''[[Like It Like That (album)|Like It Like That]]'', an original soul album with all songs written or co-written by Sebastian, was released in October 2009. It reached number six and was certified platinum.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2010 Albums\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupagesARIACharts-Accreditations-2010Albums.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2010 Albums]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 8 June 2010.</ref>\n\n\"[[Art of Love (song)|Art of Love]]\", a duet with [[Jordin Sparks]] was released as the second single.<ref>[http://www.take40.com/artists/1748/guy-sebastian/news/17348/guy-sebastian-and-jordin-sparks-record-duet! Guy Sebastian and Jordin Sparks record duet]. Take 40. 1 October 2009. Retrieved 12 October 2009.</ref> It peaked at number eight and reached double platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2014 Singles\"/> It also charted at number seven in New Zealand, gaining gold certification there.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts\"/><ref name=\"Latest Gold/Platinum Singles\"/> Two further singles, \"[[All to Myself (Guy Sebastian song)|All to Myself]]\" and \"[[Never Hold You Down]]\", did not chart in the ARIA top 50.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rH5Rlk3?url=http://auspop.blogspot.com/2010/01/news-wrap_29.html Newswrap]. auspOp. 29 January 2010. Archived from [http://auspop.blogspot.com/2010/01/news-wrap_29.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64s125J0x?url=http://auspop.blogspot.com/2010/05/guy-single-4.html Guy Single #4]. auspOp. 27 May 2010. Archived from [http://auspop.blogspot.com/2010/05/guy-single-4.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian toured in Australia during February 2010 and again in June and July.<ref name=\"Like It Like That Tour\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64s4XOPw3?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829006494 Like It Like That Tour For 2010]. Guy Sebastian official website. Retrieved 9 September 2009. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829006494 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"The Bring Yourself Tour!\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64rHPGBsQ?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829006753 The Bring Yourself Tour!]. Guy Sebastian official website. 11 May 2010. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829006753 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> The US album, now identical to the Australian album, was given limited release on the [[RED Distribution|Red Ink]] label in June 2010, with distribution via iTunes and [[Barnes & Noble]] stores.<ref name=\"Like It Like That Barnes & Noble Exclusive\">[https://www.webcitation.org/651yebYZT?url=http://music.barnesandnoble.com/Like-It-Like-That/Guy-Sebastian/e/886977446726/?itm=2&USRI=guy+sebastian+like+it+like+that Like It Like That Barnes & Noble Exclusive]. Barnes & Noble. Archived from [http://music.barnesandnoble.com/Like-It-Like-That/Guy-Sebastian/e/886977446726/?itm=2&USRI=guy+sebastian+like+it+like+that the original] on 28 January 2012.</ref> He was chosen as a judge on the 2010 series of Australia's [[The X Factor (Australia season 2)|The X-Factor]], and to fulfil commitments to X-Factor and also the release of his album in America Sebastian divided his time between Australia and the US during the show.<ref>Dennehy, Luke (30 May 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/64rHTe13c?url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/sunday-heraldsun/x-factor-to-have-a-nice-guy-judge/story-e6frf92x-1225872977171 X-Factor to have a nice guy judge]. ''Sunday Herald Sun''. 30 May 2010. Archived from [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/sunday-heraldsun/x-factor-to-have-a-nice-guy-judge/story-e6frf92x-1225872977171 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He toured the US [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] between July and September, including guest performances singing \"Art of Love\" with Sparks at three of her ''[[Battlefield Tour]]'' concerts, and also played support for [[Chicago (band)|Chicago]] at a concert in [[Oregon]].<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian Releases Debut U.S. Album, Tours West Coast\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64rHbeYEY?url=http://popdirt.com/guy-sebastian-releases-debut-u-s-album-tours-west-coast/79311/ Guy Sebastian Releases Debut U.S. Album, Tours West Coast]. popdirt.com. Archived from [http://popdirt.com/guy-sebastian-releases-debut-u-s-album-tours-west-coast/79311/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rHmeQpw?url=http://www.mjsbigblog.com/jordin-sparks-and-guy-sebastian-sing-art-of-love-nokia-theater-los-angeles.htm Jordin Sparks and Guy Sebastian sing \u2018Art of Love\u2019 Nokia Theater, LA].mjsbigblog.com. 10 July 2010. Archived from [http://mjsbigblog.com/jordin-sparks-and-guy-sebastian-sing-art-of-love-nokia-theater-los-angeles.htm the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"Guy Sebastian announces more US tour dates\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64rHyQ1bR?url=http://www.antimusic.com/news/10/aug/04Guy_Sebastian_Announces_More_US_Dates.shtml Guy Sebastian announces more US tour dates].antimusic.com. 4 August 2010. Archived from [http://www.antimusic.com/news/10/aug/04Guy_Sebastian_Announces_More_US_Dates.shtml the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian was nominated for six [[ARIA Music Awards]] for ''Like It Like That''. He received nominations for Best Pop Release, Best Male Artist, Most Popular Australian Album and Most Popular Australian Artist, with \"Like It Like That\" and \"Art of Love\" receiving nominations for Most Popular Single.<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Nominations Announced\"/>\n\n===2010\u20132011: ''The X Factor'' and ''Twenty Ten''===\n{{Main|Twenty Ten (album)}}\nIn 2010 Sebastian was selected as a judge on the Australian series of ''[[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref name=\"The X Factor Australia: Guy Sebastian\"/> It is a talent competition where the judges also mentor the contestants. The contestants are selected by all the judges at the auditions, and the chosen acts are divided into four categories, Boys, Girls, Over 25s and Groups. Each judge is given a category and has to reduce their acts to three. The three acts from each category then compete in the live shows with continuing help from their mentors. Sebastian was given Groups in 2010, and was assisted in choosing his final three acts by [[Rai Thistlethwayte]], lead singer of [[Thirsty Merc]], [[Snoop Dogg]] and [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]].<ref>Byrne, Fiona (8 September 2010). Superstars join the X Factor cull. ''Herald Sun''. Archived from [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/superstars-join-the-x-factor-cull/story-e6frf96f-1225915735227 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian released a [[Compilation album|retrospective album]] titled ''[[Twenty Ten (album)|Twenty Ten]]'' in November 2010. The album reached number four on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Album Chart.]]<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/652wgCt3e?url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian&titel=Twenty+Ten&cat=a Twenty Ten in the Australian Charts]. australian-charts.com. Archived from [http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian&titel=Twenty+Ten&cat=a the original] on 29 January 2012.</ref> It spent twelve weeks in the top ten and was the fifth highest selling Australian artist album of 2010.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64u0WFO0i?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-australian-album-2010.htm Top Australian Artist Albums 2010]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-australian-album-2010.htm the original] on 23 January 2012.</ref> It was certified double platinum in 2014.<ref name=\"ARIA Album Certifications 2014\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesaria-charts-accreditations-albums-2014.htm ARIA Album Certifications 2014]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 31 October 2014</ref> It also reached number twenty four on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|New Zealand Albums Chart]].<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts\"/> The album was a two disc release. The first disc had 18 songs from his previous albums and two new tracks, with the second disc containing acoustic versions of ten of the songs. \"[[Who's That Girl (Guy Sebastian song)|Who's That Girl]]\" featuring US rapper [[Eve (entertainer)|Eve]], was released as the only single.<ref>[http://auspop.blogspot.com/2010/10/guy-sebastian-breaks-cover.html Guy Sebastian breaks cover]. auspOp. 25 October 2010. Retrieved 25 October 2010</ref> The dance-driven [[Electronic dance music|electro R&B]] song was a departure from Sebastian's previous pop, R&B and soul releases. Eve performed the song with Sebastian on ''The X Factor'' Grand Final.<ref name=\"One very suave Guy Sebastian\">McCabe, Kathy (22 November 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/64rIIh4uL?url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/one-very-suave-guy-sebastian/story-e6frewz0-1225957921959 One very suave Guy Sebastian]. ''The Daily Telegraph''. Archived from [http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/one-very-suave-guy-sebastian/story-e6frewz0-1225957921959 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> \"Who's That Girl\" reached number one and 5\u00d7 platinum certification in Australia, and number one and platinum in New Zealand.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"Latest Gold/Platinum Singles\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2014 Singles\"/>\n[[File:Lionel Richie and Guy Sebastian.jpg|thumb|right|[[Lionel Richie]] and Sebastian performing \"[[All Night Long (All Night)|All Night Long]]\"]]\nWith the release of ''Twenty Ten'' Sebastian had completed the terms of his original contract with [[Sony Music Australia|Sony]], but re-signed with them for another long term contract.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rITet7l?url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/artists/2010/11/23/sebastian-re-signs-with-sony/ Sebastian re-signs with Sony]. The Music Network. 23 November 2010. Archived from [http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/artists/2010/11/23/sebastian-re-signs-with-sony/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He supported [[Boyzone]] on their 2011 UK tour, and [[Lionel Richie]] on his Australian and New Zealand tour.<ref name=\"Lionel Richie and Guy Sebastian to Play A Day on the Green\">\n[https://www.webcitation.org/64rIYr4lo?url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/12966-lionel-richie-and-guy-sebastian-to-play-a-day-on-the-green Lionel Richie and Guy Sebastian to Play A Day on the Green]. Undercover. Archived from [http://www.undercover.fm/news/12966-lionel-richie-and-guy-sebastian-to-play-a-day-on-the-green the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref name=\"Tour supports confirmed\">\n[https://www.webcitation.org/64rJsFdG5?url=http://boyzonebrotheralbum.com/news.php?item=182 Boyzone Brother Tour support announcement]. Boyzonebrotheralbum.com. 7 February 2011. Archived from [http://boyzonebrotheralbum.com/news.php?item=182 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> They re-recorded Richie's 1983 single \"[[All Night Long (All Night)|All Night Long]]\" to raise money for Australian and New Zealand [[2010\u20132011 Queensland floods|flood]] and [[February 2011 Christchurch earthquake|earthquake]] relief. The track was produced by [[RedOne]].<ref>Adams, Cameron (26 February 2011). [https://www.webcitation.org/64s9A8mTV?url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/lionel-ritchie-and-guy-sebastian-have-teamed-up-to-record-a-charity-single-for-earthquake-relief/story-e6frewz0-1226012196472 Lionel Richie and Guy Sebastian have teamed up to record a charity single for earthquake relief]. ''The Daily Telegraph'', Sydney. Archived from [http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/lionel-ritchie-and-guy-sebastian-have-teamed-up-to-record-a-charity-single-for-earthquake-relief/story-e6frewz0-1226012196472 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> Richie and Sebastian performed the song together at most of the concerts on the Australian leg of the tour.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64s9hPdor?url=http://mushroomgroup.wordpress.com/2011/03/18/lionel-richie-guy-sebastian-release-duet-of-all-night-long-for-queensland-flood-christchurch-earthquake-appeals/ Lionel Richie and Guy Sebastian release duet of All Night Long for Queensland flood + Christchurch earthquake appeals]. Mushroom Group Promotions. Archived from [http://mushroomgroup.wordpress.com/2011/03/18/lionel-richie-guy-sebastian-release-duet-of-all-night-long-for-queensland-flood-christchurch-earthquake-appeals/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> It peaked at number twelve in New Zealand and number twenty six in Australia.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts\"/> Sebastian received the 2011 Australian Club Entertainment Award for best Original Music Performer, and a [[Mo Award]] for Rock Performer of the Year.<ref name=\"13th Australian Club Entertainment Awards\">[http://www.aceawards.com.au/WINNERS.php 13th Australian Club Entertainment Awards].aceawards.com.au. Retrieved 8 April 2011</ref><ref name=\"2011 Mo Award Winners\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64s9pQUit?url=http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=1882 2011 Mo Award Winners] Mo Awards Inc. Archived from [http://www.moawards.com/?page_id=1882 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> He also won the Highest Selling Single ARIA Award for \"Who's That Girl\", and received nominations for Single of the Year, Best Pop Release and Most Popular Australian Artist.<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Award nominees announced for 2011\"/><ref name=\"Winners of the 2011 ARIA Awards\"/> Sebastian continued as a judge on the 2011 ''The X Factor''. He mentored the Boys and was assisted in choosing his final three by [[Wynter Gordon]] and [[Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles|Beyonc\u00e9]]. [[Reece Mastin]] who was in his group was the winner.<ref>Casamento, Jo (21 August 2011). [https://www.webcitation.org/64snBR5Ry?url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/no-fallen-idol-20110820-1j30j.html No Fallen Idol]. ''The Sydney Morning Herald''. Archived from [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/no-fallen-idol-20110820-1j30j.html#ixzz1VqjlFvwe the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132013: ''Armageddon''===\n{{Main|Armageddon (Guy Sebastian album)}}\nIn November 2011 \"[[Don't Worry Be Happy (Guy Sebastian song)|Don't Worry Be Happy]]\", a pop song Sebastian wrote after encountering an angry motorist in Los Angeles, was released as the lead single of his seventh album ''Armageddon''.<ref>McCabe, Kathy (8 November 2011). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sA8CoOp?url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastian-takes-a-big-dip-for-the-sake-of-art/story-e6frf9hf-1226188207216 Guy Sebastian takes a big dip for the sake of art]. ''Herald Sun''. Archived from [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastian-takes-a-big-dip-for-the-sake-of-art/story-e6frf9hf-1226188207216 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> It peaked at number five and reached 4\u00d7 platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2012 Singles\"/> Sebastian spent time in the US in early 2012 working on the album, and \"[[Gold (Guy Sebastian song)|Gold]]\", an uptempo soul track, was released as the second single in May. It peaked at number ten, gaining platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2014 Singles\"/> Sebastian toured nationally during June and July to showcase new songs.<ref name=\"The Armageddon Tour\">[https://www.webcitation.org/65E7aubfR?url=http://auspop.blogspot.com.au/2012/02/touring-guy-sebastian.html TOURING : Guy Sebastian]. auspOp. 5 February 2012. Archived from [http://auspop.blogspot.com.au/2012/02/touring-guy-sebastian.html the original] on 5 February 2012.</ref> In 2012, Sebastian appeared as a judge on ''The X Factor'' for a third and final year (until 2015). He was given the Over 25s, and was assisted in selecting his final three by [[Alicia Keys]]. His contestant [[Samantha Jade]] was the winner.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6CM48aZGa?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/samantha-jade-wins-x-factor-over-the-collective-and-jason-owen/story-e6frfmyi-1226520357011 Samantha Jade wins X Factor]. news.com.au. 21 November 2012. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/samantha-jade-wins-x-factor-over-the-collective-and-jason-owen/story-e6frfmyi-1226520357011 the original] on 21 November 2012.</ref> ''Armageddon'''s third single \"[[Battle Scars]]\", an [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] ballad featuring a [[rap|hip hop rap]] by [[Lupe Fiasco]], was released in August.<ref>[http://www.guysebastian.com.au/ Battle Scars featuring Lupe Fiasco preview] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Fcqwwmkr?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/ |date=4 April 2013 }}. Guy Sebastian official site. Retrieved 2 August 2012.</ref> It debuted at number one, Sebastian's sixth number one single in Australia. He has the most number one singles for an Australian male artist in Australian music history, and is third overall for all Australian acts. Only [[Kylie Minogue]] and [[Delta Goodrem]] have achieved more.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian Equals Abba For Number 1 Hits In Australia\"/><ref>Ryan, Gavin (25 December 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/64qhVdfWa?url=http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=34665&pages= ARIA Chartifacts 27-December-2010]. Australian-charts.com. Archived from [http://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=34665&pages= the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> \"Battle Scars\" was the third-highest selling single in Australia in 2012 and the highest-selling single by an Australian act.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6DX5wVAZr?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2012.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 End Of Year Charts \u2013 Top 100 Singles 2012]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-singles-2012.htm the original] on 8 January 2013</ref> It reached 11\u00d7 platinum in 2019.<ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/> \"Battle Scars\" also reached number two and double platinum certification in New Zealand.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the NZ charts\"/><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6CSEGHOdE?url=http://nztop40.co.nz/ Official New Zealand Music Chart \u2013 26 November 2012]. Recording Industry Association New Zealand (RIANZ). Archived from [http://nztop40.co.nz/ the original] on 25 November 2012.</ref>\n\nFiasco added \"Battle Scars\" to his fourth album, ''[[Lupe Fiasco's Food & Liquor II: The Great American Rap Album Pt. 1|Food & Liquor II: The Great American Rap Album Pt. 1]]'' in countries other than Australia, and it was released as the fourth single on 28 August 2012.<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/food-liquor-ii-great-american/id561751903 US iTunes preview Food & Liquor II: The Great American Rap Album Pt. 1]. iTunes. Retrieved 28 September 2012.</ref><ref>James, Jessie (21 August 2012). [https://www.webcitation.org/6A60ZcoPz?url=http://stupiddope.com/2012/08/21/guy-sebastian-lupe-fiasco-battle-scars-music-video/ Guy Sebastian Lupe Fiasco Battle Scars]. Stupid Dope. Archived from [http://stupiddope.com/2012/08/21/guy-sebastian-lupe-fiasco-battle-scars-music-video/ the original] on 21 August 2012.</ref> He came to Australia in mid September to promote the single and the release of his album, and he and Sebastian performed \"Battle Scars\" live for the first time on ''[[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|The X Factor]]''.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6Ao4VNACK?url=http://www.killerhiphop.com/video-lupe-fiasco-guy-sebastian-perform-battle-scars-on-the-x-factor-australia/ Video: Lupe Fiasco & Guy Sebastian Perform \"Battle Scars\" On \"The X Factor Australia\"]. KillerHipHop.com. 18 September 2012. Archived from [http://www.killerhiphop.com/video-lupe-fiasco-guy-sebastian-perform-battle-scars-on-the-x-factor-australia/ the original] on 19 September 2012.</ref> They also performed the song in America on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]''.<ref>Reid, Poppy (18 September 2012). [https://www.webcitation.org/6Ao7iE4nQ?url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/artists/2012/09/18/guy-sebastian-to-perform-on-letterman/ Guy Sebastian to perform on Letterman]. The Music Network. 18 September 2012. Archived from [http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/artists/2012/09/18/guy-sebastian-to-perform-on-letterman/ the original] on 19 September 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_mkC0z-QuxY Lupe Fiasco & Guy Sebastian \u2013 Battle Scars \u2013 David Letterman 9-27-12]. YouTube. 28 September 2012. Retrieved 28 September 2012.</ref> It was used in the US in the TV promotion for the movie ''[[Red Dawn (2012 film)|Red Dawn]]''.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6Bv6FAgx7?url=http://www.thelupendblog.com/2012/10/battle-scars-featured-in-red-dawn-tv.html Battle Scars featured in Red Dawn TV Spot]. LupEnd. 29 October 2012. Archived from [http://www.thelupendblog.com/2012/10/battle-scars-featured-in-red-dawn-tv.html the original] on 4 November 2012.</ref> \"Battle Scars\" spent 20 weeks on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart, peaking at number 71.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian and Lupe Fiasco \u2013 Battle Scars\"/> It also reached number 23 on the [[Hot Digital Songs|''Billboard'' Digital Song Chart]] and number one on the R&B/Hip-Hop Digital Song Chart.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6AdtHHaog?url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/chart-search-results/singles/14118857 R&B/Hip-hop Digital Song Chart 15 September 2012]. Billboard.biz. Archived from [http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/chart-search-results/singles/14118857 the original] on 13 September 2012.</ref><ref>Adams, Cameron (11 September 2012). [https://www.webcitation.org/6E1jTceA1?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastians-aria-number-one-song-battle-scars-with-lupe-fiasco-hits-73-on-the-us-billboard-hot-100/story-e6frfn09-1226471957412 Guy Sebastian's ARIA number one song Battle Scars with Lupe Fiasco hits 73 on the US Billboard Hot 100]. news.com.au. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastians-aria-number-one-song-battle-scars-with-lupe-fiasco-hits-73-on-the-us-billboard-hot-100/story-e6frfn09-1226471957412 the original] on 29 January 2013.</ref> It has been certified platinum in the US for sales of one million.<ref name=\"Gold Platinum searchable database\"/> The song also spent 13 weeks in the top ten in Norway, including six weeks at number two, and reached 46 and gold certification in Sweden.<ref name=\"Battle Scars Norway\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/|title=Sverige Toplistan: S\u00f6k |publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]] |accessdate=16 August 2014 |format=To retrieve the certification, enter \"Guy Sebastian\" in the upper right box \"S\u00f6k\", and then click on \"Visa\" on Battle Scars |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n''[[Armageddon (Guy Sebastian album)|Armageddon]]'' was released on 12 October 2012. It reached number one in its seventh week and achieved double platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref>[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesALBUMaccreds2012.htm ARIA Charts - Accreditations - 2012 Albums]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 27 January 2013</ref> After only 12 weeks of sales the album was the ninth highest selling album in Australia in 2012, the second highest selling album by an Australian act.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6DX61P6XG?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-albums-2012.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 End Of Year Charts \u2013 Top 100 Albums 2012]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-end-of-year-charts-top-100-albums-2012.htm the original] on 8 January 2013</ref> Sebastian was nominated for three 2012 [[ARIA Music Awards|ARIA Awards]]. He received nominations for Best Pop Release and Best Male Artist for \"Battle Scars\", and \"Don't Worry Be Happy\" was nominated for Song of the Year.<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\"/> Sebastian and Fiasco performed \"Battle Scars\" at the Awards.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6CY7Rk4A0?url=http://www.ariaawards.com.au/news/46/arias-2012 2012 Winners announced]. Australian Recording Industry Association. 29 November 2012. Archived from [http://www.ariaawards.com.au/news/46/arias-2012 the original] on 29 November 2012.</ref> \"Battle Scars\" was also nominated for an American [[NAACP Image Award]] for Outstanding Duo, Group or Collaboration.<ref>Couch, Aaron (1 February 2013). [https://www.webcitation.org/6EAOYX5ir?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/naacp-image-awards-winners-announced-417553 NAACP Image Awards: Winners Announced]. ''The Hollywood Reporter''. Archived from [http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/naacp-image-awards-winners-announced-417553 the original] on 2 February 2013</ref> The fourth single \"[[Get Along (Guy Sebastian song)|Get Along]]\", a song about the harm caused by religious, cultural and racial intolerance reached number five and triple platinum certification.<ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/> The song also reached number nine and gold certification in New Zealand.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6IQ4xP985?url=http://nztop40.co.nz/ Official NZ Music Chart 29 July 2013]. Recording Industry Association of New Zealand (RIANZ). Archived from [http://nztop40.co.nz/ the original] on 27 July 2013.</ref> In early 2013 Fiasco and Sebastian continued the US promotion of \"Battle Scars\", performing on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' and ''[[Conan (talk show)|Conan]]''.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6DOUpUtTK?url=http://www.thelupendblog.com/2013/01/video-lupe-fiasco-x-guy-sebastian.html Lupe Fiasco x Guy Sebastian Perform \"Battle Scars\" on Jimmy Fallon]. thelupendblog. 3 January 2013. Archived from [http://www.thelupendblog.com/2013/01/video-lupe-fiasco-x-guy-sebastian.html the original] on 3 January 2013.</ref><ref>[http://teamcoco.com/video/lupe-fiasco-feat-guy-sebastion-battle-scars-02-13-13 Lupe Fiasco feat. Guy Sebastian \"Battle Scars\" 02/13/13] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216043908/http://teamcoco.com/video/lupe-fiasco-feat-guy-sebastion-battle-scars-02-13-13 |date=16 February 2013 }}. teamcoco.com. 14 February 2013. Retrieved 14 February 2013</ref> From March to June 2013 he toured Australia with the 47-date Get Along Tour.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian's Get Along tour dates\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6Fcqwwmkr?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/ Get Along Tour 2013]. Guy Sebastian official site. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/ the original] on 4 April 2013.</ref> Sebastian won two 2013 ARIA Awards, Best Pop Release for ''Armageddon'', and Best Live Act for the Get Along Tour. He was also nominated for Album of the Year and Best Male Act for Armageddon and Song of the Year for \"Get Along\".<ref name=\"No Idol threat\">Zuel, Bernard (2 December 2013). [https://www.webcitation.org/6LXbbvLMO?url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/no-idol-threat-as-guy-sebastian-and-jessica-mauboy-beat-curse-at-arias-20131201-2yju8.html No Idol threat as Guy Sebastian and Jessica Mauboy beat curse at ARIAs]. ''Sydney Morning Herald''. Archived from the original [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/no-idol-threat-as-guy-sebastian-and-jessica-mauboy-beat-curse-at-arias-20131201-2yju8.html#ixzz2mE2fOM] on 2 December 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6KNgUCHv6?url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/documents/FineArtsandArtisanRecipientsARIANominatedArtistsAnnounced_151013.pdf 27th ARIA Award Nominations]. Australian Recording Industry Association. 15 October 2013. Archived from [http://www.aria.com.au/pages/documents/FineArtsandArtisanRecipientsARIANominatedArtistsAnnounced_151013.pdf the original] on 15 October 2013.</ref>\n\n===2013\u20132016: ''Madness'' and Eurovision Song Contest===\n{{Main|Madness (Guy Sebastian album)}}\n\nIn October 2013 Sebastian released \"[[Like a Drum]]\", the lead single from his eighth studio album. Debuting at number four, it became his 12th top ten single in Australia, and his tenth to reach the top five.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/> It has been certified 4x platinum in Australia.<ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/> Sebastian opened for [[Taylor Swift]] on the Australian leg of her [[Red Tour]].<ref name=\"Taylor Swift Tour\">Adams, Cameron (16 May 2013). [https://www.webcitation.org/6GvAlZqYW?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastian-will-open-for-taylor-swift-on-her-stadium-tour-of-australia/story-e6frfn09-1226643385758 Guy Sebastian will open for Taylor Swift on her stadium tour of Australia]. news.com.au. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastian-will-open-for-taylor-swift-on-her-stadium-tour-of-australia/story-e6frfn09-1226643385758 the original] on 27 May 2013.</ref> \"Like a Drum\" was released in the United States, Canada, and Europe in January 2014 through [[The Cherry Party]] and [[RCA Records]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Guy Sebastian's Infectious EDM Adventure \"Like A Drum\" Gets A US Release|url=http://www.idolator.com/7501409/guy-sebastian-like-a-drum-us-release|publisher=www.idolator.com}}</ref> The song reached number 20 on the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|''Billboard'' Dance Club Chart]] and 49 and platinum certification in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/303274/guy-sebastian/chart|title=Guy Sebastian Chart history|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc |date= 30 November 2013|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian Guy Sebastian on Swedish Charts]. Sverigetopplistan archives. Hung Medien. Retrieved 28 June 2014</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/|title=Sverige Toplistan: S\u00f6k |publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]] |accessdate=13 October 2013 |format=To retrieve the certification, enter \"Guy Sebastian\" in the upper right box \"S\u00f6k\", and then click on \"Visa\" on Like A Drum |language=Swedish}}</ref> The second single, \"[[Come Home With Me (song)|Come Home With Me]]\", reached number 13 on the Aria Singles Chart and platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/> The third single, \"[[Mama Ain't Proud]]\" featuring [[2 Chainz]], peaked at number 17 and reached gold certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2014 Singles\"/> Sebastian received two 2014 ARIA nominations, Best Male Artist for \"Come Home With Me\" and Song of the Year for \"Like a Drum\".<ref name=\"2014 Aria Awards\"/> Sebastian's eighth album, ''[[Madness (Guy Sebastian album)|Madness]]'', was released on 21 November 2014 and debuted at number six and was certified gold.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Album Certifications 2014\"/> The album also reached number 34 in Sweden in 2015.<ref>[http://www.swedishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian Guy Sebastian-Madness]. swedishcharts.com. Hung Medien. Retrieved 9 June 2015.</ref>\n \n[[File:20150520 ESC 2015 Guy Sebastian 9251.jpg|thumb|right|Sebastian performing at the Eurovision Song Contest]]\nThe fourth single \"[[Linger (Guy Sebastian song)|Linger]]\" reached number 17 and platinum certification.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/> Sebastian held an arena tour in Australia in February 2015 to support the album release.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian to play Australian arenas on Madness tour 2015\">McCabe, Kathy (7 August 2014). [https://www.webcitation.org/6RraG61mJ?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastian-to-play-australian-arenas-on-madness-tour-2015/story-e6frfn29-1227015718069 Guy Sebastian to play Australian arenas on Madness tour 2015]. news.com.au. Archived from the original [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/guy-sebastian-to-play-australian-arenas-on-madness-tour-2015/story-e6frfn29-1227015718069] on 16 August 2014.</ref> \"Like a Drum\" received 2015 [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA]] nominations for Pop Work of the Year and Most Played Australian Work.<ref>.[https://www.webcitation.org/6WcVynsG2?url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2015/02/26/peer-voted-apra-music-awards-name-2015-nominees/ Peer-Voted APRA Music Awards Name 2015 Nominees]. themusic.com.au. 26 February 2015. Archived from [http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2015/02/26/peer-voted-apra-music-awards-name-2015-nominees/  the original] on 26 February 2015.</ref> Sebastian was chosen as the Australian entrant in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015]], making him the first artist to represent Australia in the competition. He performed the song \"[[Tonight Again]]\", and placed fifth in the competition overall.<ref name=\"Eurovision 2015: Sweden's Mans Zelmerlow wins; Australia's Guy Sebastian fifth\"/> \"Tonight Again\" debuted at number 12 in Australia.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/> It also charted at number five in Iceland, 16 in Austria, 22 in Sweden and reached the top 50 of the German and Swiss charts.<ref name=\"ACharts.US\"/><ref name=\"Iceland\"/><ref>[http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Guy+Sebastian&titel=Tonight+Again&cat=s Guy Sebastian - Tonight Again]. AustrianCharts.at. Retrieved 4 June 2015.</ref> It achieved gold certification in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/|title=Sverige Toplistan: S\u00f6k |publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]] |accessdate=29 September 2015 |format=To retrieve the certification, enter \"Guy Sebastian\" in the upper right box \"S\u00f6k\", and then click on \"Visa\" on Tonight Again |language=Swedish}}</ref> Sebastian toured in Europe in August and September, performing in Sweden, Germany, Norway and The Netherlands.<ref name=\"European Tour\">Gallagher, Robyn (11 August 2015).[https://www.webcitation.org/6dpnzrWBS?url=http://wiwibloggs.com/2015/08/11/australia-guy-sebastian-announces-european-tour/100934/ Guy Sebastian Announces Madness European Tour]. wiwiBlogs.com. Archived from [http://wiwibloggs.com/2015/08/11/australia-guy-sebastian-announces-european-tour/100934/ the original] on 17 December 2015.</ref> He was nominated for 2015 ARIA Award for Best Male Artist for \"Tonight Again\".<ref>Baroni, Nastassia (7 October 2015).[https://www.webcitation.org/6c5aT9Kwd?url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/courtney-barnett-hermitude-tame-impala-lead-2015-aria-award-nominations/ Courtney Barnett, Hermitude, Tame Impala Lead 2015 ARIA Award Nominations]. musicfeeds.com.au. Archived from [http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/courtney-barnett-hermitude-tame-impala-lead-2015-aria-award-nominations/ the original] on 7 October 2015.</ref> He returned to the judging panel of Australia's ''[[The X Factor (Australian TV series)|The X Factor]]'' after a two-year absence.<ref name=\"Chris Isaak and James Blunt: Meet the new X Factor guys\"/> In November 2015 he released \"[[Black & Blue (Guy Sebastian song)|Black & Blue]]\". The song reached number 17, and achieved platinum certification.<ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/> In January and February 2016 he held a 35 date Australian regional tour.<ref name=\"You...Me...Us Tour\">.Cashmere, Paul. (12 November 2015).[https://www.webcitation.org/6d7iKnzd1?url=http://www.noise11.com/news/music-news-guy-sebastian-to-head-out-on-extensive-australian-tour-for-2016-20151112 Guy Sebastian to Head Out On Extensive Australian Tour in 2016]. Noise11. Archived from [http://www.noise11.com/news/music-news-guy-sebastian-to-head-out-on-extensive-australian-tour-for-2016-20151112 the original] on 17 November 2015.</ref> Sebastian received 2016 ARIA Award nominations for Best Male Artist and Best Video for \"Black & Blue\".<ref name=\"2016 Aria Awards\"/>\n\n===2016\u20132017: ''Part 1'' EP and ''Conscious''===\n{{main|Part 1 (EP)|Conscious (Guy Sebastian album)}}\nIn late 2016 Sebastian released two singles, \"[[Candle (Guy Sebastian song)|Candle]]\" which peaked at 59, and \"[[Set in Stone (song)|Set in Stone]]\" which reached number 11.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/><ref>[http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20160920-0001/Issue1386.pdf The ARIA Report \u2013 Issue #1386]. [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] Retrieved 12 November 2016</ref> It has been certified platinum.<ref>[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupagesSingleAccreds2017.htm ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 2015 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 14 June 2017</ref> Sebastian released ''[[Part 1 (EP)|Part 1]]'' EP in December 2016. It was released digitally on 2 December, and peaked at number 31 on the ARIA Album Chart.<ref>[http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/albums-chart ARIA Albums Chart]. ARIA Charts. Retrieved 10 December 2016.</ref> The physical cd was released on 16 December.<ref>Ryan Gavin (16 December 2016).[http://www.noise11.com/news/new-music-releases-for-16-december-2016-20161216 New Music Releases For 16 December 2016].Noise11 . Retrieved 16 December 2016.</ref> A third single, \"[[Mind on You (Guy Sebastian song)|Mind On You]]\", did not chart. In March and April 2017 Sebastian toured the Australian eastern states to preview songs from his next album.<ref name=\"The Sub-Conscious tour\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6p1QXKBKG?url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2017/02/06/guy-sebastian-unveils-intimate-headline-dates-to-preview-new-album/ Guy Sebastian Unveils Intimate Headline Dates To Preview New Album] the music.com.au. 6 February 2017. Archived from [http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2017/02/06/guy-sebastian-unveils-intimate-headline-dates-to-preview-new-album/ the original] on 17 March 2017</ref> In September 2017, Sebastian released the single \"[[High On Me]]\" and announced his album ''[[Conscious (Guy Sebastian album)|Conscious]]'' would be released on 3 November 2017. He also announced a November tour of the mainland capital cities and Newcastle.<ref name=\"Conscious\">[https://www.webcitation.org/6tAQjxCBa?url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/09/guy-sebastian-confirms-conscious-announces-tour/ Guy Sebastian confirms Conscious; announces tour] auspOp. 1 September 2017. Archived from [https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/09/guy-sebastian-confirms-conscious-announces-tour/ the original] on 2 September 2017</ref> \"Keep Me Coming Back\" and \"Vesuvius\" were released as promotional singles from ''[[Conscious (Guy Sebastian album)|Conscious]]'', ahead of the album release.  It was also confirmed \"[[Set in Stone (song)|Set in Stone]]\" was also included in the album. \"Set in Stone\" was nominated for an ARIA Award for Song of the Year, Sebastian's 28th Aria nomination.<ref>[http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2017/10/10/the-full-aria-award-2017-nominees-list-is-here/ The Full ARIA Award 2017 Nominees List Is Here] themusic.com.au. 10 October 2017. Retrieved 2 September 2017</ref> \"Bloodstone\", the second official single peaked at number 59 and was certified platinum, with ''Conscious'' debuting at number four, Sebastian's ninth top ten album.<ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/><ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ninth studio album===\nOn 4 October 2018, Sebastian released \"[[Before I Go]]\", the lead single from his upcoming 9th studio album. It peaked at number 43 and has been certified platinum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bofsq46lz5D/|title=@guysebastian on Instagram: \"Surprise! I have a new single coming your way on November 2nd. Pre-save is available from tomorrow. #BeforeIGo \ud83c\udfc3\ud83c\udffd\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=15 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2019 Singles\"/>  He became a coach on the 2019 season of [[The Voice Australia]].  Sebastian was made a [[Member of the Order of Australia]] (AM) in the [[2019 Queen's Birthday Honours (Australia)|2019 Queen's Birthday Honours]] in recognition of his \"significant service to the music industry and charitable initiatives\".<ref name=\"Order of Australia\"/> In June 2019 he released the single \"[[Choir (Guy Sebastian song)|Choir]]\", which has reached number seven, his 22nd top twenty single in Australia, and his 13th top ten.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian in the Australian Charts\"/> The single has been certified triple platinum.<ref name=\"ARIA Accreditations - 2020 Singles\">[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupagesSinglesAccreds2020.htm ARIA Accreditations \u2013 2020 Singles]. Australian Recording Industry Association (ARIA). Retrieved 9 February 2020.</ref> Sebastian toured Australia in September and October with his Ridin' With You Tour.<ref name=\"Ridin' With You Tour\">Fuamoli, Sosefina (10 June 2019)[https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/guy-sebastian-announces-september-australian-tour/ Guy Sebastian Announces September Australian Tour]. Music Feeds. Retrieved 11 June 2019.</ref> On 1 October 2019, it was announced that Sebastian would host the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2019]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://themusicnetwork.com/2019-aria-awards-host-guy-sebastian/|title=Guy Sebastian \u2018pumped & honoured\u2019 to host 2019 ARIA Awards |website= themusicnetwork|date=1 October 2019 |accessdate=1 October 2019 }}</ref> He received 2019 ARIA Award nominations for Best Male Artist and Best Pop Release, and won for Best Video and Song of the Year for \"Choir\".<ref name=\"Here are all the winners from the 2019 ARIA Awards\"/>\n\n==Artistry==\n\n===Musical style and influences===\nSebastian cites a number of musicians as his musical influences, including [[Sam Cooke]], [[Otis Redding]], [[Donny Hathaway]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Chicago (band)|Chicago]], and [[Boyz II Men]].<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sAEaj9X?url=http://thecelebritycafe.com/interview/guy-sebastian-australian-idol-x-factor-08-23-2010 Guy Sebastian: From 'Australian Idol' to 'X Factor']. The Celebrity Cafe. 23 August 2010. Archived from [http://thecelebritycafe.com/interview/guy-sebastian-australian-idol-x-factor-08-23-2010 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> His music has crossed many genres, including [[Pop music|pop]], [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[funk]], [[Soul music|smokey soul]], [[Gospel music|gospel]], [[jazz]], [[pop rock]], [[Memphis soul]] [[Cover version|covers]], [[1960s in music#R&B and Soul|'60s soul/pop]] and [[Electronic dance music|electro R&B]].<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian biography\"/><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sALzoc6?url=http://www.uctv.fm/site/play/47-Guy-Sebastian-Undercover-Interviews Undercover interviews Guy Sebastian]. uctv.com.fm. Archived from [http://www.uctv.fm/site/play/47-Guy-Sebastian-Undercover-Interviews the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> While Sebastian's first three albums showed elements of soul, it was ''[[The Memphis Album]]'' which consolidated his reputation as a soul musician. Reviewers almost unanimously agreed he had captured the spirit and essence of the Memphis soul classics.<ref name=\"The Memphis Album Reviews\"/> It was the critical and public reception for ''The Memphis Album'' which gave Sebastian the confidence to stay with the soul genre for his fifth album ''Like It Like That''. In an interview with ''[[The Age]]'' he said he was told early in his career, \"If you self-indulge and just do what you're into, you're going to corner your market. Soul music isn't big here.\" but \"the most comfortable I've ever felt in the studio was during ''The Memphis Album''. And the success of that prompted me to make a record like this one. Because I realised that this isn't obscure music.\"<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sLa1vZq?url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/music/2009/10/15/1255195865959.html?page=fullpage Like him like that]. ''The Age''. 18 October 2009. Archived from [http://www.theage.com.au/news/entertainment/music/2009/10/15/1255195865959.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Telegraph]]'' music editor Kathy McCabe said: \"Sometimes it takes four records, with a detour into \"concepts\" covers territory to find where you fit. Sebastian has found his niche with ''Like It Like That'', which expertly balances the line between radio friendly pop and classic soul\".<ref>McCabe, Kathy. (30 October 2009). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sAbEDDe?url=http://gsinfo-soulfan.blogspot.com/2010/07/like-it-like-that-review-daily_10.html Like It Like That review]. blogspot.com. (Source: ''The Daily Telegraph''). Archived from [http://gsinfo-soulfan.blogspot.com/2010/07/like-it-like-that-review-daily_10.html the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> [[Paul Cashmere]] from Undercover wrote: \"By covering the classics on ''The Memphis Album'' Guy Sebastian discovered Guy Sebastian. [...] If ''The Memphis Album'' was Guy's initiation into becoming a Soul Man then ''Like It Like That'' is the graduation.\"<ref>Cashmere, Paul (22 October 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20091022183244/http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=9301_Guy_Sebastian_Earns_His_Soul_Man_Stripes Guy Sebastian Earns His Soul Man Stripes]. undercover.com.au. Archived from [https://archive.today/20121230210330/http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=9301 the original] on 22 October 2009.</ref> In an interview for the release of his seventh album ''[[Armageddon (Guy Sebastian album)|Armageddon]]'', Sebastian spoke of how much ''The Memphis Album'' still influences his music: \"I got to work with some people who were instrumental in shaping the careers of artists who heavily influence me. Artists like Otis Redding, [[Sam & Dave]] and Sam Cooke. Being entrenched in that sort of environment really caused me to go 'You know what dude. Do what you want to do. Do what comes natural to you'. [...] From that Memphis thing a few years ago it's always going to start with me being true to who I want to be and what I enjoy singing.\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZyPY5gtqZyU Guy Sebastian Interview - Armageddon]. YouTube. 28 October 2012. Retrieved on 15 December 2014.</ref>\n\n===Songwriting and production===\nSebastian began writing songs before entering ''Australian Idol''. \"[[All I Need Is You]]\", the second single from his debut album ''[[Just as I Am (Guy Sebastian album)|Just as I Am]]'' was written when he was a teenager, and fine-tuned during his time on ''Idol''.<ref name=\"Angels Brought Me Here: The Official Biography\"/> He also wrote gospel songs for his church during his teenage years. One of them, \"Adore\", was included in their 2004 album ''Paradise Live: Adore''.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sAlfKGc?url=http://www.cylist.com/List/406350774/ Paradise Live: Adore CD Track Listing]. cylist.com. Archived from [http://www.cylist.com/List/406350774/ the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian wrote or co-wrote most of the songs on his albums ''[[Beautiful Life (Guy Sebastian album)|Beautiful Life]]'' and ''[[Closer to the Sun (Guy Sebastian album)|Closer to the Sun]]'', and all the tracks on his albums ''[[Like It Like That (album)|Like It Like That]]'' and ''[[Armageddon (Guy Sebastian album)|Armageddon]]''. In an article in ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]'', Kathy McCabe said of his songwriting skills, \"Sebastian has matured into a genuine hitmaker, his gift with melody so finely-honed he can pretty much punch out a catchy number in his sleep.\"<ref>McCabe, Kathy (28 December 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sFbmX3L?url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/songs-you-cant-get-out-of-your-head/story-fn6ccwsa-1225966584019 Songs you can't get out of your head]. ''The Daily Telegraph''. Archived from [http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/songs-you-cant-get-out-of-your-head/story-fn6ccwsa-1225966584019 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> Jamie Horne wrote in ''The Border Mail'', \"The inaugural winner's longevity [...] can be attributed to the fact that he's an accomplished musician and songwriter\" and AllMusic reviewer Jon O'Brien said, \"it's a testament to his vocal abilities and songwriting skills that, unlike many of his fellow winners, he's remained popular enough to see out his rather ambitious Sony contract [...] a subtle and natural progression with each album, explains why he's managed to survive once the show's publicity machine died down.\"<ref>Horne, Jamie (24 November 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/652vEnlb2?url=http://www.bordermail.com.au/blogs/music-reviews/guy-sebastian-twenty-ten-sony/2007189.aspx Guy Sebastian \u2013 Twenty Ten (Sony)]. ''The Border Mail''. Archived from yo [http://www.bordermail.com.au/blogs/music-reviews/guy-sebastian-twenty-ten-sony/2007189.aspx the original] on 29 January 2012.</ref><ref>O'Brien, Jon. [https://www.webcitation.org/653PGgF0c?url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/twenty-ten-greatest-hits-r2081576/review Twenty Ten: Greatest Hits]. allmusic.com. Archived from [http://www.allmusic.com/album/twenty-ten-greatest-hits-r2081576/review the original] on 29 January 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2008 \"[[Receive the Power]]\", a gospel song written by Sebastian and Gary Pinto, was chosen as the official anthem for the Roman Catholic Church's XXIII [[World Youth Day]].<ref name=\"Australian Idol Wrote World Youth Day Anthem\">[https://www.webcitation.org/64sAqaPg0?url=http://famvin.org/en/2007/05/17/australian-idol-wrote-world-youth-day-anthem/ Australian Idol Wrote World Youth Day Anthem]. famvin.org. 17 May 2007. Archived from [http://famvin.org/en/archive/australian-idol-wrote-world-youth-day-anthem the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> \"[[Art of Love (song)|Art of Love]]\", co-written by Adam Reilly, was shortlisted for the [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA]] Song of the Year in 2010.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sAyQyZY?url=http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/voting-now-open-for-apras-song-of-the-year-award/ Voting Now Open For APRA\u2019s \u2018Song Of The Year\u2019 Award]. musicfeeds.com.au. 18 March 2010. Archived from [http://musicfeeds.com.au/news/voting-now-open-for-apras-song-of-the-year-award/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> \"[[All to Myself (Guy Sebastian song)|All to Myself]]\", written with Carl Dimataga, and \"[[Who's That Girl (Guy Sebastian song)|Who's That Girl]]\" were shortlised for the 2011 APRA Song of the Year, with \"Who's That Girl\" winning the APRA Award for Urban Work of the Year.<ref>Treuen, Jason (24 March 2011). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sB444IC?url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/industry/2011/03/24/apra-reveals-song-of-the-year-contenders-award-details/ APRA reveals Song of the Year contenders]. The Music Network. Archived from [http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-news/industry/2011/03/24/apra-reveals-song-of-the-year-contenders-award-details/ the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref><ref>Kelton, Sam (22 June 2011). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sBA89IO?url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/our-guy-his-girl-crowned-the-best/story-fn6bqvxz-1226079584103 Our Guy, his girl crowned the best]. ''Adelaide Now''. Archived from [http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/ipad/our-guy-his-girl-crowned-the-best/story-fn6bqvxz-1226079584103 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref> \"[[Don't Worry Be Happy (Guy Sebastian song)|Don't Worry Be Happy]]\" was shortlisted for the 2012 APRA Song of the Year.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/66LLEaCWN?url=http://www.vmusic.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/latest-news/australian-song-of-the-year-finalists-announced Australian Song of the Year finalists announced]. V Music. Archived from [http://www.vmusic.com.au/pages/main-menu/news/latest-news/australian-song-of-the-year-finalists-announced the original] on 22 March 2012.</ref> \"[[Battle Scars]]\" won the R&B/Hip category in the 2013 International Songwriting Competition. \"[[Get Along (Guy Sebastian song)|Get Along]]\" was a finalist in the Pop/Top 40 category, and was awarded an honourable mention.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6Emjb3w8q?url=http://songwritingcompetition.com/winners Finalists]. International Songwriting Competition 2013. Archived from [http://songwritingcompetition.com/winners the original] on 28 February 2013.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6GHQVulj8?url=http://www.songwritingcompetition.com/winners International Songwriting Competition Winners]. International Songwriting Competition. Archived from [http://www.songwritingcompetition.com/winners the original] on 30 April 2013.</ref> \"Get Along\" was also one of the final five nominees for the 2013 APRA Song of the Year.<ref>Adams, Cameron (23 May 2013). [https://www.webcitation.org/6GpAG5MHV?url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/tame-impala-and-guy-sebastian-vie-for-apra-song-of-the-year-honour/story-fni0bvjn-1226649127165 Tame Impala and Guy Sebastian vie for APRA Song of the Year honour]. ''Herald Sun''. 23 May 2013. Archived from [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/tame-impala-and-guy-sebastian-vie-for-apra-song-of-the-year-honour/story-fni0bvjn-1226649127165 the original] on 23 May 2013.</ref> \"[[Set in Stone (song)|Set in Stone]] was shortlisted for the 2017 APRA Song of the Year, and \"[[Black & Blue (Guy Sebastian song)|Black & Blue]]\" was nominated for Pop Work of the Year.<ref>.[https://www.webcitation.org/6p1OMOG8Z?url=http://apraamcos.com.au/news/2017/march/2017-apra-music-award-nominees-announced/ 2017 APRA Music Award Nominees Announced]. APRA AMCOS. 15 March 2017. Archived from [http://apraamcos.com.au/news/2017/january/ab-original-and-flume-lead-2017-apra-song-of-the-year-top-20/ the original] on 17 March 2013.</ref><ref>.[https://www.webcitation.org/6o14R190v?url=http://apraamcos.com.au/news/2017/january/ab-original-and-flume-lead-2017-apra-song-of-the-year-top-20/ A.B. Original and Flume lead 2017 APRA Song of the Year Top 20]. APRA AMCOS. January 2017. Archived from [http://apraamcos.com.au/news/2017/january/ab-original-and-flume-lead-2017-apra-song-of-the-year-top-20/ the original] on 17 March 2013.</ref>\n\nSebastian has a worldwide, long term publishing agreement with [[Universal Music Publishing Group|Universal Music Publishing]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100525120442/http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/musiccreators/musicpublishers/publisherheadlines.aspx Publisher Headlines]. Apra-amcos.com.au. December 2009. Archived from [http://www.apra-amcos.com.au/MusicCreators/MusicPublishers/PublisherHeadlines.aspx the original] on 25 May 2010.</ref> He has written songs for other artists, including co-writing \"Dot Com\", a song performed by [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]] on ''Rhythm City Volume One: Caught Up''.<ref>Browne, Sally (23 June 2012). [https://www.webcitation.org/6BHVMC9LE?url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/life/whatson/guy-sebastian-is-just-an-ordinary-guy/story-fn8zv21o-1226404406139 Guy Sebastian is just an ordinary guy]. ''Courier Mail''. Archived from [http://www.couriermail.com.au/life/whatson/guy-sebastian-is-just-an-ordinary-guy/story-fn8zv21o-1226404406139 the original] on 9 October 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.songlyrics.com/usher/dot-com-lyrics/ Usher Dot.com lyrics]. songlyrics.com. Retrieved 18 October 2012.</ref> He also has an interest in production and co-produced ''The Memphis Album'' with [[Steve Cropper]]. He has his own recording studio, ''Cooper Lane Studio'', where he produces and engineers some of his music, and which is also used by other musicians.<ref>Stward, Andy (17 March 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/655b0nODL?url=http://www.audiotechnology.com.au/magazine/at73-out-now/ Feature \u2013 Oh my god. It's Guy Sebastian]. Audio Technology Magazine, issue 73. Archived from [http://www.audiotechnology.com.au/magazine/at73-out-now/ the original] on 31 January 2012.</ref> He produced a song called \"Think of Me\" for 2009 ''Australian Idol'' [[Stan Walker]]'s debut album, as well as playing most of the musical instruments on the track.<ref>Adams, Cameron (10 December 2009). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sG266JY?url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/review-australian-idols-stan-walkers-debut-album-introducing-stan-walker/story-e6frf9hf-1225809137824 Australian Idol's Stan Walker's debut album]. ''Herald Sun''. Archived from [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/review-australian-idols-stan-walkers-debut-album-introducing-stan-walker/story-e6frf9hf-1225809137824 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\n==Notable performances==\nWorld Youth Day, July 2008: \"[[Receive the Power]]\" a song written by Sebastian and [[Gary Pinto]] was chosen as the official anthem for the [[Roman Catholic Church]]'s XXIII [[World Youth Day]] (WYD08) held in Sydney in 2008.<ref name=\"Australian Idol Wrote World Youth Day Anthem\"/> The song also features the vocals of [[Paulini Curuenavuli]].<ref>[http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&VideoID=56420751 Receive the Power WYD08 Theme Song] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20121229170931/http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&VideoID=56420751 |date=29 December 2012 }}. Myspace Videos. Retrieved 20 June 2009.</ref> \"Receive the Power\" was released in English and also an international version with the chorus in English and verses in Italian, Spanish and French. It was used extensively throughout the six days of World Youth Day in July 2008, and also in the television coverage which went around the world. Sebastian and Curuenavuli performed both the English and International versions at the final Mass at Randwick Race Course on 20 July which was attended by 400,000 people.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian biography\"/><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64smxVSRN?url=http://www.catholic.org/wyd08/story.php?id=28655 400,000 Faithful for World Youth Day Final Mass]. Catholic Online. 20 July 2008. Archived from [http://www.catholic.org/wyd08/story.php?id=28655 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> They also performed \"Receive the Power\" at the Pope's Farewell.<ref name=\"Pope personally thanks WYD08 Volunteers\"/>\n[[File:Guy Sebastian and Olivia Newton-John at State Theatre.jpg|thumb|right|Guy Sebastian and [[Olivia Newton-John]] performing \"[[Summer Nights (John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John song)|Summer Nights]]\" at the Olivia Newton-John & Friends Concert]]\n[[Olivia Newton-John]] & Friends Concert, September 2008: This concert was held at the State Theatre in Sydney to raise funds for Newton-John's Cancer and Wellness Centre Appeal. Sebastian was chosen to sing a duet with Newton-John. They sang her iconic hit from ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]'', \"[[Summer Nights (John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John song)|Summer Nights]]\".<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64snGLYOA?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/olivia-newton-johns-the-one-guy-sebastian-wants/story-e6frfmqr-1111117629322 Olivia Newton John's the one Guy Sebastian wants]. ''The Daily Telegraph''. 1 October 2008. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/olivia-newton-johns-the-one-guy-sebastian-wants/story-e6frfmqr-1111117629322 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\nOscar Haven \u2013 Los Angeles, February 2009: Sebastian was a headline act at an Oscar Haven party hosted by Stardust Pictures and [[Jamie Kennedy]].<ref>Davalos, Adriana. [https://www.webcitation.org/64soV3Lpy?url=http://www.lasplash.com/publish/Entertainment_Celebrity_Gift_Suites/Haven_Pre-Oscars_2009_Gift_House_Review_printer.php Haven Pre-Oscars 2009 Gift House Review]. lasplash.com. Archived from [http://www.lasplash.com/publish/Entertainment_Celebrity_Gift_Suites/Haven_Pre-Oscars_2009_Gift_House_Review_printer.php the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> Haven is held during Oscar week and invitees include Film Academy nominees as well as actors and insiders from film, television and music industries.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64soZvQYp?url=http://www.24-7pressrelease.com/press-release/worldcharms-participates-in-the-oscars-week-haven-swag-event-87394.php WorldCharms Participates in the Oscars Week Haven Swag Event]. 24-7pressrelease.com. 13 February 2009. Archived from [http://www.24-7pressrelease.com/press-release/worldcharms-participates-in-the-oscars-week-haven-swag-event-87394.php the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\n9th Annual NON-COMMvention \u2013 Philadelphia, May 2009: Sebastian performed with [[Steve Cropper]] and [[David Ryan Harris]] at the 9th Annual NON-COMMvention.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sohtkxp?url=http://xpn.org/allaboutthemusic/the-derek-trucks-band-and-guy-sebastian-featuring-steve-cropper-played-xpns-free-at-noon-today-2078 The Derek Trucks Band and Guy Sebastian featuring Steve Cropper Played XPN's at Noon]. wxpn.org. 29 May 2009. Archived from [http://xpn.org/allaboutthemusic/the-derek-trucks-band-and-guy-sebastian-featuring-steve-cropper-played-xpns-free-at-noon-today-2078 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> The event is the premier annual conference for North America's non-commercial Triple A radio.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64spJ296T?url=http://xpn.org/allaboutthemusic/radio-video-33-the-2009-noncommvention-2097 Radio video #33 \u2013 The 2009 NonCOMMvention]. wxpn.org. 8 June 2009. Archived from [http://xpn.org/allaboutthemusic/radio-video-33-the-2009-noncommvention-2097 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\nAustralian launch of ''[[Michael Jackson's This Is It]]'' DVD, March 2010: Sebastian and [[Delta Goodrem]] were chosen by the Jackson estate to perform at the Australian launch of ''This Is It''.<ref>Adams, Cameron (17 February 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/64spPEVqc?url=http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/music/delta-goodrem-strips-things-back-to-basics-for-next-album/story-e6freqgx-1225831718744 Delta Goodrem strips things back to basics for next album]. ''Courier Mail''. Archived from [http://www.couriermail.com.au/entertainment/music/delta-goodrem-strips-things-back-to-basics-for-next-album/story-e6freqgx-1225831718744 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> They performed \"[[Earth Song]]\". The invitation only event was attended by the film's director [[Kenny Ortega]] and Jackson's brother [[Jackie Jackson]]<ref>[http://www.take40.com/news/18500/sydney's-all-star-tribute-to-michael-jackson's-'this-is-it'! Sydney's All Star Tribute to Michael Jackson's 'This Is It'!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013224225/http://www.take40.com/news/18500/sydney%27s-all-star-tribute-to-michael-jackson%27s-%27this-is-it%27%21 |date=13 October 2013 }}. Take40. 3 March 2010. Retrieved 11 March 2010.</ref>\n\n[[Oprah Winfrey]]'s official welcome to Sydney and wrap up party, December 2010: Sebastian was the guest performer at an event at Sydney's Botanical Gardens to officially welcome Oprah Winfrey and her American audience members to Australia.<ref>Byrnes, Holly (13 December 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/65C02SzRj?url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/true-blue-oprah-keeps-it-real-with-backyard-barbecue-and-vb/story-e6frfmyi-1225969843923 True blue Oprah keeps it real with backyard barbecue and VB]. news.com.au. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/true-blue-oprah-keeps-it-real-with-backyard-barbecue-and-vb/story-e6frfmyi-1225969843923 the original] on 3 February 2012.</ref> Winfrey was in Australia to record two of her shows at the [[Sydney Opera House]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kd1dpJ4e02A Excerpt from Network 10 News coverage on Oprah's Australian visit]. YouTube. Retrieved 2 January 2011.</ref> Sebastian sang for Winfrey a second time when she requested he perform at her private crew wrap-up party.<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian sings at Oprah's private party\"/><ref>Prior, David (24 December 2010). [https://www.webcitation.org/65By6F0nd?url=http://www.2ue.com.au/blogs/2ue-blog/guy-sebastian-on-oprahs-charms/20101224-196t0.html Guy Sebastian on Oprah's charms]. 2UE Fairfax Media. Archived from [http://www.2ue.com.au/blogs/2ue-blog/guy-sebastian-on-oprahs-charms/20101224-196t0.html the original] on 3 February 2012.</ref>\n\n[[Australia Week|G'Day USA]], January 2011 and 2012: G'Day USA is an annual two-week program designed to showcase Australian business capabilities, and is the largest foreign country promotion held in the US.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sptHKlW?url=http://www.getfarming.com.au/pages/farming/news_view.php?nId=11010063 G'Day USA promotes Australia]. Get Farming Australia. 14 January 2011. Archived from [http://www.getfarming.com.au/pages/farming/news_view.php?nId=11010063 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian and the [[Australian Girls Choir|Qantas Choir]] were the entertainers at the 2011 Black Tie Gala in Los Angeles. Sebastian performed his own songs and also a medley of [[Bee Gees]] songs prior to [[Barry Gibb]] being honoured for excellence in Music at the event.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sq0x4Np?url=http://www.3aw.com.au/blogs/donna-demaio-gossip-blog/donna-demaio-says-gday-from-la/20110123-1a0zj.html Donna Demaio says G'Day from LA]. 3aw.com.au. 23 January 2011. Archived from [http://www.3aw.com.au/blogs/donna-demaio-gossip-blog/donna-demaio-says-gday-from-la/20110123-1a0zj.html the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> During G'Day USA 2012 he performed at the American Australian Association Black Tie Gala in New York and the Australian American Chamber of Commerce Gala in Houston Texas.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64y31PWbs?url=http://www.thesearchengine.net/page/2012/01/01/e9b314400272264fad1a5ce7f572a9e8.html Black Tie Gala New York].thesearchengine.net. Archived from [http://www.thesearchengine.net/page/2012/01/01/e9b314400272264fad1a5ce7f572a9e8.html the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64y1ks25x?url=http://www.aacc-houston.org/australia-week/australia-day-gala/overview Join us in celebrating the dramatic and diverse wonders of this amazing Land Down Under]. aacc-houston.org. Archived from [http://www.aacc-houston.org/australia-week/australia-day-gala/overview the original] on 25 January 2012.</ref>\n\nGrammy week \u2013 Los Angeles, February 2011: During Grammy week each year there are many events leading up to the [[Grammy Award]]s night.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/655dwGNAK?url=http://www.grammy.com/news/oh-what-a-week Oh What a week] grammy.com. 4 February 2011. Archived from [http://www.grammy.com/news/oh-what-a-week the original] on 31 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian was invited to perform at two of these events in 2011. He performed at [[The Black Eyed Peas]] Peapod Benefit Concert which was attended by musicians, DJ's, philanthropists, Hollywood celebrities and industry executives.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sq9FJ6T?url=http://cmpr.net/press-releases/2011/02/black-eyed-peas-7th-annual-peapod-benefit-concert-gave-everyone-time-their-li The Black Eyed Peas 7th Annual Peapod Benefit Concert Gave Everyone \"The Time Of Their Life\"]. cmpr.net. Archived from [http://cmpr.net/press-releases/2011/02/black-eyed-peas-7th-annual-peapod-benefit-concert-gave-everyone-time-their-li the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> He also performed at the [[The Roots|Roots]] Pre Grammy Jam Session. The Roots are a [[Grammy Award]] winning [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[neo soul]] American band. During Grammy week they hold a [[jam session]] and invite other musicians to perform with them. Their 2011 jam session was hosted by [[Jimmy Fallon]] and other performers included [[Sara Bareilles]], [[Lalah Hathaway]], [[Booker T. Jones]] and [[Chaka Khan]].<ref>Marino, Kelly (13 February 2011). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sqDxTKf?url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1657826/20110213/index.jhtml Roots Host Genre-Spanning, Star-Studded Pre-Grammy Jam Session] vh1.com. Archived from [http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1657826/20110213/index.jhtml the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\nCHOGM 2011 Opening Ceremony \u2013 [[Perth]], [[Western Australia]] October 2011: Sebastian performed \"Agents of Change\", a song written by him especially for the event, at the opening ceremony of the biannual Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting (CHOGM). In attendance at the ceremony were [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]], [[Julia Gillard|Prime Minister Julia Gillard]], the Secretary-General of the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] and heads of government from all 53 Commonwealth nations.<ref name=\"Queen welcomes 54 countries to CHOGM\"/>\n\nThe GRAMMY Foundation's 15th Annual Music Preservation Project \u2013 Los Angeles, February 2013: Held each year during Grammy Week, in 2013 the event was \"Play It Forward: A Celebration Of Music's Evolution And Influencers\". It explored the history of legendary influencers in music, the music they inspired and their impact on the American cultural landscape. [[Lupe Fiasco]] and Sebastian were chosen to perform \"[[Battle Scars]]\" as the finale of the concert. Other performers included [[Dionne Warwick]], [[LeAnn Rimes]] and [[Ed Sheeran]].<ref>Thomas, Belinda (8 February 2013). Lupe Fiasco & Guy Sebastian performs 'Battle Scars' for Grammy Foundation]. examiner.com</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Guy Sebastian ARIA 2013.jpg|thumb|Jules and Guy Sebastian, [[ARIA Music Awards of 2013|ARIA Awards]], December 2013]]\nIn late 2007 after eight years of courtship Sebastian and girlfriend Jules Egan became engaged. They were married in Manly, Sydney on 17 May 2008.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sqRu0Uq?url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/national/guy-idolises-his-new-wife/story-e6frf7l6-1111116370432 Guy idolises his new wife]. ''Sunday Herald Sun''. 18 May 2008. Archived from [http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,23715607-662,00.html the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> They have two sons, Hudson (born 2012) and Archer (born 2014).<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/6KyNIpJhl?url=http://celebrities.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=1157749&showcomments=true Guy Sebastian and wife Jules expecting second child]. ninemsn. Archived from [http://celebrities.ninemsn.com.au/blog.aspx?blogentryid=1157749&showcomments=true the original] on 8 November 2013.</ref><ref>Hull, Christian (19 April 2014).[https://www.webcitation.org/6OwEp0xUj?url=http://www.safm.com.au/scoopla/music/blog/2014/4/guy-sebastian-welcomes-a-baby-boy/ Guy Sebastian Welcomes a Baby Boy!]. safm.com.au. Archived from [http://www.safm.com.au/scoopla/music/blog/2014/4/guy-sebastian-welcomes-a-baby-boy/ the original] on 19 April 2014.</ref>. \n\n==Charitable work==\n[[File:Guy Sebastian on Cover of World Vision Magazine 2005.jpg|thumb|left|[[World Vision Australia]] Magazine. Dec 2005]]Throughout his career Sebastian has had a strong commitment to charity. He has been an ambassador for the Ronald McDonald House charities, and is currently an ambassador for the [[Australian Red Cross]] and Golden Stave, which is the Australian music and entertainment industry's charity fund raising organisation.<ref name=\"The X Factor Australia: Guy Sebastian\"/><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sG6kHWa?url=http://www.goldenstave.com.au/events/detail.aspx?ParentPageID=60&EventGroupID=52 The Golden Stave Hall of Fame Dinner 2008]. Golden Stave. Archived from [http://www.goldenstave.com.au/events/detail.aspx?ParentPageID=60&EventGroupID=52 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> He is also an ambassador for [[World Vision Australia]], and in 2005 he travelled to Uganda to film a World Vision documentary \"An Idol in Africa\" for a [[Network Ten]] television special.<ref>Sams, Christine (19 September 2005). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sGBixDr?url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/the-fros-african-education/2005/09/18/1126981938615.html The 'fro's African education]. ''The Sun-Herald''. Archived from [http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/the-fros-african-education/2005/09/18/1126981938615.html the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nB900xkzChM Guy Sebastian World Vision Documentary]. Google Videos. Retrieved 26 February 2009</ref> Sebastian has continued his work with World Vision, supporting the Child Rescue program and the [[40 Hour Famine]]. He has also been involved in the [[Make Poverty History]] coalition of which World Vision is a part.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sGInFPi?url=http://trans.worldvision.com.au/news/newsonline/viewArticle_enh.asp?articleID=433 World Vision News: Guy Sebastian]. World Vision Australia. February 2008. Archived from [https://www.worldvision.com.au/news/newsonline/viewArticle_enh.asp?articleID=433 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> In 2008 he was presented with the Extreme Inspiration Award at the Dolly Teen Choice Awards for his continuing support of World Vision.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sGOcWuY?url=http://dolly.ninemsn.com.au/dtca/614249/dolly-teen-choice-awards-the-winners DOLLY Teen Choice Awards \u2013 the winners!]. ninemsn. 14 August 2008. Archived from [http://dolly.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=614249 the original] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090131220531/http://dolly.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=614249 |date=31 January 2009 }} on 22 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian is also strongly committed to the Sony Foundation, which raises funds to help young Australians facing homelessness, severe illness, disability and isolation.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sGTqz81?url=http://www.sonyfoundation.org.au/what-we-do.php Sony Foundation. What we do]. Sonyfoundation.corg.au. Archived from [http://www.sonyfoundation.org.au/what-we-do.php the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> In 2009 the Sony CEO Denis Handlin said: \"Every time I've asked Guy to get involved with the Sony Foundation through charity he's been completely proactive. Guy's been such a great ambassador for that, and a lot of it is under the radar but it just tells you so much about what a decent human being he is.\"<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sGXPvBZ?url=http://www.novafm.com.au/nova100/Article_Sony-Proved-Why-It-s-An-Industry-leader_414 Sony Proved Why It's An Industry Leader]. novafm.com.au. Archived from [http://www.novafm.com.au/nova100/Article_Sony-Proved-Why-It-s-An-Industry-leader_414 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\nSebastian contributes to many other charitable projects. In 2005 he was the guest performer on the annual [[Indian Pacific]] Outback Christmas Journey which raises money for the [[Royal Flying Doctor Service of Australia|Royal Flying Doctor's Service]].<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sGb6uc6?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829002416 The 'Fro Makes Tracks]. Guy Sebastian official website. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829002416 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> In 2008 he performed a series of 11 concerts with the Australian Army Band to raise funds for [[Legacy Australia|Legacy]].<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian Joins The Army Tomorrow\">Cashmere, Paul (18 September 2008). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sGeDiJp?url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/6273-guy-sebastian-joins-the-army-tomorrow Guy Sebastian Joins The Army Tomorrow]. Undercover.com.au. Archived from [http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=6339 the original] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091021003040/http://www.undercover.com.au/News-Story.aspx?id=6339 |date=21 October 2009 }} on 22 January 2012.</ref> Legacy is a voluntary organisation which supports the families of deceased veterans.<ref>[http://www.legacy.com.au/ Legacy]. Legacy Australia. Retrieved 19 June 2010.</ref> The concerts were held in theatre venues around Australia and the funds raised went to the local Legacy branch in the area each concert was held.<ref>Quagliata, Chris(2 December 2008). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sH5Ag0Z?url=http://www.townsvillebulletin.com.au/article/2008/12/02/25685_news.html Idol Guy performs in Townsville for worthy cause]. ''Townsville Bulletin''. Archived from [http://www.townsvillebulletin.com.au/article/2008/12/02/25685_news.html the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian regularly performs at other fundraising events including Brisbane radio station [[B105 FM|B105]]'s Christmas appeal for the Royal Children's Hospital,<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sHWHuQP?url=http://www.workingwonders.com.au/latest-news/guy-sebastian-working-wonders-for-sick-kids Guy Sebastian working wonders for sick kids]. workingwonders.com.au. 18 December 2009. Archived from [http://www.workingwonders.com.au/latest-news/guy-sebastian-working-wonders-for-sick-kids the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> and [[Perth]]'s annual [[Channel Seven Perth Telethon|Telethon]].<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sHhJBMD?url=http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2009/10/05/perths-telethon-raises-6-4-million/ Perth telethon raises 6.4&nbsp;million]. mediaspy.org. Archived from [http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2009/10/05/perths-telethon-raises-6-4-million/ the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> He also donates his time to annual Christmas carol events such as [[Carols in the Domain]], Vision Australia's [[Carols by Candlelight]], and [[Brisbane]]'s [[Carols in the City]].<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sHp1gpI?url=http://www.carolsinthedomain.com/line_up.php Australia's Biggest Names]. carolsinthedomain.com. Archived from [http://www.carolsinthedomain.com/line_up.php the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sHzxMfl?url=http://www.visionaustralia.org.au/info.aspx?page=1209 A Proud History]. visionaustralia.org. Archived from [http://www.visionaustralia.org.au/info.aspx?page=1209 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref><ref>Feeney, Katherine (4 December 2008). [https://www.webcitation.org/64sI60HOz?url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/news/whatson/carols-in-the-city/2008/12/03/1228257121578.html Carols in the City]. brisbanetimes.com.au. Archived from [http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/news/whatson/carols-in-the-city/2008/12/03/1228257121578.html the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> His songs are frequently featured on charity CDs including the [[Salvation Army]] Christmas fundraising CDs, ''The Spirit of Christmas'' albums.<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sIMW1mP?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/archive.do?newsId=20030829003903 The Spirit Of Christmas 2006]. Guy Sebastian official website. 16 November 2006. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/archive.do?newsId=20030829003903 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref><ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sIU975P?url=http://salvos.org.au/about-us/media-centre/documents/SpiritOfChristmas-MediaRelease.pdf Myer Continues To Share The Spirit Of Christmas] (pdf). salvos.org.au. Archived from [http://salvos.org.au/about-us/media-centre/documents/SpiritOfChristmas-MediaRelease.pdf the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref> Sebastian also makes unofficial appearances at hospitals several times a year.<ref>Tsirimokos, Natalie [https://www.webcitation.org/64sIYVmmS?url=http://www.outincanberra.com.au/articles/guysebastiancanberrasoutherncrossclub Guy Sebastian @ Canberra Southern Cross Club]. outincanberra.com.au. Archived from [http://www.outincanberra.com.au/articles/guysebastiancanberrasoutherncrossclub the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Guy together with his wife Jules formed The Sebastian Foundation. Both were raised with a strong affinity to charity and at the time of having their first child and making their own family, wanted to create an organisation through which they could help other families who were a little less fortunate than theirs. Based on an understanding of what a positive impact a strong family unit can have on both individuals and community, The Sebastian Foundation looks to provide a little bit of the warmth and benefit of family where it might be missing through serious illness, underprivilege or domestic violence. Project based, the Foundation seeks to help where the need is \u2013 they have renovated kitchens, gardens, and living areas in women's refuges, provided sleeper beds to hospitals to allow families to stay together through treatment and countless other ways to make a difference in some of Australia's most vulnerable lives.<ref>http://www.thesebastianfoundation.org</ref> The Foundation has been working alongside the NSW Minister for Social Housing on a proposal that will revolutionise the way women fleeing domestic violence seek shelter which has the potential to impact generations to come, and a mentoring program to help young women who have been through the shelter system put their best foot forward. Funds are raised for the Foundation from corporate sponsors and through the annual MYER Carols in the City performance in Sydney.\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Guy Sebastian discography}}\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Just as I Am (Guy Sebastian album)|Just as I Am]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Beautiful Life (Guy Sebastian album)|Beautiful Life]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Closer to the Sun (Guy Sebastian album)|Closer to the Sun]]'' (2006)\n*''[[The Memphis Album]]'' (2007)\n*''[[Like It Like That (album)|Like it Like That]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Armageddon (Guy Sebastian album)|Armageddon]]'' (2012)\n*''[[Madness (Guy Sebastian album)|Madness]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Conscious (Guy Sebastian album)|Conscious]]'' (2017)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Guy Sebastian}}\n\nSebastian has been nominated for numerous awards during his career, winning many of them. These awards and nominations include ARIA Awards,<ref name=\"ARIA Awards History\"/><ref name=\"No Idol threat\"/> ARIA No. 1 Chart Awards,<ref>[http://www.aria.com.au/pages/no1-awards-2004.htm Aria No.1 Awards]. Australian Recording Industry Association. Retrieved 5 June 2010.</ref> [[APRA Awards (Australia)|APRA Awards]], Australian Club Entertainment Awards,<ref name=\"ACE Awards: 11th Australian Club Awards\"/> Nickelodeon Kids Choice Awards,<ref name=\"The Age: Kids' choice \u2013 Guy\"/> Urban Music Awards,<ref name=\"smh.com.au\"/><ref name=\"inthemix.com.au\"/> and a Channel V Artist of the Year Award.<ref name=\"Musicdish: Aria Awards 2004\"/>\n\n==Tours==\n* 2004\u201305: Beautiful Life Tour<ref name=\"Beautiful Life Tour\"/>\n* 2007: Closer to the Sun Tour<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sqpY6St?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829004004 Closer To The Sun Tour 07]. Guy Sebastian official website. 7 December 2006. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829004004 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n* 2007: Acoustic Tour<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64rCjPumn?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005047 Guy Sebastian Launches Acoustic Tour This Week]. Guy Sebastian official website. 8 October 2007. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005047 the original] on 21 January 2012.</ref>\n* 2008: [[The Memphis Tour]]<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sqv84VT?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005306 Guy's On Fire: More Memphis Tour Dates]. Guy Sebastian official website. 25 January 2008. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829005306 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n* 2009: Live & By Request Tour<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64sr28XKU?url=http://www.liveguide.com.au/Tours/621471/Guy_Sebastian/Guy_Sebastian_Live_By_Request_Tour Guy Sebastian 'Live & By Request' Tour]. liveguide.com.au. Archived from [http://www.liveguide.com.au/Tours/621471/Guy_Sebastian/Guy_Sebastian_Live_By_Request_Tour the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n* 2010: Like It Like That Tour<ref name=\"Like It Like That Tour\"/>\n* 2010: Bring Yourself Tour<ref name=\"The Bring Yourself Tour!\"/>\n* 2010: Like It Like That Tour <small>(USA \u2013 [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Seattle]] & California)</small><ref name=\"Guy Sebastian Releases Debut U.S. Album, Tours West Coast\"/>\n* 2012: [[Armageddon tour]]<ref name=\"The Armageddon Tour\"/>\n* 2013: [[Get Along Tour]] <small>(March to July 2013)</small><ref name=\"Guy Sebastian's Get Along tour dates\"/>\n* 2015: [[Madness Tour]]<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian to play Australian arenas on Madness tour 2015\"/>\n* 2015: Madness European Tour<ref name=\"European Tour\"/>\n*2016:  You...Me...Us Tour<ref name=\"You...Me...Us Tour\"/>\n*2017:  Sub-Conscious Tour<ref name=\"The Sub-Conscious tour\"/>\n*2017: Conscious Tour<ref name=\"Conscious\"/>\n*2018: Then and Now Tour<ref>Williams, Tom (28 March 2018)[https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/guy-sebastian-announces-huge-2018-now-tour/ Guy Sebastian Announces Huge 2018 \u2018Then & Now\u2019 Tour]. Music Feeds. Retrieved 11 June 2019.</ref>\n*2019: Ridin' With You Tour.<ref name=\"Ridin' With You Tour\"/>\n\n'''Joint tours'''\n* 2004: Australian Idol in Concert\n* 2007: Guy & the Australian Philharmonic Orchestra<ref>[https://www.webcitation.org/64skCKChZ?url=http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829004441 Bigger Stronger Better!] Guy Sebastian official website. 3 April 2007. Archived from [http://www.guysebastian.com.au/newsEvents/home.do?newsId=20030829004441 the original] on 22 January 2012.</ref>\n* 2008: Army in Concert with Guy Sebastian<ref name=\"Guy Sebastian Joins The Army Tomorrow\"/>\n\n'''Support tours'''\n* 2011: [[Boyzone]] Tour <small>(United Kingdom)</small><ref name=\"Tour supports confirmed\"/>\n* 2011: [[Lionel Richie]] Tour <small>(Australia and New Zealand)</small><ref name=\"Lionel Richie and Guy Sebastian to Play A Day on the Green\"/>\n* 2013: [[Red Tour]] <small>(Australia)</small><ref name=\"Taylor Swift Tour\"/>\n* 2017: Love Always Tour <small>(United Kingdom)</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.songkick.com/concerts/30103019-shane-filan-at-o2-shepherds-bush-empire|title=Shane Filan, Shane Filan Meet, and Guy Sebastian at O2 Shepherd's Bush Empire (01 Oct 2017)|website=Songkick|language=en|access-date=20 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of best-selling singles in Australia]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the Australian singles chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.guysebastian.com}}\n*{{YouTube|u=guysebastianVEVO|{{PAGENAMEBASE}}}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=1468505|name=Guy Sebastian}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Australian Idol]]''<br />Winner|before=None<br />New television show|after=[[Casey Donovan (singer)|Casey Donovan]]|years=Season 1 (2003)}}\n{{succession box \n| before=none<br /><small>(Debut entry)</small>\n| title=[[Australia in the Eurovision Song Contest]]\