<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/oct/04/agents-shield-recap-episode-two-0-8-4|title=Agents of SHIELD recap: series one, episode two \u2013 0-8-4|last=Virtue|first=Graeme|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=October 4, 2013|accessdate=September 1, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SG43IDsI?url=http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/oct/04/agents-shield-recap-episode-two-0-8-4|archivedate=September 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Hollywood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agents-shield-recap-5-things-640254|title='Agents of SHIELD' Recap: 5 Things We Learned from '0-8-4'|last=Bernardin|first=Marc|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=October 1, 2013|accessdate=September 1, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SG3pCgs6?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/agents-shield-recap-5-things-640254|archivedate=September 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Steranko\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jim-steranko-agents-shield-smoother-641579|title=Jim Steranko on 'Agents of SHIELD': Smoother, But 'Too Unfocused to Be Satisfying'|last=Steranko|first=Jim|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=October 2, 2013|accessdate=September 2, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SHoBKhIS?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jim-steranko-agents-shield-smoother-641579|archivedate=September 2, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BellOct2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=48325 |last=Ching |first=Albert |title=\"Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.\" EP Talks Ratings, Nick Fury Cameo |publisher=[[Comic Book Resources]] |date=October 7, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2014 |archivedate=September 2, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6SHSkrnIn?url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=48325 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.is/20131002135318/http://abc.go.com/shows/marvels-agents-of-shield/episode-guide/102-084 \"0-8-4\"] at [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n*{{IMDb episode|3130816|0-8-4}}\n*{{Tv.com episode|marvels-agents-of-shield/0-8-4-2891925|0-8-4}}\n\n{{Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. episodes}}\n[[Category:Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. (season 1) episodes]]\n[[Category:2013 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes set in Peru]]\n[[Category:Marvel Cinematic Universe crossover episodes]]\n[[Category:Nick Fury in other media]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. episode|the locomotive classification|0-8-4T}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = 0-8-4\n| series       = [[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]\n| image        = Samuel L. Jackson in \"0-8-4\".jpg\n| alt          = Man with an eye patch over his left eye talking to another man, in an over the shoulder shot\n| caption      = [[Samuel L. Jackson]]'s cameo as [[Nick Fury]] during the episode's end tag was much talked about, being called both thrilling and unearned.\n| season       = 1\n| episode      = 2\n| director     = [[David Straiton]]\n| writer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Maurissa Tancharoen]]\n* [[Jed Whedon]]\n* [[Jeffrey Bell]]\n}}\n| producer     = {{Plainlist|\n* Jed Whedon\n* Maurissa Tancharoen\n* Jeffrey Bell\n}}\n| photographer = Feliks Parnell\n| editor       = Paul Trejo\n| airdate      = {{Start date|2013|10|01}}\n| length       = 42 minutes\n| guests       = \n* [[Leonor Varela]] as Camilla Reyes\n* [[Samuel L. Jackson]] as [[Nick Fury]]\n| prev         = [[Pilot (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Pilot]]\n| next         = [[The Asset]]\n| season_article = Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. (season 1)\n| episode_list = List of Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. episodes\n}}\n\"'''0-8-4'''\" is the second episode of the [[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. (season 1)|first season]] of the American television series ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]''. Based on the [[Marvel Comics]] organization [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]], it follows [[Phil Coulson]] and his team of S.H.I.E.L.D. agents as they travel to [[Peru]] to investigate an object of unknown origins. It is set in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] (MCU) and acknowledges the [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films|the franchise's films]]. The episode was written by showrunners [[Maurissa Tancharoen]], [[Jed Whedon]], and [[Jeffrey Bell]], and was directed by [[David Straiton]].\n\n[[Clark Gregg]] reprises his role as Coulson from the film series, starring alongside [[Ming-Na Wen]], [[Brett Dalton]], [[Chloe Bennet]], [[Iain De Caestecker]], and [[Elizabeth Henstridge]]. The episode is set in Peru, featuring guest star [[Leonor Varela]] as a member of the Peruvian military involved with the [[Internal conflict in Peru|ongoing conflict between the Peruvian government and rebel forces]]. Composer [[Bear McCreary]] used ethnic instruments in his score for the episode to support this setting. [[Cosmic Cube|Tesseract]] technology is carried over from the films to tie-in with the conflict. Special guest star [[Samuel L. Jackson]] also reprises his role of [[Nick Fury]] from the film series in a [[cameo appearance]].\n\n\"0-8-4\" originally aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on October 1, 2013, and was watched by 13.17 million viewers within a week. The episode received a mostly positive critical response, with Jackson's appearance considered a highlight by many, but also seen as unearned.\n\n==Plot==\nBeginning immediately after \"[[Pilot (Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.)|Pilot]]\", \"0-8-4\" sees [[Daisy Johnson|Skye]] accept Agent [[Phil Coulson]]'s offer to join his S.H.I.E.L.D. team as a consultant. Though agents Melinda May and Grant Ward oppose this due to her [[hacktivist]] background and lack of S.H.I.E.L.D. training, Coulson believes that Skye can be an asset.\n\nThe team travels to [[Peru]] to investigate a reported 0-8-4 (the S.H.I.E.L.D. designation for \"an object of unknown origin\"). They find the object within an ancient Incan temple, and agents Leo Fitz and Jemma Simmons determine that it is [[Hydra (comics)|Hydra]] made: powered by the [[Cosmic Cube|Tesseract]] and extremely volatile. The national military arrives to claim the weapon for the Peruvian government, led by Camilla Reyes, a former colleague of Coulson's. When they are all attacked by local rebels, the S.H.I.E.L.D. agents and soldiers escape with the weapon to the plane that serves as the agents' mobile base.\n\nEn route to a classified S.H.I.E.L.D. facility, tensions among the agents are high due to poor communication during the fight. This concerns Reyes, who decides to double-cross Coulson and secure the 0-8-4 for her government. Together, the agents devise a plan to activate the weapon, blowing a hole in the Bus. The drop in pressure opens the interior doors, allowing the agents to subdue the soldiers. At the facility, Reyes and her men are incarcerated and the 0-8-4 is launched into the sun in a rocket. The team watch the launch together, celebrating their combined efforts, while Ward agrees to supervise Skye's S.H.I.E.L.D. training. Skye secretly confirms her allegiance to the hacktivist group the Rising Tide.\n\nIn an end tag, S.H.I.E.L.D. Director [[Nick Fury]] scolds Coulson for the damage caused to the plane during the fight, and expresses his doubts over Skye's loyalty.\n\n==Production==\n===Development and casting===\n{{further|List of Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. characters}}\nIn June 2013, [[Samuel L. Jackson]] expressed interest in appearing in the show as S.H.I.E.L.D. director Nick Fury,<ref name=\"Jackson\"/> his role from the [[List of Marvel Cinematic Universe films|MCU films]],<ref name=\"JacksonIMIM2\" /><ref name=\"JacksonThorCapTFAAvengers\" /> which led to his cameo appearance at the end of this episode.<ref name=\"zap2it\" /> Executive producer [[Jeph Loeb]] said \"There were obviously a number of places that we thought Nick Fury would have a big impact on the show, but the more we talked about it, [the more we wanted] to get him in very early, so that it would kind of christen the show, legitimize it in its own way.\"<ref name=\"LoebCasting\" /> It was a challenge for the showrunners to keep Jackson's cameo a surprise due to \"this age of tweets and spoilers\".<ref name=\"BellOct2013\" />\n\nIn October, Marvel revealed that the episode would be titled \"0-8-4\", and would be written by the series' showrunners [[Maurissa Tancharoen]], [[Jed Whedon]], and [[Jeffrey Bell]], with [[David Straiton]] directing. The release confirmed that the series' main cast would star in the episode: [[Clark Gregg]] as [[Phil Coulson]], [[Ming-Na Wen]] as Melinda May, [[Brett Dalton]] as Grant Ward, [[Chloe Bennet]] as [[Daisy Johnson|Skye]], [[Iain De Caestecker]] as Leo Fitz, and [[Elizabeth Henstridge]] as Jemma Simmons. The episode's guest cast was revealed to include [[Leonor Varela]] as Camilla Reyes and [[Carlos Leal]] as an archaeologist.<ref name=\"Preview\" />\n\n===Music===\nComposer [[Bear McCreary]] had a larger orchestra to work with on \"0-8-4\" than he did with \"Pilot\", allowing him to compose a much more \"traditional and, at times, grandiose\" score; however he also opted to expand his synthesizer use to be \"beefier and more aggressive\". The South American setting also allowed an ethnic component to enter the score, with frequent McCreary collaborators M.B. Gordy and Chris Bleth playing tribal-sounding drums and ethnic woodwinds, respectively. Guitarist Ed Trybek also recorded for the episode, playing multiple South American guitars, including [[timple]] and [[charango]].<ref name=\"music\" />\n\n===Marvel Cinematic Universe tie-ins===\nThe titular weapon is powered by the Tesseract, the [[macguffin]] of ''[[Captain America: The First Avenger]]'' (2011) and ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]'' (2012), and was made by [[Hydra (comics)|Hydra]], a fictional organization that also appeared in ''Captain America: The First Avenger''.<ref name=\"MarvelContinuity\" /> It is stated in the episode that the last object of unknown origin that S.H.I.E.L.D. encountered was \"a hammer\", referring to the weapon [[Mjolnir|Mj\u00f6lnir]], which Coulson discovered during the events of ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'' (2011).<ref name=\"MarvelContinuity\" /> Also, Coulson refers to Skye as a consultant, which S.H.I.E.L.D. classified [[Iron Man|Tony Stark]] as during ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' (2010), ''The Avengers'', and the [[Marvel One-Shot]] ''[[Marvel One-Shots#The Consultant (2011)|The Consultant]]'' (2011).<ref name=\"zap2it\" />\n\n==Release==\n===Broadcast===\n\"0-8-4\" was first aired in the United States on ABC on October 1, 2013.<ref name=\"ratings\" /> It was aired alongside the US broadcast in Canada on [[CTV Television Network|CTV]],<ref name=\"canada\" /> while it was first aired in the United Kingdom on [[Channel 4]] on October 4, 2013.<ref name=\"uk\" /> It premiered on the [[Seven Network]] in Australia on October 2, 2013.<ref name=\"australia\"/>\n\n===Home media===\nThe episode, along with the rest of ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.''{{'}}s first season, was released on [[Blu-ray]] and [[DVD]] on September 9, 2014. Bonus features include behind-the-scenes featurettes, audio commentary, deleted scenes, and a blooper reel.<ref name=\"HomeMedia\" /> On November 20, 2014, the episode became available for streaming on [[Netflix]].<ref name=\"Netflix\" />\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\nIn the United States the episode received a 3.3/10 percent share among adults between the ages of 18 and 49, meaning that it was seen by 3.3 percent of all households, and 10 percent of all of those watching television at the time of the broadcast. It was watched by 8.66 million viewers.<ref name=\"ratings\" /> The Canadian broadcast gained 1.83 million viewers, the fourth highest for that day and the twelfth highest for the week.<ref name=\"canada\" /> The [[United Kingdom]] premiere had 3.08 million viewers,<ref name=\"uk\" /> and in [[Australia]], the premiere had 2.8 million viewers, including 1.3 million [[Time shifting|timeshifted]] viewers.<ref name=\"australia\" /> Within a week of its release, the episode was watched by 13.17 million U.S. viewers,<ref name=\"DVR\" /> above the season average of 8.31.<ref name=\"AvgRatings\" />\n\n===Critical response===\n[[MTV.com]] gave a positive review, saying \"If tonight's installment is any indication, the cast will soon be able to support their own weight, make Coulson proud, and audiences sit up and pay attention\", and comparing it positively to ''[[Tarzan: The Epic Adventures|Tarzan]]'', ''[[BeastMaster (TV series)|Beastmaster]]'', and ''[[Mutant X (TV series)|Mutant X]]''.<ref name=\"MTV\" /> Terri Schwartz of [[Zap2it]] also gave a particularly positive review, praising both the connections to the films, including Jackson's cameo, and the internal development of the show, namely that of the character Skye and the team as a whole.<ref name=\"zap2it\" /> Dan Casey of [[Nerdist Industries|Nerdist]] called \"0-8-4\" \"a strong second episode, [which] managed to course-correct from some of the missteps of the pilot\". He praised the \"solid mix of action, character development, and humor\" and concluded that the episode was \"genuinely enjoyable television\".<ref name=\"Nerdist\" /> Eric Goldman of [[IGN]] scored the episode 7.5 out of 10, comparing it positively to ''[[The A-Team]]'' and ''[[Indiana Jones (franchise)|Indiana Jones]]'', praising its self-awareness, Jackson's cameo, and the development of Coulson's character, but criticizing the lack of development for other characters.<ref name=\"IGN\" />\n\nOliver Sava of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' called the episode \"an adequate hour of action-adventure television, but the first 59 minutes are missing the spark of the final post-credits scene\", seeing room for improvement for all the cast members, and concluding that the show falls \"somewhere between [[Firefly (TV series)|''Firefly'']] and [[Dollhouse (TV series)|''Dollhouse'']] on the spectrum of Whedon TV influences\".<ref name=\"AVClub\" />  Graeme Virtue of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called Gregg \"''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.''{{'}}s greatest asset\", finding the Jackson cameo to be a \"thrill\", but that \"plot-wise, things perhaps still feel a little inconsequential\".<ref name=\"Guardian\" /> ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]''{{'}}s Marc Bernardin praised the scale of the episode, describing it as coming \"out of the gate like a blockbuster\", but criticized its ambitions, asking \"Shouldn't this show be, well, nuttier? ... ''Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.'' needs to unhinge itself, but good, and not just be a procedural.\" He also singled out Skye and May as being unfocused and underdeveloped, respectively, as characters, and he felt the Jackson cameo \"gave the whole thing a charge that, in truth, it didn't really earn.\"<ref name=\"Hollywood\" /> [[Jim Steranko]], known for his work on ''Nick Fury, Agent of S.H.I.E.L.D.'', found the episode to be \"smoother [than 'Pilot'], although more formulaic\". He criticized the plot and characters, but praised Jackson's cameo as \"an electrifying reminder of what the series could and should be.\"<ref name=\"Steranko\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<!-- CONTINUITY -->\n\n<ref name=\"JacksonIMIM2\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Fleming |date=February 25, 2009 |title=Samuel Jackson joins 'Iron' cast |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118000573.html |accessdate=March 30, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6A5l4hTlW?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118000573 |archivedate=August 21, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"JacksonThorCapTFAAvengers\">{{cite news |url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2011/02/03/nick-fury-cameos-thor-captain-america-avengers-actresses/ |last=Marshall |first=Rick |title=Nick Fury's 'Thor' & 'Captain America' Cameos Confirmed, Four Actresses Vying For New 'Avengers' Role |publisher=[[MT