019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Scotiabank Arena\n| nickname = The Hanger<br  />The ACC\n| logo_image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena logo.svg|250px]]\n| image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena - 2018 (cropped).jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Exterior view of the arena in 2018\n| address = 40 [[Bay Street]]\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|38|36|N|79|22|45|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| publictransit = {{rint|toronto|rail}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]<br />{{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Union station (TTC)|Union subway station]]<br />{{rint|gotransit|bus}} [[Union Station Bus Terminal|GO Bus Terminal]]\n| broke_ground = March 12, 1997\n| opened = February 19, 1999\n| Acreage = {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4306707/air-canada-centre-gets-new-name/|title=Air Canada Centre sign removed on eve of facility becoming Scotiabank Arena|work=Global News|accessdate=September 27, 2018|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n| operator = \n| former_names = Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. --> {{small|(1999\u20132018)}}\n| construction_cost = {{CAD|265&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/corporate/CompanyFacts.asp|title=Company Facts|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=Air Canada Centre}}</ref><ref name=cost/><br />(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|265000000|1999}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars{{inflation-fn|CA}})\n| architect = Brisbin Brook Beynon Architects (Architect of Record)<br />[[Populous (company)|HOK Sport]]<br />(Consulting Architects)<ref>{{cite web |title=Clubhouse Confidential: When a Bunch of Alpha Males Get Together Daily in a Confined Space, Lots of Things\u2014Good and Bad\u2014Can Happen|first=Michael|last=Faber|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1024724/3/index.htm|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 14, 2002|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| project_manager = Clarendon Projects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|title=Clarendon Projects \u2013 Air Canada Centre|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151414/http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = [[Halcrow Group|Yolles Partnership Inc.]]<ref>[http://www.halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ Halcrow Yolles \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026034118/http://halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ |date=October 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| services engineer = The Mitchell Partnership, Inc.<ref>[http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf The Mitchell Partnership \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115741/http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf |date=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n| general_contractor = [[PCL Construction|PCL Constructors Western, Inc.]]\n| tenants = [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Raptors]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Rock]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (2001\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2001\u20132002)<br />[[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (2010\u2013present, occasional home games)\n| seating_capacity = [[Basketball]]: 19,800 (20,511 with standing room)<br />[[Ice hockey|Hockey]]: 18,800 (20,270 with standing room)<br />[[Lacrosse]]: 18,800<br />[[Concert]]s: 19,800<br />[[Theatre]]: 5,200<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://www.aircanadacentre.com/venue-information/about|publisher=Air Canada Centre|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| parking = 2 underground levels for 212 vehicles<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>\n| website = [https://www.scotiabankarena.com/ scotiabankarena.com]\n}}\n\n'''Scotiabank Arena''', formerly '''Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. -->''', is a multi-purpose [[arena]] located on [[Bay Street]] in the [[South Core, Toronto|South Core]] district of [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]] [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Toronto Rock]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). In addition, the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] play occasional games at the arena. The arena was previously home to the [[Toronto Phantoms]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) during their brief existence.\n\nThe arena  is {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft}} in size. It is owned and operated by [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.]] (MLSE), the same group that owns the Leafs and the Raptors, as well as their respective development teams. In 2018, Scotiabank Arena was the 13th busiest arena in the world and the busiest in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/Chart/2019/01/2018YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues_705.pdf|title=2018 YEAR END Worldwide Ticket Sales TOP 200 ARENA VENUES|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|date=2018|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> It is also the most photographed location in Canada on [[Instagram]] according to [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2018/07/01/scotiabank-arena-now-officially-the-home-of-maple-leafs-and-raptors.html|title=Scotiabank Arena now officially the home of Maple Leafs and Raptors - The Star|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref> Scotiabank Arena is connected to [[Union Station (Toronto)|Toronto Union]] railway station, [[Union station (TTC)|subway station]] and [[Union Station Bus Terminal|bus terminal]] via the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]].\n\nScotiabank Arena has, from its initial design to completion, revolutionized many concepts included in new arenas and stadiums built since then.{{according to whom|date=October 2019}} These features include luxury suites accessible on the ground floor, splitting the main scoreboard into several sections, rotating all sponsor signage in the bowl at once (to allow dominant messaging or \"neutralization\" for events that disallow commercial advertising), and multiple restaurants in and out of the main arena bowl view.\n\nScotiabank Arena also hosts other events, such as concerts, political conventions and [[Esports|video game competitions]].\n\n==History==\n===Site History===\n[[File:Toronto in 1858.jpg|left|thumb|A map showing downtown Toronto in 1858]]The stadium is located on land that was once part of Toronto's inner harbour.  Infill of the inner harbour began in the 1850's and accelerated with the arrival of the railroad resulting in the current day shape of downtown <ref>https://www.cgenarchive.org/toronto-lakeshores.html</ref>.  By 1858 the site was located between two warfs (Rees & Tinnings Warf). As land was expanded southward, it remained under Government control as possible locations of various Union Station expansions.  The majority of the land was still part of the lake up until the early 1900's. By 1925 The northern parcel of the property was turned into of Bayside Park, which had been part of an early proposal that was to have seen the lands south of the rail corridor transformed into an extensive lakeside park that followed today's Esplande. The remaining land was most likely under the control of Central Harbor Terminals<ref>https://maps.library.utoronto.ca/dvhmp/maps.html</ref>.\n\nIn the 1930s the property became the proposed home to [[Canada Post]]'s Toronto Postal Delivery Building.  In the 1920's a postal handling facility already existed in the east wing of the city's then New Union Station (Downtown Toronto's 3rd major train station)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=A Toronto Album 2: More Glimpses of the City That Was|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=K0tIsZ_TAIoC&pg=PA43 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=43 |isbn=}}</ref>. But it quickly reached capacity by the 1930s due to major population growth of Toronto and its surrounding region.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotiabankarena.com/venue-information/about/history|title=History {{!}} Scotiabank Arena|last=Arena|first=Scotiabank|website=www.scotiabankarena.com|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref>. In 1937 the Postmaster General appealed to the Minister of Public Works to approve a new replacement facility at the corner of Bay & Fleet Street (now Lake Shore Boulevard). Approval was granted by the federal Department of Public Works in part to stimulate the depression impacted construction industry<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. Design and construction of the warehouse built with steel & concrete would begin in 1938. Designed by [[Charles B. Dolphin]] it's a building that incorporates a combination of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Moderne]] architectural style. The original building would be built for around $2,000,000 (CAD)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref> [$ 35 million 2020],  The building was strategically located south of Union Station and was connected directly to the train platforms via an underground tunnel. Trains would be able to directly unload mail and move it directly to the mail sorting centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Toronto Postal Delivery Building Postcard.jpg|thumb|left|Toronto Postal Delivery Building c.1950s]]\nThe building was handed over to Department of National Defence for war storage purposes upon completion in 1941, but returned to Canada Post in 1946. Modifications were made to the building to be more adequately equipped for postal delivery, after it was altered by the Department of National Defence.  After the refurbishment work was completed in 1948, the building now possessed the capability and equipment for proper mail sorting and other mailing functions. Though it was designed as a mail sorting warehouse it was also the home of Postal Station \"A\" which served mostly institutional & commercial clients.  The Ground floor was where the mail was dropped off by both railway carts and postal vans. Unsorted mail was moved by conveyor belts to the top floor and via gravity fed mail chutes sorted by size & destination.  Eventually the sorted mail would end up back on the ground floor where it would be sent out for delivery<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. The building would be used as a postal sorting centre up until the 1990s.\n\n====Postal Building Sculptures==== \nThe structures most notable feature (which has been retained) are the exterior 13-part series of limestone [[bas relief]] carvings by [[Louis Temporale]] Sr. [[Order of Canada|CM]] which depicts the history of transportation and communication in Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>.  Carved in 1938-39 begins with scenes showing human speech, a runner carrying a message, aboriginals communicating by smoke signal, a group of voyageurs, a schooner & a Royal Mail steamship crossing the ocean from England, the CN train used during the 1939 Royal Tour, the mythical flying boat named 'Canopus' and northern travel by dog sled<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location= |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref>. The sculptors son Louis Temporale jr. helped with restoration efforts in 1998 and in 2016 was still critical of the lack of protection of the artwork by stadium ownership for over 20 years. The nearby elevated Gardiner Expressway results in salt spray which is speeding up the deterioration of the limestone<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/mlse-acc-art-temporale-heritage-1.3395714|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>. \n\n====1990s Transition to Stadium====\nThe the late 1980s, the building & antiquated sorting equipment was in need of major renovations & expensive upgrades. In a cost cutting move (part of larger overall service changes & cuts made to the Crown Corporation under the [[Brian Mulroney]] Conservatives), Canada Post decided to close the facility and move operations to an alternate more modern c.1970s letter processing faculty on nearby Eastern Avenue. A structure with easy access to highways was designed specificity for transport truck delivery of mail. By 1989, all of the old building's work was transferred here.<ref name=\":0\" />. The 1980s real estate boom saw the building site become surrounded by skyscrapers, hotels, convention centres, SkyDome stadium & condo towers.  In the early 1990s, real estate developers [[Bramalea (company)|Bramalea Ltd]] and [[Trizec Properties|Trizec]] arranged to purchase the building from Canada Post, and redevelop the site into a {{convert|230,000|m2|sqft|adj=on}} office, retail and residential space. Financial and development details of the purchase imposed various conditions prior to development, including rezoning by the city, remediation of soil contamination by Canada Post.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bramalea's Moves Shake Taxpayers|first=Stevie|last=Cameron|date=November 15, 1992|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nDue to financial difficulties, the building's ownership was returned to Canada Post in 1993 and remained abandoned. The Toronto Raptors purchased the unused building from Canada Post the following year.<ref name=\"rapnba\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/history/raptors_history.html/| title=Laying the Groundwork for the NBA in Toronto| website=nba.com| accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal terminal now Air Canada Centre.jpg|thumb|left|The arena retains the eastern & southern walls of the original postal structure built, through a process of [[facadism]].]]\nConstruction of the arena was started by the Toronto Raptors, under their initial ownership group headed by Canadian businessman [[John Bitove]]. In 1995, it had been decided that the NBA would expand into Canada. The Toronto Raptors were created and would need an indoor arena to play in. The Canada Post building was chosen to be the new home of the Raptors due to its downtown location and lot size. Other venues such as [[Exhibition Place]], North York Centre, Bay and Wellesley, and Bay and Dundas were also considered. The Canada Post building was purchased for {{CAD|60}} million.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Raptors initially played in SkyDome (now [[Rogers Centre]]) while the arena was constructed.<ref name=\"blogTo\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Bateman|title=That time the Raptors and the Maple Leafs moved to the ACC|url=http://www.blogto.com/city/2014/02/that_time_the_raptors_and_leafs_moved_to_the_acc/|website=blogTo|date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Groundbreaking took place in March 1997. The building retained the [[Art Deco]] Queenston limestone facade of the Toronto Postal Delivery Building along the east (along [[Bay Street]]) and south ([[Lake Shore Boulevard]]) walls of that structure, but the rest of the building (facing [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]) was removed to make room for the arena, through the process of [[facadism]]. The original building is protected under the ''[[Ontario Heritage Act]]''.\n\n====Arena 'Wars'====\nWhen MLGL ([[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment|Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited]] at the time the controlling company of the Toronto Maple Leafs) lost out on their desire to be the franchise owners of the Raptors, competition between the two organizations heated up centred around venues. MLGL declined to allow Maple Leaf Gardens to be used for the NBA upstart as a result pushing Bitove to secure rights to have the Raptors' opening seasons played at SkyDome until construction of the new stadium to be complete.\n\nThe 1930s-era Maple Leaf Gardens was showing its age; the Maple Leafs in desperate desire for a new facility began developing plans for building an all-new stadium with one of the key criteria for the new location that it must be within close walking proximity to both the subway system and GO Transit. During the early stages of construction, MLGL floated to the media plans for their own plans to build a competing single-use stadium on adjacent property just to the north of the stadium atop the train sheds at Union Station (similar to how [[Madison Square Garden]] was constructed) as the new home for the Toronto Maple Leafs.<ref name=ArenaWars>{{cite news|title=Leafs ready to Move (Page 2)|first=Craig|last=Daniels|date=April 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> The reaction from Raptors was nothing but anger. \"This proposed (Maple Leaf) location really disturbs us\" stated team president Richard Peddie, who went on to say that they would fight the Leafs \"every step of the way\" and he didn't understand why the Leafs have refused to join with the Raptors at their site; claiming that the Leafs want to \"build virtually on top of us\".<ref name=\"ArenaWars\" /> The major problem of the Union Station proposal is the land that the stadium would be built on was actually City of Toronto land that was leased out to CN Rail and CP Rail, which were in a major, long-standing dispute over rent payments (dating back to 1969). As a result, MLGL offered the city $156 Million (1997 CAD) in cash & assets to settle any and all outstanding claims and to buy the air rights above the Union Station train platforms.\n\nDuring this period John Bitove who disputed over the future of the arena who as a result of a [[shotgun clause]] was forced to sell his stake to Allan Slaight (who wanted a joint arena deal with MLGL) and now with majority ownership immediately went into talks with MLGL which eventually purchased both the Raptors and their partially completed arena, which subsequently resulted in major modifications to the original design, which was basketball-specific, to make the arena become more suitable for hockey. Originally planned to cost $217&nbsp;million, MLGL increased the budget to $265&nbsp;million after taking control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> The Raptors were twice fined a million dollars (which were donated to their charitable foundation) by the NBA for missing deadlines to begin construction of their new arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors' arena bites dust|last=Christe|first=James|date=May 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\n====Construction==== \nAfter the purchase of the Raptors and the Air Canada Centre the new owners entered into a design-build contract with PCL with the commitment to finish the stadium in 24-months by March 1st 1999<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>.  The intergartion of the Maple Leafs into the new structure would result in a 25% increase in construction costs (over $25 million CAD in 1999)<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>. \n\nThe completed structure included a 15-storey tower (reduced from a proposed 30-stories), four restaurants, and an underground parking lot. \n\n====Opening====\nIn 1998, a strange twist of scheduling conflicts had the Toronto Raptors playing their final regular-season game at [[Copps Coliseum]] in Hamilton, as the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] had first right of refusal for all SkyDome dates.  The Raptors had attempted to play the April 19 match at Maple Leaf Gardens, but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors Move Final Game to Hamilton|date=January 7, 1998|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.apnews.com/7027ff09054e45b3b7471205f12cb521}}</ref>\n[[File:Air Canada Centre in 1999.jpg|thumb|right|Air Canada Centre in July 1999, five months after the arena opened]]\n\nOn December 30th 1998, the building's construction was completed, 9 days ahead of schedule. Opening events took place early the next year and [[Steve Stavro]] (who was the majority shareholder of MLGL) was named CEO. The initial hockey game took place February 20, 1999 (Toronto Maple Leafs vs. [[Montreal Canadiens]]), the first basketball Game on February 21, 1999 (Toronto Raptors vs. [[Vancouver Grizzlies]]), and the opening concert on February 22, 1999 ([[The Tragically Hip]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> Features of the new building consist of a {{convert|65000|sqft|adj=on}} arena and a {{convert|165000|sqft|adj=on}} office tower. There is also an east\u2013west covered, climate controlled galleria and walkway onsite that contains restaurants, the ticket office, and other commercial units. The Galleria also connects Scotiabank Arena to popular locations in the downtown core such as Union Station, Bay Street and York Street. Scotiabank Arena is connected to the underground PATH network. The Galleria also doubles as a historical museum by displaying numerous artifacts from the old Canada Post building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Air-Canada-Centre.aspx|title=Air Canada Centre|work=PCL Constructors|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n[[File:PATH Escalators Construction Scotiabank Arena.jpg|thumb|left|Escalators for a new [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] system connection to the under-construction [[CIBC Square]] office complex being installed in the arena's lobby in 2019]]In its first ten years of operation, the new arena had an estimated economic benefit of $2.4&nbsp;billion. This boosted Toronto's economy and led to further construction in the downtown core. Many projects in the area were completed ahead of schedule as a result of a desire to increase the infrastructure of downtown Toronto, and also from private funding (approximately $13&nbsp;million) that was invested in seeing the economic growth of Toronto. These projects included the Bay West Teamway, Union Plaza, the Galleria (shopping centre), and Bremner Boulevard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Air Canada]] purchased [[naming rights]] to the arena for US$30&nbsp;million for 20 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/marketing/|work=CBC News|title=Branding for dollars|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Current History== \nIn 2003, MLSE completed a $5-million upgrade of the arena, including a new LED signage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=459588|title=Air Canada Centre Renovations to Improve Ultimate Fan Experience|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  During the summer of 2015, a $10-million upgrade of the arena was carried out, which included the installation of a new scoreboard four times larger than the previous one. The old scoreboard was later installed at [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2015/07/24/acc-to-debut-new-scoreboard-this-year.html|title=Air Canada Centre to debut new scoreboard this year|first=Raju|last=Mudhar|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the winter of 2003\u20132004, the [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] imposed a seven-day penalty on the arena for \"permitting drunken patrons to be in the licensed patrons{{sic}}\" in the fall of 2002 at a Toronto Maple Leafs game and also a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert. As a result of these misdemeanours, there was no alcohol served at the arena from December 21 to 28 in 2003. The venue had multiple major events during this time frame, which included a Toronto Raptors\u2013[[Orlando Magic]] game on December 21, a Toronto Maple Leafs\u2013[[Florida Panthers]] game on December 23, and [[Disney on Ice]]: [[Toy Story 2]], which ran from December 25, 2003 to January 1, 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/air-canada-centre-loses-liquor-licence-for-a-week-1.401537|title=Air Canada Centre loses liquor licence for a week {{!}} CBC Sports|work=CBC|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC08942 - Legends Row (37049346192).jpg|thumb|In September 2014, a group of life-sized statues were installed at the southwest corner of the arena.]]\nOn September 6, 2014, a group of statues known as ''Legends Row'' was unveiled outside the arena at the southwest corner of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2014/09/06/maple_leaf_legends_row_unveils_first_three_honourees.html|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row starts with Ted Kennedy, Darryl Sittler, Johnny Bower|publisher=Torstar Corporation|accessdate=September 27, 2018|work=Toronto Star|date=September 7, 2014|last=Rubin|first=Josh}}</ref> The statues were situated in multiple waves from 2014 to 2016 and include [[Ted Kennedy (ice hockey)|Ted Kennedy]], [[Johnny Bower]], [[Darryl Sittler]], [[B\u00f6rje Salming|Borje Salming]], [[Syl Apps]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Mats Sundin]], [[Dave Keon]], [[Turk Broda]], and [[Tim Horton]]. In 2017, the final four statues were unveiled including [[Red Kelly]], [[Frank Mahovlich]], [[Charlie Conacher]], and [[Wendel Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/maple-leafs-legends-row-adds-conacher-kelly-mahovlich-and-clark/c-286915412|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row 'is full' with four added|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''Legends Row'' now features 14 life-sized statues of former Maple Leaf players alongside a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|round=5}} granite players' bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/2017/10/05/4-more-leafs-added-to-legends-row/wcm/53247716-67d7-445e-9f20-a91a51890592|title=Four more Maple Leafs added to Legends Row|work=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|date=October 5, 2017|last=Hornby|first=Lance|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Renaming====\nThe Air Canada Centre was renamed Scotiabank Arena on July 1, 2018. The landmark 20-year sponsorship agreement between Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment and [[Scotiabank]] is worth about C$800&nbsp;million. This is believed to be the highest-priced annual building and team sponsorship in North American sports history.<ref name=\"MLSEScotiaBankArena\">{{cite news|title=HOME OF THE MAPLE LEAFS AND RAPTORS TO BECOME SCOTIABANK ARENA NEXT SUMMER|url=http://mlse.com/news/scotiabankarena/|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestheadTSN\">{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|website=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The arena is the third in Canada to bear naming rights to Scotiabank.\n\n==Maple Leaf Square==\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|A popular gathering point during [[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] and [[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]] playoff runs, the arena has a large video screen that overlooks the atrium of Maple Leaf Square.]]\n{{main|Maple Leaf Square}}\nIn late 2005, Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment announced that they would be renovating the western side of the Air Canada Centre during the 2008 off-season to connect it with the [[Maple Leaf Square]] development. Maple Leaf Square is jointly owned by MLSE, [[Cadillac Fairview]] and Lantera Developments. The $500&nbsp;million development includes two restaurants, Hotel Le Germain at Maple Leaf Square boutique hotel, extensive retail shopping, including a {{convert|840|m2|sqft|adj=on}} Leafs, [[Toronto Marlies|Marlies]], Raptors, and [[Toronto FC]] store, two 54-storey condominiums, a [[Longo's]] supermarket, and a public square. It opened in 2010. The two-year, $48&nbsp;million renovation of the ACC added a new atrium that includes a High-Definition broadcast studio for [[Leafs Nation Network]] (formerly Leafs TV), [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV (Canadian TV channel)|GolTV Canada]].\n\nThe outside wall of the atrium features a {{convert|9.1|by|15.2|m|ft|adj=on}} video screen overlooking the plaza, which often broadcasts games taking place inside the arena. During [[Stanley Cup playoffs|NHL]] and [[NBA playoffs|NBA playoff]] runs, the square attracts thousands of Leafs and Raptors fans, respectively, sometimes broadcasting away playoff matches featuring the Leafs and/or the Raptors as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=NBA.com/Raptors|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> A section of the square is designated Ford Fan Zone at Maple Leaf Square, with naming rights given to the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]. During Raptors playoff runs, the square has acquired the nickname \"[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]\" after the 1993 film adaptation that inspired the team's name. During the [[2019 NBA Playoffs]] and especially during the [[2019 NBA Finals]], other city squares across Canada also acquired the Jurassic Park nickname, such as in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-jurassic-park-spin-offs-ontario-1.5159009|publisher=CBC|title=Jurassic Park spin-offs popping up as Raptors fever sweeps Canada|author=Lucas Powers}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Concerts===\n{{main|List of entertainment events at Scotiabank Arena}}\n\n===Political conventions===\nIn 2003, the governing [[Liberal Party of Canada]] held their [[2003 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|leadership convention]] at the Air Canada Centre. [[Paul Martin]] was elected as the new leader of the party and thus also became [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]], succeeding [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]].\n\n===Sports===\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1 = Raptors vs Bucks 2.jpg\n | width1 = 165\n | image2 = Buffalo Bandits at Toronto Rock.jpg\n | width2 = 155\n | image3 = Toronto AirCanadaCenter 01.jpg\n | width3 = 165\n |footer= Scotiabank Arena is a [[Multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose arena]] that is able to host a number of sporting events, including basketball, box lacrosse, and ice hockey.\n}}\nThe first Maple Leafs home game took place on February 20, 1999, versus the Montreal Canadiens, won by the Leafs 3\u20132 on an [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal by [[Steve Thomas (ice hockey)|Steve Thomas]]. Maple Leaf home games are generally sold out,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryl|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/toronto-maple-leafs/#h3_jump_10|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and there is a waitlist since the start of 2015 for Season Ticket Holders for upcoming seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Purchase Season Seats|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=73129|website=Toronto Maple Leafs|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The first Raptors game took place the following night versus the then-[[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]]. The Raptors won 102\u201387 in front of a sell-out crowd. The facility hosted the [[2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game|2000 NHL All-Star Game]], the championship game of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], all games of the [[2016 World Cup of Hockey]] and the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game]], the first NBA All-Star Game held outside of the United States.\n\nThe Toronto Rock also moved to the Air Canada Centre from Maple Leaf Gardens for the [[2001 NLL season]]. The Rock's first game was a 17\u20137 win over the [[Ottawa Rebel]] on December 21, 2000.\n\nOn October 3, 2003, Air Canada Centre had a power outage during the third quarter of a Raptors pre-season game against the Athens-based club [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The game was called final, because the power was not restored in time and the Raptors already had a [[Mercy rule|30-point lead]].\n\nAir Canada Centre hosted the [[2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] for the first time, as well as hosted the final match of that tournament, in which Canada was crowned champion, defeating Russia. The ACC co-hosted that tournament with [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, and both venues co-hosted the [[2017 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2017 edition of the same event]], though the ACC did not host the medal rounds.\n[[File:Laura Wright performs during the Invictus Flag Raising (37021670620).jpg|thumb|Flag raising during the [[2017 Invictus Games]] closing ceremonies]]\nIn 2017, the Air Canada Centre hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for [[2017 Invictus Games|that year's Invictus Games]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.invictusgames2017.com/ceremonies/|title=Ceremonies|publisher=Invictus Games Toronto 2017|year=2016|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, the ACC presented the opening ceremony as a live two-hour event spectacular. This ceremony was designed to welcome and honour the 550 competitors and their families who come from 17 different competing nations. The show featured hundreds of cast members, including honorary men and women from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]]. The cast showed a display of ceremony in multiple different productions and the raising of the flag. Other guests of the event included celebrities, world dignitaries, headline music stars and other special guests. They gathered to celebrate the service and stories of the members of the 2017 Invictus Games. Headline performers included [[Laura Wright (singer)|Laura Wright]], [[Alessia Cara]], [[The Tenors]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], and [[La Bottine Souriante]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe ACC hosted the Invictus Games Toronto 2017 Closing Ceremony on September 20, 2017. The event featured an arrangement of international headline music artists, coming together to celebrate and recognize the Invictus Games competitors. The closing ceremony featured headline musical guests [[Bachman & Turner]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[C\u0153ur de pirate|Coeur de Pirate]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. This celebration also included words from world dignitaries as the Games are passed to the host nation of the [[2018 Invictus Games|Invictus Games 2018]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe venue hosted its first championship series when the Raptors played the [[Golden State Warriors]] in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]. The Raptors won the NBA championship, albeit in the Warriors' home arena of [[Oracle Arena]] in [[Oakland]] in Game 6.\n\nThe arena has also played host to five [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/05/ufc-165-heads-to-air-canada-centre-in-toronto-on-sept-21|title=UFC 165 heads to Air Canada Centre in Toronto on Sept. 21|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UFC206\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/8/19/12562718/ufc-releases-schedule-for-rest-of-2016-including-ufc-206-in-toronto|title=UFC releases schedule for rest of 2016 including UFC 206 in Toronto|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| [[UFC 140]]\n| Saturday, December 10, 2011\n|-\n| [[UFC 152]]\n| Saturday, September 22, 2012\n|-\n| [[UFC 165]]\n| Saturday, September 21, 2013\n|-\n| [[UFC 206]]\n|Saturday, December 10, 2016\n|-\n| [[UFC 231]]\n|Saturday, December 8, 2018\n|}\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n\n===Video game competitions===\nOn August 27 and 28, 2016, Air Canada Centre hosted the [[2016 Summer North American League of Legends Championship Series|sixth season of the Summer North American Championship Series]] of ''[[League of Legends]]'' (LoL), marking the first [[League of Legends Championship Series|professional ''League of Legends'' competition]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/na-summer-finals-coming-toronto|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is a popular [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) [[PC game|computer game]] by American video game developer [[Riot Games]]; ''League of Legends'' competitions are among the most viewed among professional video game competitions worldwide. During the final round, [[Team SoloMid]] (TSM) defeated [[Cloud9]] (C9) three matches to one in a best-of-five format. The Summer North American Championship Series serve as the qualifiers for the annual [[League of Legends World Championship]] for North American teams.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.scotiabankarena.com/}}\n* [http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html Toronto's Historical Plaques; Toronto Postal Delivery Building]\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Ice hockey|Canada|Ontario}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n&nbsp;\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Raptors]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Rock]]\n | years = 2000\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]]\n | years = 2001\u20132002\n | before = [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n | after = last arena\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2000\n | before = [[Amalie Arena|St. Pete Times Forum]]\n | after = [[Pepsi Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[NBA All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2016\n | before = [[Madison Square Garden]]\n | after = [[Smoothie King Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of<br />[[Unforgiven (2006)|Unforgiven]]\n | years = 2006\n | before = [[Chesapeake Energy Arena|Ford Center]]\n | after = [[FedExForum]]\n}}\n{{End}}\n{{Toronto landmarks}}\n{{Sport venues in Toronto}}\n{{NHL Arenas}}\n{{NBA Arenas}}\n{{NLL Arenas}}\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Raptors}}\n{{Toronto Phantoms}}\n{{Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n{{Canada Cup World Cup of Hockey Finals venues}}\n}}<!-- end of infoboxes -->\n\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Indoor lacrosse venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Basketball venues in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Raptors venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League venues]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association venues]]\n[[Category:PATH (Toronto)]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:City of Toronto Heritage Properties]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Scotiabank]]\n", "name_user": "Themedpark", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scotiabank_Arena"}
{"title_page": "Interplanetary Scintillation Array", "text_new": "{{moreref|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox telescope}}\n[[File:Chart Showing Radio Signal of First Identified Pulsar.jpg|thumb|upright|Chart on which [[Jocelyn Bell Burnell]] first recognised evidence of a [[pulsar]], later designated [[PSR B1919+21]] (exhibited at [[Cambridge University Library]]) ]]\n\nThe '''Interplanetary Scintillation Array''' (also known as the '''IPS Array''' or '''Pulsar Array''') is a [[radio telescope]] that was built in 1967 at the [[Mullard Radio Astronomy Observatory]], in [[Cambridge|Cambridge, United Kingdom]], and was operated by the [[Cavendish Astrophysics Group]]. The instrument originally covered 4 [[acre]]s (16,000 m\u00b2). It was enlarged to 9 acres in 1978, and was refurbished in 1989. \n\nThe array operates at a [[radio frequency]] of 81.5 MHz (3.7 m [[wavelength]]), and is made up of 4,096 [[dipole antenna]]s in a [[phased array]]. Using 14 beams, it can map the northern sky in one day. The observatory's staff use [[sheep]] to keep grass away from the antennas because a [[lawn mower]] cannot fit in the spaces.\n\n[[Antony Hewish]] designed the IPS Array to measure the high-frequency fluctuations of radio sources, originally for monitoring [[interplanetary scintillation]]. Hewish received a [[Nobel prize]] after the high time-resolution of the array allowed the detection of [[pulsars]] by [[Jocelyn Bell]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite web |title=The First Pulsar |url=https://astrobites.org/2017/09/15/the-first-pulsar/ |website=astrobites |date=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe IPS Array has more recently been used to track and help forecast interplanetary weather, and specifically to monitor the solar wind. It is now essentially retired, and has lost a significant fraction of its area.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cavendish Laboratory]]\n[[Category:Radio telescopes]]\n\n{{observatory-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{moreref|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox telescope}}\n[[File:Chart Showing Radio Signal of First Identified Pulsar.jpg|thumb|upright|Chart on which [[Jocelyn Bell Burnell]] first recognised evidence of a [[pulsar]], later designated [[PSR B1919+21]] (exhibited at [[Cambridge University Library]]) ]]\n\nThe '''Interplanetary Scintillation Array''' (also known as the '''IPS Array''' or '''Pulsar Array''') is a [[radio telescope]] that was built in 1967 at the [[Mullard Radio Astronomy Observatory]], in [[Cambridge|Cambridge, United Kingdom]], and was operated by the [[Cavendish Astrophysics Group]]. The instrument originally covered 4 [[acre]]s (16,000 m\u00b2). It was enlarged to 9 acres in 1978, and was re-furbished in 1989. \n\nThe array operates at a [[radio frequency]] of 81.5 MHz (3.7 m [[wavelength]]), and is made up of 4,096 [[dipole antenna]]s in a [[phased array]]. Using 14 beams, it can map the northern sky in one day. The observatory's staff uses [[sheep]] to keep grass away from the antennas because a [[lawn mower]] cannot fit in the spaces.\n\n[[Antony Hewish]] designed the IPS Array to measure the high-frequency fluctuations of radio sources, originally for monitoring [[interplanetary scintillation]]. Hewish received a [[Nobel prize]] after the high time-resolution of the array allowed the detection of [[pulsars]] by [[Jocelyn Bell]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite web |title=The First Pulsar |url=https://astrobites.org/2017/09/15/the-first-pulsar/ |website=astrobites |date=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe IPS Array has more recently been used to track and help forecast interplanetary weather, and specifically to monitor the solar wind. It is now essentially retired, and has lost a significant fraction of its area.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cavendish Laboratory]]\n[[Category:Radio telescopes]]\n\n{{observatory-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alituxworth", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interplanetary_Scintillation_Array"}
{"title_page": "Black Christmas (1974 film)", "text_new": "{{missing information|the film's themes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Black Christmas\n| image          = File:Black Christmas (1974) poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Bob Clark]]\n| producer       = Bob Clark\n| writer         = A. Roy Moore\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Olivia Hussey]]\n* [[Keir Dullea]]\n* [[Margot Kidder]]\n* [[John Saxon]]\n}} <!-- The four actors listed only poster only, do not list anyone else. -->\n| music          = Carl Zittrer\n| cinematography = Reginald H. Morris\n| editing        = Stan Cole\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Telefilm Canada|Canadian Film Development Corportation]]\n* Film Funding Ltd.\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* Ambassador Film Distributors (Canada)\n* [[Warner Bros.]] (USA/International)\n}}\n| released       = {{start date|1974|10|11|Toronto}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes{{sfn|Muir|2011|p=314}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/black-christmas-1974 |title=Black Christmas (1974) |website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $620,000\n| gross          = $4.1 million\n}}\n\n'''''Black Christmas''''' ([[Canadian French]]: ''No\u00ebl tragique'') is a 1974 Canadian [[Horror film|horror]] produced and directed by [[Bob Clark]], and written by A. Roy Moore. It stars [[Olivia Hussey]], [[Keir Dullea]], [[Margot Kidder]], [[Andrea Martin]], Marian Waldman, [[Lynne Griffin]] and [[John Saxon]]. The story follows a group of sorority sisters who receive threatening phone calls and are eventually stalked and murdered by a deranged killer during the [[Christmas]] season. It is the first film in the [[Black Christmas (film series)|''Black Christmas'' series]].\n\nInspired by the urban legend \"[[The babysitter and the man upstairs]]\" and a series of murders that took place in the [[Westmount, Quebec|Westmount section]] of [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Moore wrote the screenplay under the title ''Stop Me''. The filmmakers made numerous alterations to the script, primarily the shifting to a university setting with young adult characters. It was shot in Toronto in 1974 on an estimated budget of $620,000, and was distributed by [[Warner Bros.]] in North America.\n\n''Black Christmas'' was released on October 11, 1974, in Canada and December 20 in the United States under the title '''''Silent Night, Evil Night'''''. Upon its release, the film received mixed reviews, but it has since received critical re-appraisal, with film historians noting it for being one of the earliest slasher films.<ref>{{Cite book |author= Paszylx, Bart\u0142omiej |title=The Pleasure and Pain of Cult Horror Films: An Historical Survey |year=2009 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-786-43695-8 |pages=135\u20136}}</ref> It is also praised for concluding without revealing the identity of its villain, as well as serving as an influence on [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' (1978). Aside from its earning a [[cult following]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Philip|title=Decade of Nightmares: The End of the Sixties and the Making of Eighties America|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-195-34158-4|p=[https://archive.org/details/decadeofnightmar00jenk/page/146 146]|url=https://archive.org/details/decadeofnightmar00jenk/page/146}}</ref> since its release, a novelization written by Lee Hays was published in 1976.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Billy (Black Christmas)|An unseen and disoriented man]] climbs up into the attic of a sorority house, where the tenants are celebrating with a Christmas party. One of the girls, Jess, answers an obscene phone call from a mentally unstable man who is implied to call the house regularly. She summons her fellow students into the room, where they listen as the caller screams and curses them on the phone. When one of the girls, foul-mouthed Barb, takes the phone from Jess, she incites the caller, who in turn promises to kill her. Barb argues with a younger student, Clare Harrison, who implies that the caller could be a serial rapist, before Clare returns to her bedroom to finish packing for Christmas break. The disoriented man lures Clare into her closet, where he suffocates her with a plastic dress bag. He moves her body to the attic.\n\nThe following morning, Mr. Harrison arrives at the school to pick up his daughter, but she fails to show up to their agreed meeting place. He quickly makes his way to the sorority house, where the housemother, Mrs. MacHenry, is surprised by Clare's absence. Meanwhile, Jess meets her boyfriend, Peter, a neurotic music student. She explains she is pregnant and planning to get an abortion, angering Peter, who attempts to intimidate her. In town, Mr. Harrison, accompanied by Barb and one of the other girls, Phyllis Carlson, attempt to report Clare as missing, while Jess quickly tells Clare's boyfriend Chris about Clare's sudden disappearance. They learn that another local girl named Janis Quaife has also seemingly vanished while walking home from school.\n\nAfter putting a drunken Barb to bed, Mr. Harrison, Chris, Jess, and Phyllis help search for Janis in a nearby park where she allegedly disappeared, hoping to turn up some sign of Clare. Meanwhile, Mrs. Mac plans to leave for her sister's home, only to be lured up into the attic, where she discovers Clare's body. The killer throws a crane hook into her face, hanging and killing her. In the park, Janis's disfigured body is found by the police and Jess returns home, while the search continues for Clare. Jess answers another obscene phone call and decides to file a report with the police, only for Peter to appear and surprise her. He attempts to persuade her into marriage for the sake of their child, but Jess adamantly refuses. Peter leaves in an emotional state, while Lieutenant Kenneth Fuller arrives to bug the telephone.\n\nA group of choir children arrive on the house's stoop to sing Christmas carols, distracting Jess. The killer enters Barb's room and murders her with a glass figurine; Barb's cries for help are drowned out by the singing children. One of the women in charge of the children ushers them away, having learned of Janis's murder. Jess experiences another unnerving phone call, in which the caller restates part of her argument with Peter. Lieutenant Fuller theorizes that Peter could be responsible, due to the caller's knowledge of the argument and his own mental fragility, but Jess doubts this. Moments later, Phyllis enters Barb's room and is ambushed by the killer, who murders her off-screen.\n\nJess gets another obscene phone call, in which the killer alludes to some sort of transgression between two children named Agnes and Billy. The call is long enough to be traced by Graham, a telephone company employee, and Sergeant Nash instructs Jess to leave the house immediately, as the calls have been traced to be coming from within the house. Concerned for Barb and Phyllis, Jess arms herself with a poker and ventures upstairs, where she discovers Barb and Phyllis's maimed figures. The killer appears and pursues Jess through the house; Jess locks herself in the cellar, only for Peter to appear outside one of the windows. He smashes the window to get to Jess, who proceeds to bludgeon him with the poker, assuming he is the killer.\n\nThe police arrive moments later, alerted by Jess's screams. They discover her barely conscious in the basement, with Peter's bloody remains next to her. They put Jess to bed and discuss the murders, unaware of the bodies of Clare and Mrs. MacHenry still in the attic. Jess is left in the house to rest, with a policeman standing outside. The killer climbs down from the attic as Jess sleeps in a nearby room. The house's telephone begins to ring, leaving Jess's fate unknown as the credits roll.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Olivia Hussey]] as Jess Bradford\n* [[Keir Dullea]] as Peter Smythe\n* [[Margot Kidder]] as Barbara \"Barb\" Coard\n* [[John Saxon]] as Lt. Kenneth Fuller\n* Marian Waldman as Mrs. MacHenry\n* [[Andrea Martin]] as Phyllis \"Phyl\" Carlson\n* James Edmond as Mr. Harrison\n* [[Doug McGrath|Douglas \"Doug\" McGrath]] as Sergeant Nash\n* [[Art Hindle|Arthur \"Art\" Hindle]] as Chris Hayden\n* [[Lynne Griffin]] as Clare Harrison\n* Michael Rapport as Patrick Cornell\n* [[Leslie Carlson|Leslie \"Les\" Carlson]] as Bill Graham\n* [[Martha Gibson]] as Mrs. Quaife\n* John Rutter as laughing detective\n* David Clement as Cogan {{small|(as Dave Clement)}}\n* Julian Reed as Officer Jennings\n* [[Nick Mancuso]] as [[Billy (Black Christmas)|Billy / Phone Voice]] (uncredited)<ref name=\"filmreel\">{{cite web|title=Slay bells ring: an interview with Black Christmas stars Lynne Griffin, Nick Mancuso and Doug McGrath|url=http://www.the-filmreel.com/2015/11/24/slay-bells-ring-an-interview-with-black-christmas-stars-lynne-griffin-nick-mancuso-and-doug-mcgrath/|work=The Film Reel|accessdate=December 18, 2016|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Power2019\">{{cite web|last1=Power|first1=Ed|title=The curse of Black Christmas: the man behind The Prowler on the slasher film that ruined his career|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/curse-black-christmas-man-behind-prowler-slasher-film-ruined/|website=Telegraph.co.uk|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=January 13, 2020|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> \n** [[Bob Clark]] as Billy's shadow / Phone Voice (uncredited)<ref name=\"Chiller\">{{cite web|title=13 Things You Didn't Know About 'Black Christmas'|url=http://www.chillertv.com/friday13/13-things-you-didn%E2%80%99t-know-about-black-christmas|work=[[Chiller (TV channel)]]|date=December 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archivedate=December 29, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229181231/http://www.chillertv.com/friday13/13-things-you-didn%E2%80%99t-know-about-black-christmas}}</ref>\n** Albert J. Dunk as Billy's POV (uncredited)<ref name=\"iconsoffright05\">{{cite web |last1=DuFort-Leavy |first1=Lyne |last2=Duffin |first2=Dan |title=Bob Clark interview - BLACK CHRISTMAS, A CHRISTMAS STORY, CHILDREN SHOULDN'T P |url=http://www.iconsoffright.com/IV_BClark.htm |website=IconsofFright.com |publisher=Icons of Fright |accessdate=25 March 2019 |date=May 2005}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\n{{expand section|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Development===\n''Black Christmas'' was  initially developed by Canadian screenwriter Roy Moore, who wrote the screenplay under the title ''Stop Me''.<ref name=onscreen/> Inspirations for the film came from the [[urban legend]] known as \"[[The Babysitter and the Man Upstairs]]\",<ref name=\"TCM\">{{cite web|author=Smith, Richard Harland |title=Black Christmas (1974)|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/410638%7C0/Black-Christmas.html|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> which had become widespread during the 1970s.<ref name=\"Brunvand2012\">{{cite book|author=Jan Harold Brunvand|title=Encyclopedia of Urban Legends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9xOb-19lXx8C&pg=PA47|year=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-720-8|pages=46\u201347}}</ref><ref name=\"Koven2008\">{{cite book|first=Mikel J.|last=Koven|title=Film, Folklore, and Urban Legends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qHZ4FwuZi7EC|year=2008|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6025-4|page=129}}</ref> Moore also claimed to have been inspired by a series of murders that occurred during the holiday season in the [[Westmount, Quebec|Westmount]] area of [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/homegrown-horror-5-canadian-scary-movies-you-need-to-watch-this-halloween-1.3825829|work=Canadian Broadcasting Company|title=Homegrown horror: 5 Canadian scary movies you need to watch this Halloween|date=October 28, 2016|author=Dupuis, Chris|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"duffin2006\">{{cite video|people=Dan Duffin (Director)|title=The 12 Days of 'Black Christmas'|medium=DVD|location=Canada|publisher=Critical Mass Releasing|date=2006}}</ref> As noted in an article for ''[[The Telegraph (London)|The Telegraph]]'', the murders, which occurred in 1943, were perpetrated by a fourteen-year-old boy who [[Familicide|bludgeoned several of his family members to death]].<ref name=\"Power2019\"/>\nFilm producers Harvey Sherman and Richard Schouten had Timothy Bond rewrite the script to give it a university setting.<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref name=legacy>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas Legacy (documentary)|work=Black Christmas|type=Blu-ray|medium=|publisher=Scream Factory|year=2016}}</ref> Clark, who had felt the original script was too much of a straightforward slasher film, made several alterations in dialogue,<ref name=\"TCM\"/> and also incorporated humorous elements into the film, particularly the drunkenness of Barb, and Mrs. Mac, who Clark based on his aunt.<ref name=onscreen/> Clark felt that college and high school students had not been depicted with \"any sense of reality\" in American film, and that he intended to capture the \"astuteness\" of young adults: \"College students\u2014even in 1974\u2014are astute people. They're not fools. It's not all 'bikinis, beach blankets, [and] bingo'.\"<ref name=onscreen/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Black Christmas main cast.png|thumb|right|upright|The central cast of ''Black Christmas'' {{small|(clockwise from left to right)}}: Olivia Hussey, Keir Dullea, John Saxon, and Margot Kidder]]\nOlivia Hussey, who had previously garnered international fame for her role as Juliet in [[Franco Zeffirelli]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1968 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' (1968), signed on to appear in the film after being told by a [[psychic]] that she would \"make a film in Canada that would earn a great deal of money.\"<ref name=onscreen/> Clark sought Keir Dullea to play the role of Peter based on his performance as Dave Bowman in ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' (1968).<ref name=onscreen/> The role of Mrs. Mac was offered to [[Bette Davis]],<ref name=\"TCM\"/> who declined the part.<ref name=onscreen/> Margot Kidder was cast in the role of Barb, and said she had been attracted to the character \"because she was wild and out of control\", and not a \"conventional leading\" part.<ref name=onscreen/> For the role of Clare Harrison, whose murder jump-starts the film's plot, Toronto native [[Lynne Griffin]] was cast after her mother, who was also her [[casting agent]] at the time, got her an audition. Griffin would later go on to star in ''[[Curtains (1983 film)|Curtains]]'' (1983), and in the acclaimed television series ''[[Wind at My Back]]'' (1996\u20132001).<ref name=\"griffininterview11\">{{cite web |title=Six for Her Scythe: An Interview with Lynne Griffin: Part I |url=http://www.terrortrap.com/interviews/lynnegriffin/ |website=Yerror Trap.com |publisher=The Terror Trap |accessdate=26 March 2019 |date=July 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Gilda Radner]] was offered the role of Phyllis Carlson. She accepted the part, but dropped out one month before filming began owing to ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' commitments, and was replaced by Andrea Martin.<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref name=onscreen/> The role of Lieutenant Fuller was originally given to [[Edmond O'Brien]]. Upon his arrival to the set, however, the producers realized he would be unable to fulfill the duties required of the part due to his failing health (stemming from [[Alzheimer's disease]]).<ref name=\"Chiller\" /> John Saxon, who had read the script prior, was called by the producers who offered him the role. He accepted, and had to arrive in Toronto from New York City within two days to begin shooting.<ref name=onscreen/> For the role of the film's antagonist, Italian-American actor [[Nick Mancuso]] was cast as one of the main voices in the phone call sequences. When [[audition]]ing for the role, director Clark had Mancuso sit in a chair facing away from him, so as not to see the actor's face. Clark then had Mancuso experiment with different voices in order to come up with one that was right for the character, with Clark later offering him the part.<ref name=\"Power2019\"/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Harthouse night.jpg|thumb|upright=1|left|[[Soldiers' Tower]] at the [[University of Toronto]] is featured in the film]]\n''Black Christmas'' was shot on location in [[Toronto]] in the winter of 1973\u201374. The house featured in the film had been discovered by Clark while scouting for locations, and its owners agreed to lease the home for the production.<ref name=onscreen/> Additional photography was completed on the [[University of Toronto]] campus.<ref name=onscreen/> According to John Saxon, Clark had meticulously drawn out storyboards with key shots, which he brought to the film set each day: \"I could understand exactly what I thought he needed, and the scene needed.\"<ref name=onscreen/> Scenes in the film involving [[POV shot]] of Billy scaling the house was accomplished through the use of a rig designed by [[camera operator]] Bert Dunk, which was attached to Dunk's head as he climbed up the side of the house.<ref name=\"iconsoffright05\" /> Griffin's death scene, which was shot with a handheld camera in a real closet, was accomplished in only a couple of takes. According to Griffin, her character's surprise as the killer lunges from the closet was genuine as the actress later recalled: \"it was a total shock because I didn't really know when to expect him to jump out!\" Shots of Clare's corpse in the rocking chair required the actress to wear an actual plastic bag over her head for extended periods of time. Griffin would also state that these scenes came relatively easy for her, \"I was actually, and still am, a fairly good swimmer so I could hold my breath for a long time. And I could also keep my eyes open for a long time without blinking.\"<ref name=\"griffininterview11\" />\n\nMargot Kidder remembered shooting the film as being \"fun. I really bonded with Andrea Martin, filming in Toronto and Ontario. Olivia Hussey was a bit of an odd one. She was obsessed with the idea of falling in love with [[Paul McCartney]] through her psychic. We were a little hard on her for things like that.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Random Roles: Margot Kidder|url=https://avclub.com/article/random-roles-margot-kidder-24554|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=March 3, 2009|accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nThe composer of the film's score, Carl Zittrer, stated in an interview that he created the film's mysterious music by [[Prepared piano|tying forks, combs, and knives onto the strings of the piano]] to warp the sound of the keys.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/> Zittrer also stated that he would distort the sound further by recording its sound onto an audiotape and make the sound slower.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/> The audio for the disturbing phone calls was performed by multiple actors including Mancuso<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref name=\"Power2019\"/> and director Bob Clark.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/> Mancuso stated in an interview that he stood on his head during the recording sessions to compress his [[thorax]] and make his voice sound more demented.<ref name=\"filmreel\"/> Mancuso spent only three days recording dialogue for the character, later recalling the experience as being very \"[[avant-garde]]\", with Clark encouraging him to improvise with the character's voice.<ref name=\"Power2019\"/>\n\nDuring preparation in 1975 for the film's American release, [[Warner Bros.]] studio executives asked Clark to change the concluding scene to show Clare's boyfriend, Chris, appear in front of Jess and say, \"Agnes, don't tell them what we did\" before killing her. However, Clark insisted on keeping the ending ambiguous. The original title of the film was initially planned to be ''Stop Me''.<ref name=\"TCM\"/> Clark has stated in an interview that he came up with the film's official title, saying that he enjoyed the irony of a dark event occurring during a festive holiday. According to Clark as well, Warner Bros. changed the title to ''Silent Night, Evil Night'' for the United States theatrical release.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/>\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical distribution===\n''Black Christmas'' was distributed in Canada by Ambassador Film Distributors and released in Toronto on October 11, 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/canadian-feature-film-database/Pages/item.aspx?IdNumber=541&DotsIdNumber=|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|title=Black Christmas|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>  In the United States, [[Warner Bros.]] released the film in tandem with the [[Christmas]] season on December 20, 1974.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|title=Black Christmas (1974)|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=blackchristmas74.htm|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref> For the American release, Warner Bros. initially changed the title to ''Silent Night, Evil Night'', worried that the original title would mislead audiences into believing the film was a [[blaxploitation]] movie.<ref name=onscreen/> They retracted the title after the initial release, restoring it to ''Black Christmas'' for subsequent screenings.<ref name=onscreen/>\n\nThe film later screened in October 1975 in New York City and Chicago,<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite news |title=Screen: Murky Whodunit; 'Black Christmas' Is at Local Theaters|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 20, 1975|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0E12F63E5C1A7493C2AB178BD95F418785F9|accessdate= June 4, 2012}}</ref> as well as 19 theaters in Los Angeles, where it generated considerable ticket sales. This prompted Warner Bros. to expand the release to a total of 70 theaters nationwide in time for Halloween, but the film only generated a daily average of $700 per theater, per day, after which Warner Bros. withdrew the film from circulation in December.<ref>{{cite book|title=Blood Money: A History of the First Teen Slasher Film Cycle|p=77|author=Nowell, Richard|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic|year=2010|isbn=978-1-441-12496-8}}</ref> The film had previously screened under the alternative title ''Silent Night, Evil Night'' in Virginia in July 1975.<ref name=\"ref3\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Edward|title=Horror Cliches: Up from the Dead, and Still Fun|newspaper=[[The Free Lance\u2013Star]]|date= July 14, 1975|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uIgTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KosDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1021,2184693&dq=silent-night-evil-night&hl=en|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOverall, ''Black Christmas'' grossed over $4,053,000 internationally, managing to earn more than its budget of $620,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Justice|first=Chris|title=Black Christmas (1974)|url=http://classic-horror.com/reviews/black_christmas_1974|publisher=Classic-Horror|date=October 27, 2006}}</ref> When released in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], the [[BBFC]] had the word \"cunt\" removed, as well as several other crude and sexual references during the first obscene phone call.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n===Television premiere controversy===\nThe film, under the title ''Stranger in the House'', was set to make its network television premiere on Saturday night, January 28, 1978, on [[NBC]]'s weekly \"Saturday Night at the Movies\". Two weeks prior to its premiere, the [[Chi Omega]] Sorority House on the campus of [[Florida State University]] in [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]] was the scene of a double murder in which two Chi Omega sisters, asleep in their beds, were bludgeoned to death. The killer then went to a nearby room in the sorority house and violently attacked two more sleeping co-eds, who survived. The killer was later identified as [[Ted Bundy]], who was executed for this and other homicides on January 24, 1989.<ref name=\"ap\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/134823910/?terms=%22Stranger%2Bin%2Bthe%2BHouse%22|title=Network Offers TV Alternative for Terror Film|agency=Associated Press|date=January 25, 1978|work=The Palm Beach Post|page=61|access-date=July 14, 2016|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nA few days before the movie was set to premiere on network television Florida's then-Governor [[Reubin Askew]] contacted NBC President Robert Mullholland to request the movie not be shown due to its all-too-similar theme as the murders of sorority sisters by an unknown madman at the Chi Omega Sorority House. On Tuesday, January 24, NBC-TV gave several of its affiliates in Florida, Georgia, and Alabama, the option of showing an alternate movie, ''[[Doc Savage: The Man of Bronze]]'', in place of ''Stranger in the House''.<ref name=\"ap\"/>\n\n\"The network said in a statement issued yesterday in New York City that it was responding to concern voiced by the affiliates because of the murder of two coeds this month in a sorority house at Florida State University in Tallahassee.\"<ref name=\"ap\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nDuring its initial release, the film had garnered mixed reviews. [[A. H. Weiler]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a whodunit that raises the question as to why was it made.\"<ref>{{Cite news |date= October 20, 1975 |title=Screen: Murky Whodunit: 'Black Christmas' Is at Local Theaters |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/movies/black-christmas-review.html |page=45 |accessdate= June 1, 2019}} {{rating|1|5}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film \"a bloody, senseless kill-for-kicks feature, [that] exploits unnecessary violence in a university sorority house operated by an implausibly alcoholic ex-hoofer. Its slow-paced, murky tale involves an obscene telephone caller who apparently delights in killing the girls off one by one, even the hapless house-mother.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|title=Black Christmas|date=December 31, 1974|accessdate=November 18, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231231035/https://variety.com/1973/film/reviews/black-christmas-1200423278/|archivedate=December 31, 2013|url=https://variety.com/1973/film/reviews/black-christmas-1200423278/}}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 1.5 stars out of 4 and called it a \"routine shocker\" that \"is notable only for indicating the kind of junk roles that talented actresses are forced to play in the movies.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (October 6, 1975). \"'Master Gunfighter' a whopping misfire\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 3, p. 6.</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote, \"Before it maddeningly overreaches in a gratuitously evasive ending, 'Black Christmas' (opening today at selected theaters) is a smart, stylish Canadian-made little horror picture that is completely diverting ... It may well be that its makers simply couldn't figure out how to end it.\"<ref>Thomas, Kevin (August 6, 1975). \"Gothic Tale of a 'Black Christmas'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 12.</ref>\n\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Black Christmas'' holds a 71% approval rating based on 34 reviews, with an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 6.26/10. The critical consensus reads: \"The rare slasher with enough intelligence to wind up the tension between bloody outbursts, ''Black Christmas'' offers fiendishly enjoyable holiday viewing for genre fans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/1002484-black_christmas/ |title=Black Christmas (1974) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> Heidi Martinuzzi of ''[[Film Threat]]'' called the film \"innovative\" and praised the leading actresses, [[Olivia Hussey]] and [[Margot Kidder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/6782/ |title=Black Christmas |work=[[Film Threat]] |date= December 24, 2004|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]'' awarded the film three out of four stars, writing: \"Although strictly standard fare, the material is elevated somewhat through Clark's skillful handling of such plot devices as obscene phone calls from the killer to the girls via the upstairs phone and a nicely handled twist ending, which provides a genuine shock.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[TV Guide]]|title=Black Christmas (1974) Review|accessdate=November 20, 2017|url=http://www.tvguide.com/movies/black-christmas/review/108583/}} {{rating|3|4}}</ref>\nAuthor and film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] gave the film two and a half out of a possible four stars calling it \"bizarre\" but also praised Kidder's performance as a standout.<ref name=\"maltin14\">{{cite book|last1=Maltin|first1=Leonard|last2=Carson|first2=Darwyn|last3=Sader|first3=Luke|title=Leonard Maltin's 2014 Movie Guide|publisher=Penguin Press|isbn=978-0-451-41810-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780451418104/page/137 137]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780451418104/page/137}}</ref> The ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' film guide noted that the film \"manages a good slice of old-fashioned suspense.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timeout.com/film/reviews/67908/black_christmas.html|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|location=London|title=Black Christmas|accessdate=November 9, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107083055/https://timeout.com/film/reviews/67908/black_christmas.html|archivedate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Black Christmas'' has been released on [[DVD]] several times in North America. A 25th Anniversary edition was released in Canada on November 6, 2001 by Critical Mass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/5126/black-christmas-25th-anniversary/|work=DVD Talk|title=Black Christmas 25th Anniversary: DVD|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref> This edition only contains the theatrical trailer as a bonus feature.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas|publisher=Critical Mass|year=2001|type=DVD}}</ref> The following year, on December 3, 2002, Critical Mass released a Collector's Edition of the film on DVD with making-of documentaries, two audio commentary tracks, and reversible English and French cover artwork.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas|publisher=Critical Mass|year=2002|isbn=1-55259-366-5|type=DVD}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2006, Critical Mass released a third \"Special Edition\" DVD with a newly remastered transfer, two original scenes with newly-uncovered vocal tracks, a new documentary on the making of the film, and cast and crew interviews.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas|year=2006|publisher=Critical Mass|type=DVD}}</ref> This edition was later released on [[Blu-ray]] on November 11, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|work=Blu-ray.com|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Black-Christmas-Blu-ray/1164/|title=Black Christmas Blu-ray|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Anchor Bay Entertainment|Anchor Bay]] released a Blu-ray and DVD in Canada, titled the \"Season's Grievings Edition\". It contains the same transfer of the film as the \"Special Edition\" release and all previous bonus content, plus the addition of: a new documentary (\"Black Christmas Legacy\"), a 40th anniversary panel from [[Fan Expo Canada|Fan Expo]] 2014, a new commentary track featuring [[Nick Mancuso]] as the character \"Billy\", a new retrospective booklet written by [[Rue Morgue (magazine)|Rue Morgue Magazine]], and new packaging art by Gary Pullin ([[art director]] of Rue Morgue Magazine). This new edition was released on Blu-ray and DVD on November 24, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/exclusive-trailer-anchor-bay-canadas-black-christmas-blu-ray-seasons-grievings-edition/|work=Fangoria|title=Exclusive Trailer: Anchor Bay Canada's \"BLACK CHRISTMAS\" Blu-ray, 'Seasons Grievings' Edition!|date=October 15, 2015|accessdate=November 20, 2017|author=Hanley, Ken W.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044643/http://www.fangoria.com/new/exclusive-trailer-anchor-bay-canadas-black-christmas-blu-ray-seasons-grievings-edition/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, [[Scream Factory]] released the film in a collector's edition Blu-ray on December 13, 2016 with a new transfer and new extras.<ref name=dvd>{{cite web|work=DVD Talk|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/71725/black-christmas-collectors-edition/|title=Black Christmas: Collector's Edition|author=Spurlin, Thomas|date=January 20, 2017|accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref> The Scream Factory release collates all of the bonus materials from the previous releases by Critical Mass and Anchor Bay, and also features the 2006 Critical Mass restoration of the film in the bonus materials.<ref name=dvd/>\n\n==Accolades==\n'''Saturn Award-Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films'''\n* 1976: Nominated, Best Horror Film{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n'''Canadian Film Awards'''\n* 1975: Won, Best Sound Editing in a Feature \u2013 Kenneth Heeley-Ray<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Cinema Canada]]|issue=18\u201324|year=1975|p=25|title=Canadian Film Awards|publisher=Cinema Canada Magazine Foundation}}</ref>\n* 1975: Won, Best Performance by a Lead Actress \u2013 [[Margot Kidder]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Guide to the Cinema(s) of Canada|editor=Rist, Peter|p=112|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2001|isbn=978-0-313-29931-5}}</ref>\n* 1975: Nominee, [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Feature Film]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Best-film showdown: 11 vie for all-Canadian honours |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18703453/|newspaper=[[Ottawa Journal]]|date=October 3, 1975|page=39|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = March 28, 2018 }} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n'''Edgar Allan Poe Awards'''\n* 1976: Nominated, Best Motion Picture \u2013 A. Roy Moore<ref>{{cite book|title=The Christmas Encyclopedia|edition=3rd|p=43|author=Crump, William D.|year=2013|publisher=McFarland|isbn= 978-1-476-60573-9}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n''Black Christmas'' eventually gained a [[Cult film|cult following]], and is notable for being one of the earliest [[slasher film]]s. It went on to inspire other slasher films, the biggest one of all being [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' (which was apparently inspired by Clark suggesting what a ''Black Christmas'' sequel would be like).<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=John|title=How 'Halloween' Was Basically an Unofficial 'Black Christmas' Sequel|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3413469/halloween-basically-unofficial-black-christmas-sequel|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=November 11, 2016|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=onscreen>{{cite episode|people=Orchard, Tristan (dir.); Clark, Bob; Kidder, Margot; Dullea, Keir|display-authors=etal|series=On Screen!|publisher=Canadian Television Fund|title= Black Christmas|airdate=July 22, 2005|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1074369/}}</ref>{{sfn|Muir|2011|p=315}}\n\n''Black Christmas'' has been included in multiple lists in various media outlets as one of the greatest horror films ever made. The film ranked No. 87 on ''[[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s ''[[The 100 Scariest Movie Moments]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dirks|first=Tim|title=Greatest Scariest Movie Moments and Scenes (B)|url=http://www.filmsite.org/scariestscenes2.html|publisher=AMC Filmsite}}</ref> It was ranked at No. 67 in ''[[IndieWire]]''s ''The 100 Best Horror Movies of All Time'', its entry stating \"The plot sounds formulaic, but ''Black Christmas'' remains timeless thanks to its terrifying and elusive killer, 'Billy,' whose backstory is never revealed, as well as a foreboding ending that doesn't offer much hope for the film's Final Girl\".<ref name=\"100besthorrormovies\">{{cite web |last1=Righetti |first1=Jamie |title=The 100 Best Horror Movies of All Time |url=https://www.indiewire.com/feature/best-horror-movies-all-time-scary-films-1202012183/4/ |website=IndieWire.com |publisher=IndieWire |accessdate=3 December 2019 |page=4 |date=9 October 2019}}</ref> [[Thrillist]]'s Scott Weinberg, in his article ''The 75 Best Horror Movies of All Time'', ranked the film at No. 48.<ref name=\"weinberg19\">{{cite web |last1=Weinberg |first1=Scott |title=Best Horror Movies of All Time, Ranked: Scariest Movies Ever Made - Thrillist |url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-horror-movies-ever |website=Thrillist.com |publisher=Thrillist |accessdate=3 December 2019 |date=22 October 2019}}</ref> Paul Schrodt of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' placed the film at No. 23 in his list of the ''50 Best Horror Films of All Time''.<ref name=\"esquirelist\">{{cite web |last1=Schrodt |first1=Paul |title=50 Best Horror Movies of All Time - Scariest Horror Films Ever Made |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/g3383/best-horror-movies-of-all-time/ |website=Esquire.com |publisher=Esquire |accessdate=3 December 2019 |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> In 2017, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' magazine named ''Black Christmas'' the 2nd-best slasher film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/best-slasher-movies-of-all-time/black-christmas|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|title=The Best Slasher Films of All Time|date=October 23, 2017|last=Barone|first=Matt|access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref> The following year, ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' listed it the 3rd-best slasher film of all time,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/08/the-50-best-slasher-movies-of-all-time.html|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|title=The Best Slasher Movies of All Time|date=August 8, 2018|last=Vorel|first=Jim|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712181827/https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/08/the-50-best-slasher-movies-of-all-time.html|archive-date=July 12, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref> while also placing the character Jess Bradford at #1 in their list of \"20 Best 'Final Girls' in Horror Movie History\".<ref name=\"finalgirllist16\">{{cite web |last1=Vorel |first1=Jim |title=The 20 Best \"Final Girls\" in Horror Movie History |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/movies/final-girls/the-20-best-final-girls-in-horror-movie-history/ |website=PasteMagazine.com |publisher=Paste Magazine |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=October 4, 2016}}</ref>  Film critic Tim Dirks of the film-review website [[Filmsite.org]] added the film to his list of films featuring the \"Greatest Film Plot Twists, Film Spoilers and Surprise Endings\", based on the film's major [[plot twist]]s- the revelation that the real killer was hidden inside the unsearched attic, and Jess' implied murder.<ref name=\"filmsite\">{{cite web |last1=Dirks |first1=Tim |title=Greatest Movie Plot Twists, Spoilers and Surprise Endings |url=https://www.filmsite.org/greattwists5.html |website=Filmsite.org |publisher=[[AMC (TV channel)|American Movie Classics Company, Inc.]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOlivia Hussey told [[Bravo (U.S. TV network)|Bravo]] during an interview about their ''100 Scariest Movie Moments'' series, that when she met [[Steve Martin]] for the first time, he told her she starred in one of his favorite movies of all time. Hussey initially thought he was referring to ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1968 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'', but was surprised when Martin said it was ''Black Christmas'' and that he had seen the film 27 times.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stitzel|first=Kelly|title=Horror Movie Marathon: Part The Last|url=http://popdose.com/horror-movie-marathon-part-the-last/|publisher=Popdose|date=October 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Related works==\n===Novelization===\nA novelization of the film written by Lee Hays was published in 1976 by Popular Library.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hays, Lee|title=Black Christmas|year=1976|publisher=Popular Library|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8568273-black-christmas}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-christmas-review-first-slasher-film-genre|title=The Low-Budget Canadian Film That Inspired 'Halloween' and Launched an Entire Horror Genre|last=Searles|first=Jourdain|date=2018-10-30|website=Thrillist|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n===Remakes===\n{{Main|Black Christmas (2006 film)|Black Christmas (2019 film)}}\n''Black Christmas'' has been remade on two separate occasions, with the films differing significantly from the original.\n\nThe first remake was directed by [[Glen Morgan]] and was released on December 25, 2006. It is loosely based on the original film, containing more graphic content and a focus into the past of Billy. [[Andrea Martin]] was the only original cast member to appear in the film, and [[Bob Clark]] served as an executive producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/markets-festivals/bob-clark-67-director-1117962526/|title=Bob Clark, 67, director|last=Garrett|first=Diane|work=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=April 4, 2007|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2019, a new remake was announced by [[Blumhouse Productions]]. Directed and written by [[Sophia Takal]], co-written by April Wolfe and produced by [[Jason Blum]]. Principal photography began on June 24 and wrapped on July 31, 2019, in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BzEbM8tp8Al/|title=Day 1! #blackchristmas|last=Hendricks|first=Adam|via=[[Instagram]]|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B0j_TQfJE2Q/|title=Day 27! #blackchristmas|last=Hendricks|first=Adam|via=[[Instagram]]|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B0lC_vVJbxM/|title=THAT\u2019S A WRAP!! #blackchristmas|last=Hendricks|first=Adam|via=[[Instagram]]|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref> Starring [[Imogen Poots]] and [[Cary Elwes]], the film was released on December 13, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/blumhouse-black-christmas-remake-sophia-takal-imogen-poots/|title=Blumhouse to Remake \u2018Black Christmas\u2019 with Director Sophia Takal|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614002737/https://collider.com/blumhouse-black-christmas-remake-sophia-takal-imogen-poots/|archive-date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring home invasions]]\n* [[Holiday horror]]\n* [[List of films set around Christmas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite book|last=Muir|first=John Kenneth|author-link=John Kenneth Muir|title=Horror Films of the 1970s|year=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-786-49156-8|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0071222|title=Black Christmas}}\n* {{Allmovie title|5838|Black Christmas}}\n* {{mojo title|blackchristmas74|Black Christmas}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=1002484-black_christmas|title=Black Christmas}}\n* {{tcmdb title|68859|Black Christmas}}\n\n{{Black Christmas}}\n{{Bob Clark}}\n{{Warner Christmas films}}\n\n[[Category:1970s Christmas films]]\n[[Category:1970s slasher films]]\n[[Category:1974 films]]\n[[Category:1974 horror films]]\n[[Category:Black Christmas (film series)]]\n[[Category:Canadian Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian independent films]]\n[[Category:Canadian serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Canadian slasher films]]\n[[Category:Christmas horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Exploitation films]]\n[[Category:Films about fraternities and sororities]]\n[[Category:Films about fratricide and sororicide]]\n[[Category:Films based on urban legends]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bob Clark]]\n[[Category:Films set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Home invasions in film]]\n[[Category:Pregnancy films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n", "text_old": "{{missing information|the film's themes|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Black Christmas\n| image          = File:Black Christmas (1974) poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Bob Clark]]\n| producer       = Bob Clark\n| writer         = A. Roy Moore\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Olivia Hussey]]\n* [[Keir Dullea]]\n* [[Margot Kidder]]\n* [[John Saxon]]\n}} <!-- The four actors listed only poster only, do not list anyone else. -->\n| music          = Carl Zittrer\n| cinematography = Reginald H. Morris\n| editing        = Stan Cole\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Telefilm Canada|Canadian Film Development Corportation]]\n* Film Funding Ltd.\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* Ambassador Film Distributors (Canada)\n* [[Warner Bros.]] (USA/International)\n}}\n| released       = {{start date|1974|10|11|Toronto}}\n| runtime        = 98 minutes{{sfn|Muir|2011|p=314}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/black-christmas-1974 |title=Black Christmas (1974) |website=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| country        = Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $620,000\n| gross          = $4.1 million\n}}\n\n'''''Black Christmas''''' ([[Canadian French]]: ''No\u00ebl tragique'') is a 1974 Canadian [[horror]] produced and directed by [[Bob Clark]], and written by A. Roy Moore. It stars [[Olivia Hussey]], [[Keir Dullea]], [[Margot Kidder]], [[Andrea Martin]], Marian Waldman, [[Lynne Griffin]] and [[John Saxon]]. The story follows a group of sorority sisters who receive threatening phone calls and are eventually stalked and murdered by a deranged killer during the [[Christmas]] season. It is the first film in the [[Black Christmas (film series)|''Black Christmas'' series]].\n\nInspired by the urban legend \"[[The babysitter and the man upstairs]]\" and a series of murders that took place in the [[Westmount, Quebec|Westmount section]] of [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Moore wrote the screenplay under the title ''Stop Me''. The filmmakers made numerous alterations to the script, primarily the shifting to a university setting with young adult characters. It was shot in Toronto in 1974 on an estimated budget of $620,000, and was distributed by [[Warner Bros.]] in North America.\n\n''Black Christmas'' was released on October 11, 1974, in Canada and December 20 in the United States under the title '''''Silent Night, Evil Night'''''. Upon its release, the film received mixed reviews, but it has since received critical re-appraisal, with film historians noting it for being one of the earliest slasher films.<ref>{{Cite book |author= Paszylx, Bart\u0142omiej |title=The Pleasure and Pain of Cult Horror Films: An Historical Survey |year=2009 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-0-786-43695-8 |pages=135\u20136}}</ref> It is also praised for concluding without revealing the identity of its villain, as well as serving as an influence on [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' (1978). Aside from its earning a [[cult following]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Philip|title=Decade of Nightmares: The End of the Sixties and the Making of Eighties America|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-195-34158-4|p=[https://archive.org/details/decadeofnightmar00jenk/page/146 146]|url=https://archive.org/details/decadeofnightmar00jenk/page/146}}</ref> since its release, a novelization written by Lee Hays was published in 1976.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Billy (Black Christmas)|An unseen and disoriented man]] climbs up into the attic of a sorority house, where the tenants are celebrating with a Christmas party. One of the girls, Jess, answers an obscene phone call from a mentally unstable man who is implied to call the house regularly. She summons her fellow students into the room, where they listen as the caller screams and curses them on the phone. When one of the girls, foul-mouthed Barb, takes the phone from Jess, she incites the caller, who in turn promises to kill her. Barb argues with a younger student, Clare Harrison, who implies that the caller could be a serial rapist, before Clare returns to her bedroom to finish packing for Christmas break. The disoriented man lures Clare into her closet, where he suffocates her with a plastic dress bag. He moves her body to the attic.\n\nThe following morning, Mr. Harrison arrives at the school to pick up his daughter, but she fails to show up to their agreed meeting place. He quickly makes his way to the sorority house, where the housemother, Mrs. MacHenry, is surprised by Clare's absence. Meanwhile, Jess meets her boyfriend, Peter, a neurotic music student. She explains she is pregnant and planning to get an abortion, angering Peter, who attempts to intimidate her. In town, Mr. Harrison, accompanied by Barb and one of the other girls, Phyllis Carlson, attempt to report Clare as missing, while Jess quickly tells Clare's boyfriend Chris about Clare's sudden disappearance. They learn that another local girl named Janis Quaife has also seemingly vanished while walking home from school.\n\nAfter putting a drunken Barb to bed, Mr. Harrison, Chris, Jess, and Phyllis help search for Janis in a nearby park where she allegedly disappeared, hoping to turn up some sign of Clare. Meanwhile, Mrs. Mac plans to leave for her sister's home, only to be lured up into the attic, where she discovers Clare's body. The killer throws a crane hook into her face, hanging and killing her. In the park, Janis's disfigured body is found by the police and Jess returns home, while the search continues for Clare. Jess answers another obscene phone call and decides to file a report with the police, only for Peter to appear and surprise her. He attempts to persuade her into marriage for the sake of their child, but Jess adamantly refuses. Peter leaves in an emotional state, while Lieutenant Kenneth Fuller arrives to bug the telephone.\n\nA group of choir children arrive on the house's stoop to sing Christmas carols, distracting Jess. The killer enters Barb's room and murders her with a glass figurine; Barb's cries for help are drowned out by the singing children. One of the women in charge of the children ushers them away, having learned of Janis's murder. Jess experiences another unnerving phone call, in which the caller restates part of her argument with Peter. Lieutenant Fuller theorizes that Peter could be responsible, due to the caller's knowledge of the argument and his own mental fragility, but Jess doubts this. Moments later, Phyllis enters Barb's room and is ambushed by the killer, who murders her off-screen.\n\nJess gets another obscene phone call, in which the killer alludes to some sort of transgression between two children named Agnes and Billy. The call is long enough to be traced by Graham, a telephone company employee, and Sergeant Nash instructs Jess to leave the house immediately, as the calls have been traced to be coming from within the house. Concerned for Barb and Phyllis, Jess arms herself with a poker and ventures upstairs, where she discovers Barb and Phyllis's maimed figures. The killer appears and pursues Jess through the house; Jess locks herself in the cellar, only for Peter to appear outside one of the windows. He smashes the window to get to Jess, who proceeds to bludgeon him with the poker, assuming he is the killer.\n\nThe police arrive moments later, alerted by Jess's screams. They discover her barely conscious in the basement, with Peter's bloody remains next to her. They put Jess to bed and discuss the murders, unaware of the bodies of Clare and Mrs. MacHenry still in the attic. Jess is left in the house to rest, with a policeman standing outside. The killer climbs down from the attic as Jess sleeps in a nearby room. The house's telephone begins to ring, leaving Jess's fate unknown as the credits roll.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Olivia Hussey]] as Jess Bradford\n* [[Keir Dullea]] as Peter Smythe\n* [[Margot Kidder]] as Barbara \"Barb\" Coard\n* [[John Saxon]] as Lt. Kenneth Fuller\n* Marian Waldman as Mrs. MacHenry\n* [[Andrea Martin]] as Phyllis \"Phyl\" Carlson\n* James Edmond as Mr. Harrison\n* [[Doug McGrath|Douglas \"Doug\" McGrath]] as Sergeant Nash\n* [[Art Hindle|Arthur \"Art\" Hindle]] as Chris Hayden\n* [[Lynne Griffin]] as Clare Harrison\n* Michael Rapport as Patrick Cornell\n* [[Leslie Carlson|Leslie \"Les\" Carlson]] as Bill Graham\n* [[Martha Gibson]] as Mrs. Quaife\n* John Rutter as laughing detective\n* David Clement as Cogan {{small|(as Dave Clement)}}\n* Julian Reed as Officer Jennings\n* [[Nick Mancuso]] as [[Billy (Black Christmas)|Billy / Phone Voice]] (uncredited)<ref name=\"filmreel\">{{cite web|title=Slay bells ring: an interview with Black Christmas stars Lynne Griffin, Nick Mancuso and Doug McGrath|url=http://www.the-filmreel.com/2015/11/24/slay-bells-ring-an-interview-with-black-christmas-stars-lynne-griffin-nick-mancuso-and-doug-mcgrath/|work=The Film Reel|accessdate=December 18, 2016|date=November 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Power2019\">{{cite web|last1=Power|first1=Ed|title=The curse of Black Christmas: the man behind The Prowler on the slasher film that ruined his career|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/0/curse-black-christmas-man-behind-prowler-slasher-film-ruined/|website=Telegraph.co.uk|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=January 13, 2020|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> \n** [[Bob Clark]] as Billy's shadow / Phone Voice (uncredited)<ref name=\"Chiller\">{{cite web|title=13 Things You Didn't Know About 'Black Christmas'|url=http://www.chillertv.com/friday13/13-things-you-didn%E2%80%99t-know-about-black-christmas|work=[[Chiller (TV channel)]]|date=December 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archivedate=December 29, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229181231/http://www.chillertv.com/friday13/13-things-you-didn%E2%80%99t-know-about-black-christmas}}</ref>\n** Albert J. Dunk as Billy's POV (uncredited)<ref name=\"iconsoffright05\">{{cite web |last1=DuFort-Leavy |first1=Lyne |last2=Duffin |first2=Dan |title=Bob Clark interview - BLACK CHRISTMAS, A CHRISTMAS STORY, CHILDREN SHOULDN'T P |url=http://www.iconsoffright.com/IV_BClark.htm |website=IconsofFright.com |publisher=Icons of Fright |accessdate=25 March 2019 |date=May 2005}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\n{{expand section|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Development===\n''Black Christmas'' was  initially developed by Canadian screenwriter Roy Moore, who wrote the screenplay under the title ''Stop Me''.<ref name=onscreen/> Inspirations for the film came from the [[urban legend]] known as \"[[The Babysitter and the Man Upstairs]]\",<ref name=\"TCM\">{{cite web|author=Smith, Richard Harland |title=Black Christmas (1974)|url=http://www.tcm.com/this-month/article/410638%7C0/Black-Christmas.html|work=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref> which had become widespread during the 1970s.<ref name=\"Brunvand2012\">{{cite book|author=Jan Harold Brunvand|title=Encyclopedia of Urban Legends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9xOb-19lXx8C&pg=PA47|year=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-59884-720-8|pages=46\u201347}}</ref><ref name=\"Koven2008\">{{cite book|first=Mikel J.|last=Koven|title=Film, Folklore, and Urban Legends|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qHZ4FwuZi7EC|year=2008|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6025-4|page=129}}</ref> Moore also claimed to have been inspired by a series of murders that occurred during the holiday season in the [[Westmount, Quebec|Westmount]] area of [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/homegrown-horror-5-canadian-scary-movies-you-need-to-watch-this-halloween-1.3825829|work=Canadian Broadcasting Company|title=Homegrown horror: 5 Canadian scary movies you need to watch this Halloween|date=October 28, 2016|author=Dupuis, Chris|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"duffin2006\">{{cite video|people=Dan Duffin (Director)|title=The 12 Days of 'Black Christmas'|medium=DVD|location=Canada|publisher=Critical Mass Releasing|date=2006}}</ref> As noted in an article for ''[[The Telegraph (London)|The Telegraph]]'', the murders, which occurred in 1943, were perpetrated by a fourteen-year-old boy who [[Familicide|bludgeoned several of his family members to death]].<ref name=\"Power2019\"/>\nFilm producers Harvey Sherman and Richard Schouten had Timothy Bond rewrite the script to give it a university setting.<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref name=legacy>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas Legacy (documentary)|work=Black Christmas|type=Blu-ray|medium=|publisher=Scream Factory|year=2016}}</ref> Clark, who had felt the original script was too much of a straightforward slasher film, made several alterations in dialogue,<ref name=\"TCM\"/> and also incorporated humorous elements into the film, particularly the drunkenness of Barb, and Mrs. Mac, who Clark based on his aunt.<ref name=onscreen/> Clark felt that college and high school students had not been depicted with \"any sense of reality\" in American film, and that he intended to capture the \"astuteness\" of young adults: \"College students\u2014even in 1974\u2014are astute people. They're not fools. It's not all 'bikinis, beach blankets, [and] bingo'.\"<ref name=onscreen/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Black Christmas main cast.png|thumb|right|upright|The central cast of ''Black Christmas'' {{small|(clockwise from left to right)}}: Olivia Hussey, Keir Dullea, John Saxon, and Margot Kidder]]\nOlivia Hussey, who had previously garnered international fame for her role as Juliet in [[Franco Zeffirelli]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1968 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'' (1968), signed on to appear in the film after being told by a [[psychic]] that she would \"make a film in Canada that would earn a great deal of money.\"<ref name=onscreen/> Clark sought Keir Dullea to play the role of Peter based on his performance as Dave Bowman in ''[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]]'' (1968).<ref name=onscreen/> The role of Mrs. Mac was offered to [[Bette Davis]],<ref name=\"TCM\"/> who declined the part.<ref name=onscreen/> Margot Kidder was cast in the role of Barb, and said she had been attracted to the character \"because she was wild and out of control\", and not a \"conventional leading\" part.<ref name=onscreen/> For the role of Clare Harrison, whose murder jump-starts the film's plot, Toronto native [[Lynne Griffin]] was cast after her mother, who was also her [[casting agent]] at the time, got her an audition. Griffin would later go on to star in ''[[Curtains (1983 film)|Curtains]]'' (1983), and in the acclaimed television series ''[[Wind at My Back]]'' (1996\u20132001).<ref name=\"griffininterview11\">{{cite web |title=Six for Her Scythe: An Interview with Lynne Griffin: Part I |url=http://www.terrortrap.com/interviews/lynnegriffin/ |website=Yerror Trap.com |publisher=The Terror Trap |accessdate=26 March 2019 |date=July 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Gilda Radner]] was offered the role of Phyllis Carlson. She accepted the part, but dropped out one month before filming began owing to ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' commitments, and was replaced by Andrea Martin.<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref name=onscreen/> The role of Lieutenant Fuller was originally given to [[Edmond O'Brien]]. Upon his arrival to the set, however, the producers realized he would be unable to fulfill the duties required of the part due to his failing health (stemming from [[Alzheimer's disease]]).<ref name=\"Chiller\" /> John Saxon, who had read the script prior, was called by the producers who offered him the role. He accepted, and had to arrive in Toronto from New York City within two days to begin shooting.<ref name=onscreen/> For the role of the film's antagonist, Italian-American actor [[Nick Mancuso]] was cast as one of the main voices in the phone call sequences. When [[audition]]ing for the role, director Clark had Mancuso sit in a chair facing away from him, so as not to see the actor's face. Clark then had Mancuso experiment with different voices in order to come up with one that was right for the character, with Clark later offering him the part.<ref name=\"Power2019\"/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Harthouse night.jpg|thumb|upright=1|left|[[Soldiers' Tower]] at the [[University of Toronto]] is featured in the film]]\n''Black Christmas'' was shot on location in [[Toronto]] in the winter of 1973\u201374. The house featured in the film had been discovered by Clark while scouting for locations, and its owners agreed to lease the home for the production.<ref name=onscreen/> Additional photography was completed on the [[University of Toronto]] campus.<ref name=onscreen/> According to John Saxon, Clark had meticulously drawn out storyboards with key shots, which he brought to the film set each day: \"I could understand exactly what I thought he needed, and the scene needed.\"<ref name=onscreen/> Scenes in the film involving [[POV shot]] of Billy scaling the house was accomplished through the use of a rig designed by [[camera operator]] Bert Dunk, which was attached to Dunk's head as he climbed up the side of the house.<ref name=\"iconsoffright05\" /> Griffin's death scene, which was shot with a handheld camera in a real closet, was accomplished in only a couple of takes. According to Griffin, her character's surprise as the killer lunges from the closet was genuine as the actress later recalled: \"it was a total shock because I didn't really know when to expect him to jump out!\" Shots of Clare's corpse in the rocking chair required the actress to wear an actual plastic bag over her head for extended periods of time. Griffin would also state that these scenes came relatively easy for her, \"I was actually, and still am, a fairly good swimmer so I could hold my breath for a long time. And I could also keep my eyes open for a long time without blinking.\"<ref name=\"griffininterview11\" />\n\nMargot Kidder remembered shooting the film as being \"fun. I really bonded with Andrea Martin, filming in Toronto and Ontario. Olivia Hussey was a bit of an odd one. She was obsessed with the idea of falling in love with [[Paul McCartney]] through her psychic. We were a little hard on her for things like that.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Random Roles: Margot Kidder|url=https://avclub.com/article/random-roles-margot-kidder-24554|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=March 3, 2009|accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nThe composer of the film's score, Carl Zittrer, stated in an interview that he created the film's mysterious music by [[Prepared piano|tying forks, combs, and knives onto the strings of the piano]] to warp the sound of the keys.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/> Zittrer also stated that he would distort the sound further by recording its sound onto an audiotape and make the sound slower.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/> The audio for the disturbing phone calls was performed by multiple actors including Mancuso<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref name=\"Power2019\"/> and director Bob Clark.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/> Mancuso stated in an interview that he stood on his head during the recording sessions to compress his [[thorax]] and make his voice sound more demented.<ref name=\"filmreel\"/> Mancuso spent only three days recording dialogue for the character, later recalling the experience as being very \"[[avant-garde]]\", with Clark encouraging him to improvise with the character's voice.<ref name=\"Power2019\"/>\n\nDuring preparation in 1975 for the film's American release, [[Warner Bros.]] studio executives asked Clark to change the concluding scene to show Clare's boyfriend, Chris, appear in front of Jess and say, \"Agnes, don't tell them what we did\" before killing her. However, Clark insisted on keeping the ending ambiguous. The original title of the film was initially planned to be ''Stop Me''.<ref name=\"TCM\"/> Clark has stated in an interview that he came up with the film's official title, saying that he enjoyed the irony of a dark event occurring during a festive holiday. According to Clark as well, Warner Bros. changed the title to ''Silent Night, Evil Night'' for the United States theatrical release.<ref name=\"Chiller\"/>\n\n==Release==\n===Theatrical distribution===\n''Black Christmas'' was distributed in Canada by Ambassador Film Distributors and released in Toronto on October 11, 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/canadian-feature-film-database/Pages/item.aspx?IdNumber=541&DotsIdNumber=|publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]]|title=Black Christmas|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>  In the United States, [[Warner Bros.]] released the film in tandem with the [[Christmas]] season on December 20, 1974.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|title=Black Christmas (1974)|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=blackchristmas74.htm|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref> For the American release, Warner Bros. initially changed the title to ''Silent Night, Evil Night'', worried that the original title would mislead audiences into believing the film was a [[blaxploitation]] movie.<ref name=onscreen/> They retracted the title after the initial release, restoring it to ''Black Christmas'' for subsequent screenings.<ref name=onscreen/>\n\nThe film later screened in October 1975 in New York City and Chicago,<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite news |title=Screen: Murky Whodunit; 'Black Christmas' Is at Local Theaters|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 20, 1975|url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0E12F63E5C1A7493C2AB178BD95F418785F9|accessdate= June 4, 2012}}</ref> as well as 19 theaters in Los Angeles, where it generated considerable ticket sales. This prompted Warner Bros. to expand the release to a total of 70 theaters nationwide in time for Halloween, but the film only generated a daily average of $700 per theater, per day, after which Warner Bros. withdrew the film from circulation in December.<ref>{{cite book|title=Blood Money: A History of the First Teen Slasher Film Cycle|p=77|author=Nowell, Richard|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic|year=2010|isbn=978-1-441-12496-8}}</ref> The film had previously screened under the alternative title ''Silent Night, Evil Night'' in Virginia in July 1975.<ref name=\"ref3\">{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Edward|title=Horror Cliches: Up from the Dead, and Still Fun|newspaper=[[The Free Lance\u2013Star]]|date= July 14, 1975|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=uIgTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KosDAAAAIBAJ&pg=1021,2184693&dq=silent-night-evil-night&hl=en|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nOverall, ''Black Christmas'' grossed over $4,053,000 internationally, managing to earn more than its budget of $620,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Justice|first=Chris|title=Black Christmas (1974)|url=http://classic-horror.com/reviews/black_christmas_1974|publisher=Classic-Horror|date=October 27, 2006}}</ref> When released in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], the [[BBFC]] had the word \"cunt\" removed, as well as several other crude and sexual references during the first obscene phone call.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\n===Television premiere controversy===\nThe film, under the title ''Stranger in the House'', was set to make its network television premiere on Saturday night, January 28, 1978, on [[NBC]]'s weekly \"Saturday Night at the Movies\". Two weeks prior to its premiere, the [[Chi Omega]] Sorority House on the campus of [[Florida State University]] in [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]] was the scene of a double murder in which two Chi Omega sisters, asleep in their beds, were bludgeoned to death. The killer then went to a nearby room in the sorority house and violently attacked two more sleeping co-eds, who survived. The killer was later identified as [[Ted Bundy]], who was executed for this and other homicides on January 24, 1989.<ref name=\"ap\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/134823910/?terms=%22Stranger%2Bin%2Bthe%2BHouse%22|title=Network Offers TV Alternative for Terror Film|agency=Associated Press|date=January 25, 1978|work=The Palm Beach Post|page=61|access-date=July 14, 2016|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nA few days before the movie was set to premiere on network television Florida's then-Governor [[Reubin Askew]] contacted NBC President Robert Mullholland to request the movie not be shown due to its all-too-similar theme as the murders of sorority sisters by an unknown madman at the Chi Omega Sorority House. On Tuesday, January 24, NBC-TV gave several of its affiliates in Florida, Georgia, and Alabama, the option of showing an alternate movie, ''[[Doc Savage: The Man of Bronze]]'', in place of ''Stranger in the House''.<ref name=\"ap\"/>\n\n\"The network said in a statement issued yesterday in New York City that it was responding to concern voiced by the affiliates because of the murder of two coeds this month in a sorority house at Florida State University in Tallahassee.\"<ref name=\"ap\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nDuring its initial release, the film had garnered mixed reviews. [[A. H. Weiler]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a whodunit that raises the question as to why was it made.\"<ref>{{Cite news |date= October 20, 1975 |title=Screen: Murky Whodunit: 'Black Christmas' Is at Local Theaters |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/11/movies/black-christmas-review.html |page=45 |accessdate= June 1, 2019}} {{rating|1|5}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called the film \"a bloody, senseless kill-for-kicks feature, [that] exploits unnecessary violence in a university sorority house operated by an implausibly alcoholic ex-hoofer. Its slow-paced, murky tale involves an obscene telephone caller who apparently delights in killing the girls off one by one, even the hapless house-mother.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|title=Black Christmas|date=December 31, 1974|accessdate=November 18, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231231035/https://variety.com/1973/film/reviews/black-christmas-1200423278/|archivedate=December 31, 2013|url=https://variety.com/1973/film/reviews/black-christmas-1200423278/}}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film 1.5 stars out of 4 and called it a \"routine shocker\" that \"is notable only for indicating the kind of junk roles that talented actresses are forced to play in the movies.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (October 6, 1975). \"'Master Gunfighter' a whopping misfire\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 3, p. 6.</ref> [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote, \"Before it maddeningly overreaches in a gratuitously evasive ending, 'Black Christmas' (opening today at selected theaters) is a smart, stylish Canadian-made little horror picture that is completely diverting ... It may well be that its makers simply couldn't figure out how to end it.\"<ref>Thomas, Kevin (August 6, 1975). \"Gothic Tale of a 'Black Christmas'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 12.</ref>\n\nOn the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''Black Christmas'' holds a 71% approval rating based on 34 reviews, with an [[weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 6.26/10. The critical consensus reads: \"The rare slasher with enough intelligence to wind up the tension between bloody outbursts, ''Black Christmas'' offers fiendishly enjoyable holiday viewing for genre fans.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rottentomatoes.com/m/1002484-black_christmas/ |title=Black Christmas (1974) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> Heidi Martinuzzi of ''[[Film Threat]]'' called the film \"innovative\" and praised the leading actresses, [[Olivia Hussey]] and [[Margot Kidder]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/6782/ |title=Black Christmas |work=[[Film Threat]] |date= December 24, 2004|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]'' awarded the film three out of four stars, writing: \"Although strictly standard fare, the material is elevated somewhat through Clark's skillful handling of such plot devices as obscene phone calls from the killer to the girls via the upstairs phone and a nicely handled twist ending, which provides a genuine shock.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=[[TV Guide]]|title=Black Christmas (1974) Review|accessdate=November 20, 2017|url=http://www.tvguide.com/movies/black-christmas/review/108583/}} {{rating|3|4}}</ref>\nAuthor and film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] gave the film two and a half out of a possible four stars calling it \"bizarre\" but also praised Kidder's performance as a standout.<ref name=\"maltin14\">{{cite book|last1=Maltin|first1=Leonard|last2=Carson|first2=Darwyn|last3=Sader|first3=Luke|title=Leonard Maltin's 2014 Movie Guide|publisher=Penguin Press|isbn=978-0-451-41810-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780451418104/page/137 137]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780451418104/page/137}}</ref> The ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' film guide noted that the film \"manages a good slice of old-fashioned suspense.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timeout.com/film/reviews/67908/black_christmas.html|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|location=London|title=Black Christmas|accessdate=November 9, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107083055/https://timeout.com/film/reviews/67908/black_christmas.html|archivedate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Black Christmas'' has been released on [[DVD]] several times in North America. A 25th Anniversary edition was released in Canada on November 6, 2001 by Critical Mass.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/5126/black-christmas-25th-anniversary/|work=DVD Talk|title=Black Christmas 25th Anniversary: DVD|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref> This edition only contains the theatrical trailer as a bonus feature.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas|publisher=Critical Mass|year=2001|type=DVD}}</ref> The following year, on December 3, 2002, Critical Mass released a Collector's Edition of the film on DVD with making-of documentaries, two audio commentary tracks, and reversible English and French cover artwork.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas|publisher=Critical Mass|year=2002|isbn=1-55259-366-5|type=DVD}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2006, Critical Mass released a third \"Special Edition\" DVD with a newly remastered transfer, two original scenes with newly-uncovered vocal tracks, a new documentary on the making of the film, and cast and crew interviews.<ref>{{cite av media|title=Black Christmas|year=2006|publisher=Critical Mass|type=DVD}}</ref> This edition was later released on [[Blu-ray]] on November 11, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|work=Blu-ray.com|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Black-Christmas-Blu-ray/1164/|title=Black Christmas Blu-ray|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Anchor Bay Entertainment|Anchor Bay]] released a Blu-ray and DVD in Canada, titled the \"Season's Grievings Edition\". It contains the same transfer of the film as the \"Special Edition\" release and all previous bonus content, plus the addition of: a new documentary (\"Black Christmas Legacy\"), a 40th anniversary panel from [[Fan Expo Canada|Fan Expo]] 2014, a new commentary track featuring [[Nick Mancuso]] as the character \"Billy\", a new retrospective booklet written by [[Rue Morgue (magazine)|Rue Morgue Magazine]], and new packaging art by Gary Pullin ([[art director]] of Rue Morgue Magazine). This new edition was released on Blu-ray and DVD on November 24, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/exclusive-trailer-anchor-bay-canadas-black-christmas-blu-ray-seasons-grievings-edition/|work=Fangoria|title=Exclusive Trailer: Anchor Bay Canada's \"BLACK CHRISTMAS\" Blu-ray, 'Seasons Grievings' Edition!|date=October 15, 2015|accessdate=November 20, 2017|author=Hanley, Ken W.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044643/http://www.fangoria.com/new/exclusive-trailer-anchor-bay-canadas-black-christmas-blu-ray-seasons-grievings-edition/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, [[Scream Factory]] released the film in a collector's edition Blu-ray on December 13, 2016 with a new transfer and new extras.<ref name=dvd>{{cite web|work=DVD Talk|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/71725/black-christmas-collectors-edition/|title=Black Christmas: Collector's Edition|author=Spurlin, Thomas|date=January 20, 2017|accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref> The Scream Factory release collates all of the bonus materials from the previous releases by Critical Mass and Anchor Bay, and also features the 2006 Critical Mass restoration of the film in the bonus materials.<ref name=dvd/>\n\n==Accolades==\n'''Saturn Award-Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy & Horror Films'''\n* 1976: Nominated, Best Horror Film{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n'''Canadian Film Awards'''\n* 1975: Won, Best Sound Editing in a Feature \u2013 Kenneth Heeley-Ray<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Cinema Canada]]|issue=18\u201324|year=1975|p=25|title=Canadian Film Awards|publisher=Cinema Canada Magazine Foundation}}</ref>\n* 1975: Won, Best Performance by a Lead Actress \u2013 [[Margot Kidder]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Guide to the Cinema(s) of Canada|editor=Rist, Peter|p=112|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2001|isbn=978-0-313-29931-5}}</ref>\n* 1975: Nominee, [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Motion Picture|Best Feature Film]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Best-film showdown: 11 vie for all-Canadian honours |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18703453/|newspaper=[[Ottawa Journal]]|date=October 3, 1975|page=39|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = March 28, 2018 }} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n'''Edgar Allan Poe Awards'''\n* 1976: Nominated, Best Motion Picture \u2013 A. Roy Moore<ref>{{cite book|title=The Christmas Encyclopedia|edition=3rd|p=43|author=Crump, William D.|year=2013|publisher=McFarland|isbn= 978-1-476-60573-9}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n''Black Christmas'' eventually gained a [[Cult film|cult following]], and is notable for being one of the earliest [[slasher film]]s. It went on to inspire other slasher films, the biggest one of all being [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' (which was apparently inspired by Clark suggesting what a ''Black Christmas'' sequel would be like).<ref>{{cite web|last=Squires|first=John|title=How 'Halloween' Was Basically an Unofficial 'Black Christmas' Sequel|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3413469/halloween-basically-unofficial-black-christmas-sequel|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=November 11, 2016|accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref><ref name=onscreen>{{cite episode|people=Orchard, Tristan (dir.); Clark, Bob; Kidder, Margot; Dullea, Keir|display-authors=etal|series=On Screen!|publisher=Canadian Television Fund|title= Black Christmas|airdate=July 22, 2005|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1074369/}}</ref>{{sfn|Muir|2011|p=315}}\n\n''Black Christmas'' has been included in multiple lists in various media outlets as one of the greatest horror films ever made. The film ranked No. 87 on ''[[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s ''[[The 100 Scariest Movie Moments]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dirks|first=Tim|title=Greatest Scariest Movie Moments and Scenes (B)|url=http://www.filmsite.org/scariestscenes2.html|publisher=AMC Filmsite}}</ref> It was ranked at No. 67 in ''[[IndieWire]]''s ''The 100 Best Horror Movies of All Time'', its entry stating \"The plot sounds formulaic, but ''Black Christmas'' remains timeless thanks to its terrifying and elusive killer, 'Billy,' whose backstory is never revealed, as well as a foreboding ending that doesn't offer much hope for the film's Final Girl\".<ref name=\"100besthorrormovies\">{{cite web |last1=Righetti |first1=Jamie |title=The 100 Best Horror Movies of All Time |url=https://www.indiewire.com/feature/best-horror-movies-all-time-scary-films-1202012183/4/ |website=IndieWire.com |publisher=IndieWire |accessdate=3 December 2019 |page=4 |date=9 October 2019}}</ref> [[Thrillist]]'s Scott Weinberg, in his article ''The 75 Best Horror Movies of All Time'', ranked the film at No. 48.<ref name=\"weinberg19\">{{cite web |last1=Weinberg |first1=Scott |title=Best Horror Movies of All Time, Ranked: Scariest Movies Ever Made - Thrillist |url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-horror-movies-ever |website=Thrillist.com |publisher=Thrillist |accessdate=3 December 2019 |date=22 October 2019}}</ref> Paul Schrodt of ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' placed the film at No. 23 in his list of the ''50 Best Horror Films of All Time''.<ref name=\"esquirelist\">{{cite web |last1=Schrodt |first1=Paul |title=50 Best Horror Movies of All Time - Scariest Horror Films Ever Made |url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/g3383/best-horror-movies-of-all-time/ |website=Esquire.com |publisher=Esquire |accessdate=3 December 2019 |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> In 2017, ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' magazine named ''Black Christmas'' the 2nd-best slasher film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pop-culture/best-slasher-movies-of-all-time/black-christmas|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|title=The Best Slasher Films of All Time|date=October 23, 2017|last=Barone|first=Matt|access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref> The following year, ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' listed it the 3rd-best slasher film of all time,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/08/the-50-best-slasher-movies-of-all-time.html|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|title=The Best Slasher Movies of All Time|date=August 8, 2018|last=Vorel|first=Jim|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712181827/https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2018/08/the-50-best-slasher-movies-of-all-time.html|archive-date=July 12, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref> while also placing the character Jess Bradford at #1 in their list of \"20 Best 'Final Girls' in Horror Movie History\".<ref name=\"finalgirllist16\">{{cite web |last1=Vorel |first1=Jim |title=The 20 Best \"Final Girls\" in Horror Movie History |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/movies/final-girls/the-20-best-final-girls-in-horror-movie-history/ |website=PasteMagazine.com |publisher=Paste Magazine |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=October 4, 2016}}</ref>  Film critic Tim Dirks of the film-review website [[Filmsite.org]] added the film to his list of films featuring the \"Greatest Film Plot Twists, Film Spoilers and Surprise Endings\", based on the film's major [[plot twist]]s- the revelation that the real killer was hidden inside the unsearched attic, and Jess' implied murder.<ref name=\"filmsite\">{{cite web |last1=Dirks |first1=Tim |title=Greatest Movie Plot Twists, Spoilers and Surprise Endings |url=https://www.filmsite.org/greattwists5.html |website=Filmsite.org |publisher=[[AMC (TV channel)|American Movie Classics Company, Inc.]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOlivia Hussey told [[Bravo (U.S. TV network)|Bravo]] during an interview about their ''100 Scariest Movie Moments'' series, that when she met [[Steve Martin]] for the first time, he told her she starred in one of his favorite movies of all time. Hussey initially thought he was referring to ''[[Romeo and Juliet (1968 film)|Romeo and Juliet]]'', but was surprised when Martin said it was ''Black Christmas'' and that he had seen the film 27 times.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stitzel|first=Kelly|title=Horror Movie Marathon: Part The Last|url=http://popdose.com/horror-movie-marathon-part-the-last/|publisher=Popdose|date=October 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Related works==\n===Novelization===\nA novelization of the film written by Lee Hays was published in 1976 by Popular Library.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hays, Lee|title=Black Christmas|year=1976|publisher=Popular Library|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8568273-black-christmas}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/black-christmas-review-first-slasher-film-genre|title=The Low-Budget Canadian Film That Inspired 'Halloween' and Launched an Entire Horror Genre|last=Searles|first=Jourdain|date=2018-10-30|website=Thrillist|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n===Remakes===\n{{Main|Black Christmas (2006 film)|Black Christmas (2019 film)}}\n''Black Christmas'' has been remade on two separate occasions, with the films differing significantly from the original.\n\nThe first remake was directed by [[Glen Morgan]] and was released on December 25, 2006. It is loosely based on the original film, containing more graphic content and a focus into the past of Billy. [[Andrea Martin]] was the only original cast member to appear in the film, and [[Bob Clark]] served as an executive producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/markets-festivals/bob-clark-67-director-1117962526/|title=Bob Clark, 67, director|last=Garrett|first=Diane|work=Variety|publisher=Penske Media Corporation|date=April 4, 2007|accessdate=November 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 13, 2019, a new remake was announced by [[Blumhouse Productions]]. Directed and written by [[Sophia Takal]], co-written by April Wolfe and produced by [[Jason Blum]]. Principal photography began on June 24 and wrapped on July 31, 2019, in [[Dunedin]], New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BzEbM8tp8Al/|title=Day 1! #blackchristmas|last=Hendricks|first=Adam|via=[[Instagram]]|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B0j_TQfJE2Q/|title=Day 27! #blackchristmas|last=Hendricks|first=Adam|via=[[Instagram]]|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B0lC_vVJbxM/|title=THAT\u2019S A WRAP!! #blackchristmas|last=Hendricks|first=Adam|via=[[Instagram]]|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=August 8, 2019}}</ref> Starring [[Imogen Poots]] and [[Cary Elwes]], the film was released on December 13, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/blumhouse-black-christmas-remake-sophia-takal-imogen-poots/|title=Blumhouse to Remake \u2018Black Christmas\u2019 with Director Sophia Takal|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190614002737/https://collider.com/blumhouse-black-christmas-remake-sophia-takal-imogen-poots/|archive-date=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring home invasions]]\n* [[Holiday horror]]\n* [[List of films set around Christmas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite book|last=Muir|first=John Kenneth|author-link=John Kenneth Muir|title=Horror Films of the 1970s|year=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-786-49156-8|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0071222|title=Black Christmas}}\n* {{Allmovie title|5838|Black Christmas}}\n* {{mojo title|blackchristmas74|Black Christmas}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=1002484-black_christmas|title=Black Christmas}}\n* {{tcmdb title|68859|Black Christmas}}\n\n{{Black Christmas}}\n{{Bob Clark}}\n{{Warner Christmas films}}\n\n[[Category:1970s Christmas films]]\n[[Category:1970s slasher films]]\n[[Category:1974 films]]\n[[Category:1974 horror films]]\n[[Category:Black Christmas (film series)]]\n[[Category:Canadian Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian independent films]]\n[[Category:Canadian serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Canadian slasher films]]\n[[Category:Christmas horror films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Exploitation films]]\n[[Category:Films about fraternities and sororities]]\n[[Category:Films about fratricide and sororicide]]\n[[Category:Films based on urban legends]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bob Clark]]\n[[Category:Films set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Home invasions in film]]\n[[Category:Pregnancy films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHorror(link changed toHorror film) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Christmas_(1974_film)"}
